[White "Introduction and Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

{ Hello chess fans, a warm welcome to my course: Attacking Repertoire for Club Players with Black! This is my second course for Chessable, and in combination with my first course, Attacking Repertoire for Club Players: 1.e4, it provides a complete opening repertoire. I am very excited to share the variations with you. We will play in the same attacking style as the White course and challenge our opponent with countless nasty tricks.   For part of the course, I collaborated with co-author FM Mees van Osch. We went on a working holiday together, and for two weeks, we were working almost non-stop on the course in the sunny Gran Canaria. Our trip started with an incredible surprise when we met Carlsen at the airport, who was flying back home after winning the Tata Steel Chess Tournament in the Netherlands. We were so passionate about the work that Mees mentioned late Friday evening: “It would be so hard not to continue working this weekend”. As you understand, we didn’t see much from the sunny island, which I don’t regret at all. Most of the work was done during the working holiday and after our trip, I finished the rest of the course!     A little background about me: my name is Midas Ratsma from the Netherlands. I am a FIDE-Master, a full-time chess coach, and an author of Chessable courses. Also, I am the founder of the website www. thechesscommunity.com, a place where chess players can connect for lessons from professional and passionate coaches and friendly training games. Thank you very much for buying the course.  In my work, I take into account that the popularity of opening variations is totally different at the 1600-level compared to the high-amateur and top-level chess. This inspired me to discover the best way to get winning positions against 1600-level players in the opening. Based on a database I used with more than 50-million rapid and classical games at the 1600-level, the course should give you an excellent chance to get a winning position against a 1600-level player. I look forward to sharing the countless tricks that a typical 1600-rated opponent will fall for.     Studying 1600-level games, I discovered that the games almost never reach 15 moves of theory. So as not to occupy your memory, we will never go beyond 15 moves of theory. The density of each chapter is based on how frequently it is played at the 1600-level. We start with the variations you will face most starting with 1.e4 and then 1.d4. Also, less popular variations like 1.b3, 1.b4, 1.e3, 1.g3, 1.f4, 1.Nf3, and 1.c4 will be covered!     The video explanations sometimes go deeper than the trainable lines. This is intentional and designed not to overburden your memory with variations. The course is to the point and teaches you the 187 variations you must know to win with Black. This knowledge should be sufficient for everyone under the 1800-FIDE rating, and it’s much more important to refresh and repeat the lines than to go deeper into the theory. And don’t forget that understanding all the ideas is much more essential than memorizing the moves, so try to watch the videos or read everything thoroughly for the best learning experience.      “Chess is 99% tactics” is a famous quote by Richard Teichmann. Although 99% is a bit too much, tactics are indeed incredibly important, and tactical mistakes decide most games. Therefore, the course has tactics chapters that test your tactical knowledge directly after the theoretical chapters. In the Themed Based Tactics chapter, in the end, you can do a final tactic test repeating all tactics combinations in the course.  Also, there are 20 model games to make you more familiar with the typical middle game plans after the openings! You can study the tactics and model games directly after each theoretical chapter.    I did my utter best to explain all the moves and variations as clearly as possible. Surely it could be that you have questions, and you can place all your comments on Chessable by clicking on the moves of variations you have a question about. Every Monday, I will take the time to reply to all comments and update the course if necessary.      A few study tips. The Quickerstarter guide will teach you the 20 most essential variations you must know to start playing the openings. Repeat the Quickerstarter guide until you master it before moving on with the following chapters. I recommend studying the chapters in chronological order and finishing the tactics and model games before going to the next theoretical chapter. The most convenient way to use the move trainer is to click on the learn next button, and after each variation, you can click on next or the space bar to study the next one. You can use the Browse Repertoire Tree option to check the move recommendation quickly after a tournament or online game. I recommend the Chessable default settings to study the variations.     With these two courses, all the openings are covered! My goal as an author is to continue with courses on tactics, strategy, and endgames in a reach 1800 series that provides you with all the knowledge to reach 1800 FIDE rating. I will keep you posted about future courses in the forums. Let’s not wait any longer and jump into the variations. I can’t wait to share the sneaky tricks and attacking variations. }
