{ 1.e4  is by far the most popular move at the 1600-level. We don't want to give White the opportunity to also play d4 next move and get a strong center and the flexibility to develop the bishops and queen. We will counter with  1...e5  .   As a rule of thumb, we play 1...e5 against any first move from White except in cases where White plays  1.d4  or  1.Nf3  since in those cases it blunders a pawn. Instead, we put our other pawn in the center with  1...d5  . }
1. e4
{ White puts the pawn in the center and opens the diagonals for the bishop and queen. }
1... e5
{ We copy White and also put our pawn in the center. We prevent White from playing  2.d4  getting a strong pawn center since we can capture with  2...exd4  and after  3.Qxd4  Nc6  develops the knight with tempo. }
2. Nf3 { Developing and attacking the e5-pawn. } 2... Nc6
{ Developing and defending the e5-pawn. } 3. Bc4
{ The Italian opening! White develops the bishop and prepares to castle, this is the most popular opening at the 1600-level. }
3... Nf6
{ We develop and attack the e4-pawn. This is called the Two Knights Defense. }
4. d3 Be7
{ We prefer ...Be7 in this line, avoiding the annoying pin with Bg5 that often happens if we move the bishop somewhere else. }
5. O-O O-O 6. c3
{ When White plays c3 or a3, the plan to play ...d6 and ...Na5, to trap White's light-squared bishop, doesn't work anymore. So after  6...d6  7.h3  Na5  8.Bb5  c6  9.Ba4  b5  10.Bc2  , the light-squared bishop escapes to the c2-square. That's why we change our plan and play ...d5 instead!   The same idea applies after  6.a3  , and we reply with  6...d5  .   If White plays  6.h3  , we go  6...d6  , threatening ...Na5 again to trap White's light-squared bishop. }
6... d5
{ Let's open the diagonal for the bishops. After  7.exd5  Nxd5  8.Re1  Bg4  is strong, pinning the knight. Study more about this variation here. }
