{ 1.e4  is by far the most popular move at the 1600-level. We don't want to give White the opportunity to also play d4 next move and get a strong center and the flexibility to develop the bishops and queen. We will counter with  1...e5  .   As a rule of thumb, we play 1...e5 against any first move from White except in cases where White plays  1.d4  or  1.Nf3  since in those cases it blunders a pawn. Instead, we put our other pawn in the center with  1...d5  . }
1. e4
{ White puts the pawn in the center and opens the diagonals for the bishop and queen. }
1... e5
{ We copy White and also put our pawn in the center. We prevent White from playing  2.d4  getting a strong pawn center since we can capture with  2...exd4  and after  3.Qxd4  Nc6  develops the knight with tempo. }
2. Nf3 { Developing and attacking the e5-pawn. } 2... Nc6
{ Developing and defending the e5-pawn. } 3. Bc4
{ The Italian opening! White develops the bishop and prepares to castle, this is the most popular opening at the 1600-level. }
3... Nf6
{ We develop and attack the e4-pawn. This is called the Two Knights Defense. }
4. Ng5
{ This attacking move is the most popular move at the 1600-level! We will make sure this risky approach from White backfires. }
4... d5
{ It's essential to block the bishop's diagonal to f7 and counter-attack in the center. }
5. exd5 b5
{ A brilliant move, chasing the bishop away to regain control in the center. We shouldn't play  5...Nxd5  because then White has the powerful  6.Nxf7  Kxf7  7.Qf3+  , attacking the king and increasing pressure on the knight on d5. }
6. Bxb5
{ By far the most played move at the 1600-level! White's best move is  6.Bf1  when we continue with  6...Nd4  7.c3  Nxd5  8.cxd4  Qxg5  9.Bxb5+  Kd8  These fighting variations are covered from here. Also, after  6.Bb3  , we will reply with  6...Nd4  getting our knight into a powerful position. Study more about that here. }
6... Qxd5
{ Recapturing the pawn and attacking the bishop as well as the g2-pawn. } 7.
Bxc6+ Qxc6 { We are still threatening to capture on g2. } 8. O-O Bb7
{ Threatening mate! White is already under massive pressure. The most played move at the 1600-level is  9.f3  when after  9...Bc5+  10.Kh1  h6!  11.Nh3  g5  Black has a devastating attack. This variation is covered here.   After the second most popular move at the 1600-level  9.Nf3  Black also reaches a winning position with  9...O-O-O  covered here. }
