{ 1.e4  is by far the most popular move at the 1600-level. We don't want to give White the opportunity to also play d4 next move and get a strong center and the flexibility to develop the bishops and queen. We will counter with  1...e5  .   As a rule of thumb, we play 1...e5 against any first move from White except in cases where White plays  1.d4  or  1.Nf3  since in those cases it blunders a pawn. Instead, we put our other pawn in the center with  1...d5  . }
1. e4
{ White puts the pawn in the center and opens the diagonals for the bishop and queen. }
1... e5 { 1.e4 was a good move from White, let's copy them } 2. Nf3
{ White develops and attacks the e5-pawn. } 2... Nc6
{ Developing and defending the e5-pawn. } 3. Bb5
{ The Ruy Lopez, also known as The Spanish. } 3... a6
{ The Morphy Defence is the most popular response to the Ruy Lopez. We are forcing White to decide what to do with the light-squared bishop. }
4. Ba4 Nf6
{ We don't rush to attack the bishop another time with  4...b5  since after White's light-squared bishop can put pressure on our center after  5.Bb3  Nf6  6.O-O  Nxe4?  7.Re1  Nc5  8.Bd5  White pins the knight and will regain the e5-pawn with a significant advantage.   Also after  4...b5  5.Bb3  Nf6  6.O-O  Nxe4?  7.Re1  d5  8.Nc3  Nxc3  9.dxc3  White is doing well and puts lots of pressure on our center. }
5. O-O
{ The most popular move. White doesn't defend the e4-pawn, so we capture it. When White plays  5.d3  or  5.Nc3  instead, they threaten to capture the knight with the bishop and subsequently win the e5-pawn. We will prevent that with  5...b5  . After  6.Bb3  we can continue with  6...Be7  , and castle. }
5... Nxe4
{ This variation is called the Open Spanish. We capture the pawn, but our goal is not to gain material. We are fine giving back the pawn to White in exchange for development. }
6. Re1
{ The most popular move at the 1600-level, whereas on top level  6.d4  is the most popular. }
6... Nc5
{ We will manage to trade White's strong light-squared bishop once again. Also, we can play ...Be7 and ...O-O with a very comfortable position. These variations are covered from here. }
