{ 1.e4  is by far the most popular move at the 1600-level. We don't want to give White the opportunity to also play d4 next move and get a strong center and the flexibility to develop the bishops and queen. We will counter with  1...e5  .   As a rule of thumb, we play 1...e5 against any first move from White except in cases where White plays  1.d4  or  1.Nf3  since in those cases it blunders a pawn. Instead, we put our other pawn in the center with  1...d5  . }
1. e4
{ White puts the pawn in the center and opens the diagonals for the bishop and queen. }
1... e5
{ We copy White and also put our pawn in the center. We prevent White from playing  2.d4  getting a strong pawn center since we can capture with  2...exd4  and after  3.Qxd4  Nc6  develops the knight with tempo. }
2. Nf3 { Developing and attacking the e5-pawn. } 2... Nc6
{ Developing and defending the e5-pawn. } 3. d4
{ The Scotch opening. White immediately puts pressure on the e5-pawn. We should capture the d4-pawn to get rid of the pressure. }
3... exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5
{ Attacking the knight!  4...Nxd4  would be a mistake since, after  5.Qxd4  , White's queen is great in the center attacking the g7-pawn, which prevents our dark-squared bishop from developing. }
5. Nxc6 Qf6
{ We are playing directly for the mate! After  6.Qf3  , we are only willing to trade queens on our terms and play  6...dxc6  when after  7.Qxf6  Nxf6  we can develop the knight and attack the e4-pawn. These variations are covered here.   Also, after  6.Qe2  or  6.f3  we will always recapture with  6...dxc6  getting ready to develop our bishop and planning to get a rook to the open d-file with ...Rd8 or ...O-O-O.   6.Be3  is a frequent mistake at the 1600-level when we destroy White's pawn structure with  6...Bxe3  . }
