{ 1.e4  is by far the most popular move at the 1600-level. We don't want to give White the opportunity to also play d4 next move and get a strong center and the flexibility to develop the bishops and queen. We will counter with  1...e5  .   As a rule of thumb, we play 1...e5 against any first move from White except in cases where White plays  1.d4  or  1.Nf3  since in those cases it blunders a pawn. Instead, we put our other pawn in the center with  1...d5  . }
1. e4
{ White puts the pawn in the center and opens the diagonals for the bishop and queen. }
1... e5
{ We copy White and also put our pawn in the center. We prevent White from playing  2.d4  getting a strong pawn center since we can capture with  2...exd4  and after  3.Qxd4  Nc6  develops the knight with tempo. }
2. f4
{ The King's Gambit. White plays risky chess by opening up diagonals toward the king. Other sidelines are the bishop's opening with  2.Bc4  when after  2...Nf6  3.d3  Nc6  we will most likely transpose to the Italian opening. The bishop's opening is covered here.   The Vienna Gambit happens after  2.Nc3  Nf6  3.f4  when we counter in the center with  3...d5  .  This is covered here.   Also, the four-knights opening could occur after  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.Nc3  Nf6  , which is covered here. }
2... exf4
{ Opening up the kingside and immediately threatening a deadly check with ...Qh4+! }
3. Nf3 { Preventing ...Qh4+. } 3... d5
{ As usual, we quickly play ...d5! By playing both ...e5 and ...d5 early, we ensure that we can develop all our pieces. }
4. exd5 Nf6
{ We want to take back the d5-pawn with our knight and immediately protect the f4-pawn. After  5.c4  c6  6.dxc6  Nxc6  Black can develop lightning-fast with ...Bg4 and ...Bb4 this is covered here. }
