[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction and Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Albin Countergambit with 5.e3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ The second most popular move at the 1600-level. White puts the pawn in the center and wants to play e4 next move to occupy the whole center. }
1... d5 { We copy White and prevent them from playing e4. } 2. c4
{ The Queens Gambit has started, and White challenges our center pawn. White is not giving up the pawn for free since after  2...dxc4  , our pawn is vulnerable, and White has two center pawns and could play  3.e4  grabbing a big center and threatening Bxc4 to recapture our pawn. We won't do that. It's time to shock your opponent and get into a fighting position. }
2... e5
{ Surely your opponent didn't see that one coming. We go for the Albin Countergambit, a surprising and attacking opening. We immediately open the lines for all pieces to activate them with lightning-fast speed.   Objectively speaking, this opening is a bit dubious. However, practically it's fantastic to surprise our opponent on the second move and enter a position where they can fall for countless tricks. Studying the database with over 50 million 1600-level games, I can ensure you that it gives excellent chances to reach winning positions. Carlsen recently played it in a blitz game and World Championship challenger Nepomniachtchi played it in five blitz games. The pressure is on White now, and they have to immediately deal with the tension in the center. }
3. dxe5
{ The critical try for White against the Albin Countergambit. We push the d-pawn forward, gaining space and making it more difficult for White to develop the light-squared bishop. We shouldn't play  3...dxc4  because White plays  4.Qxd8+  Kxd8  . We lost our right to castle, and the c4-pawn is weak.   After  3.e3  exd4  4.exd4  Nc6  , Black has a comfortable position putting pressure on White's center. The variations are covered here.   After  3.cxd5  Qxd5  4.Nc3  Qxd4  Black reaches a better endgame covered here.   After  3.Nc3  , we go for a pawn sacrifice with  3...exd4  4.Qxd4  Nc6  5.Qxd5  Be6  6.Qxd8+  Rxd8  when we threaten the deadly ...Nb4-Nc2+ to win a rook. At the 1600-level White struggles against this idea, and we likely reach a winning position immediately. This is covered here. }
3... d4
{ We aim to regain the e5-pawn. We are better when we succeed in this due to a better pawn structure. At this point, both our bishops can develop freely, whereas White's light-squared bishop is still stuck. }
4. Nf3
{ After  4.e3?  we will reply with  4...Bb4+  when after  5.Bd2  we strike with  5...dxe3  , and White cannot capture the bishop since we will in brilliant fashion in the variation here. }
4... Nc6
{ White has many replies here. Our standard plan is to win the pawn back with ...Ne7-Ng6-Ngxe5. And a rule of thumb is that we play ...Bb4+ after White plays e3. The variations  5.e3  Bb4+  and  5.Bg5  f6  are the expectations where we won't go for this plan. }
5. e3
{ This is by far the most played at 1600-level, and Black has a perfect position now. }
5... Bb4+
{ We follow the rule of thumb and play this powerful developing move, after which we can weaken White's pawn structure. }
6. Bd2 dxe3 { Forcing White to recapture with the pawn. } 7. fxe3
{ 7.Bxb4  is a mistake White frequently makes when we reply with intermediate move  7...exf2+  and get a big advantage after  8.Ke2  Qxd1+  9.Kxd1  Nxb4  . }
7... Nh6
{ Developing, preparing to castle, and getting ready to jump with ...Ng4 and attack the weak e-pawns. These variations have been covered from here  . }
