1. d4 d5 2. Bf4
{ The London system is known as one of the most solid openings for White, let's immediately increase the pressure. }
2... c5 { Attacking the center. } 3. e3
{ Strengthening the center. White can also play  3.c3  with the same idea. Then we continue in the same fashion: developing our knights with ...Nc6 and ...Nf6. We transpose to this variation after  3...Nc6  4.e3  Nf6  .   When White captures the pawn with  3.dxc5  , we reply with  3...Nc6  threatening ...e5 to take over the center. }
3... Nc6 { We start by developing our knights to their natural squares. } 4. c3
{ The London is known for this V-shaped pawn structure. It's meant to be solid, but we'll see that Black has strong attacking ideas against this setup.  4.Bb5  is harmless since we can continue with  4...Nf6  and Black benefits from the trade with  5.Bxc6+  bxc6  . We can play ...Ba6 later to prevent White from casting. }
4... Nf6
{ This position can also be reached by @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2pp4/3P1B2/8/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.c3  Nf6  4.e3  Nc6  . }
5. Nf3
{ After  5.Bd3  , we will also go for  5...Qb6  attacking the b2-pawn. This has been covered here.   If White plays  5.Nd2  , we shouldn't go for ...Qb6 anymore since we can no longer trap the rook after ...Qxb2. So we will reply  5...Bf5  also getting a strong bishop.   This position also could have been reached from the @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp2pppp/2n5/2pp4/3P1B2/4P3/PPP2PPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Nf3  Nf6  5.c3  move order. }
5... Qb6
{ Attacking the b2-pawn. We don't give White time to get into their comfort zone and play all the standard London moves. After the most played move at the 1600-level  6.Qc2  , we will play  6...Bf5!  developing with tempo, and White can't capture the bishop, which is covered here.   When White plays  6.Qb3  , we will go for  6...c4  when a trade of queens with  7.Qxb6  axb6  activates our rook on the open a-file. This is covered here. }
