[Black "Reversed Jobava London with 3.c4 "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ The second most popular move at the 1600-level. White puts the pawn in the center and wants to play e4 next move to occupy the whole center. }
1... d5 { We copy White and prevent them from playing e4. } 2. Nf3
{ White develops the knight and delays c4. This same position can be reached by the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Nf3  d5  2.d4  move order. }
2... Bf5
{ An aggressive move that Carlsen and Nepomniachtchi both tried several times. Since we are playing the Albin Countergambit, we must have a reply here where White cannot transpose into the standard d4-mainlines. The idea behind the ...Bf5 move is that we want to develop the light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain before we play ...e6. }
3. c4
{ The critical try for White. This is only the third most popular move at the 1600-level.  3.Bf4  Looks similar to London but should be approached differently, as explained in the variation here. We will play  3...e6  preparing ...Bd6 to neutralize White's bishop.   3.e3  e6  4.c4  Nc6  5.Nc3  can transpose to this variation covered here. }
3... e6
{ We support the pawn in the center and open the diagonal to develop our other bishop. We shouldn't be greedy and play  3...dxc4  since after  4.Nc3  Nf6  5.e3  e6  6.Bxc4  White will regain the pawn and has a strategical advantage as White has one more center pawn. Center pawns on e and d-files are typically stronger than pawns outside the center. }
4. Nc3
{ White develops the knight and increases the pressure on the center.  4.e3  Nf6  would transpose to the previous variation. }
4... Nc6
{ The reversed Jobava London started. The Jobava London is typically a set-up where White plays with d4, Nc3, and Bf4, and we copied the same set-up with Black. It's time to put White under pressure immediately. We are planning to play ...Nb4-Nc2+ forking the king and rook. }
5. Bf4
{ White defends against  5...Nb4  since they can play  6.Rc1  . That's why we continue developing instead.   5.e3  is the most popular move at the 1600-level when we happily play  5...Nb4  .  Black gets a fantastic position which is covered here. }
5... Nf6
{ We plan to continue development with ...Bb4 and ...O-O. This variation has been covered here. }
