[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction and Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "King's Indian Attack "]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3
{ We have discussed everything after  1.d4  and will now look at  1.Nf3  and  1.c4  .  These openings could often transpose into each other. Since we play the Albin Countergambit after  1.d4  , I carefully selected variations against  1.Nf3  and  1.c4  where White cannot transpose back in other  1.d4  mainlines, which we don't know. With  1.Nf3  , White goes for a slower opening and prevents us from playing ...e5. }
1... d5
{ As a rule of thumb, we will always play ...e5 or ...d5 on the first move. We prefer to play ...e5, but only when White plays 1.d4 or 1.Nf3 and prevents that we will go 1...d5 }
2. g3
{ White aims for a solid set-up to fianchetto the bishop and castle quickly. We go for a reversed London set-up, bringing the bishop out before closing the pawn chain with ...e6.  2.d4  is more popular, and this transposes to the reserved Jobava London, which we have covered here.   White sometimes played  2.e4?  playing for an opening trick. After  2...dxe4  3.Ng5  , I recommend  3...e5  giving back the pawn after  4.Nxe4  Nc6  Black has better development and position.   After  2.c4  , we will play  2...d4  grabbing space and after  3.e3  Nc6  , we develop and support our d4-pawn. }
2... Bf5
{ We ensure that we don't lock in our light-squared bishop behind the pawn chain. }
3. Bg2
{ White continues with their plan and gets ready to castle. Now that our light-squared bishop is out, we can play ...e6 supporting the center and opening the diagonal for our dark-squared bishop. }
3... e6 4. O-O
{ White is quick with castling; however, they are not putting pressure on us yet. We would also like to develop our pieces on the kingside and castle. }
4... Nf6
{ In this variation, we have to be a little bit patient with Black. We love to attack in every variation, but what White did so far is very solid, and they didn't give us any targets to attack yet. All I can teach you here is to make sure you also develop your pieces to proper squares so that you are ready for a fair battle later in the game. We develop the bishop and get ready to castle. You can find the variation here. }
