1. c4 e5
{ Let's play the reversed Sicilian. We used the rule of thumb that we play  1...e5  against every more from White except 1.d4 or 1.Nf3 when 1...e5 would blunder the pawn. Even after 1.f4, we go 1...e5 and sacrifice the pawn. }
2. Nc3
{ Those of you who also have the White course know that we fight the Sicilian with the Alapin. In this position, it would not work if we go a reversed Alapin since after  2...c6  , White plays  3.Nf3  attacking our e5-pawn when we don't have our signature knight-hunting move  3...e4  attacking that knight since White captures with  4.Nxe4  .   We keep in mind that we want to go for the Alapin idea later. And first, develop the knight.  2.g3  Nf6  3.Bg2  c6  4.Nc3  d5  transposes to this variation. }
2... Nf6 { Developing and also getting ready to castle. } 3. g3
{ The most popular move at the 1600-level. And this is good news for us since now we can go for the delayed reversed Alapin. After  3.Nf3  Nc6  , we plan to play ...Bb4, castle, and then start hunting the knight with ...e4. This has been covered here. }
3... c6
{ Let's go for the reversed delayed Alapin and get the same ideas as in the White course. The plan is to play ...d5 getting a strong pawn center and get ready to hunt White's knights. }
4. Bg2 d5
{ We go for our Alapin plan and get our two strong pawns in the center. Also, we are ready for ...d4 hunting White's knight. In 80% of the 1600-level games, White trades with  5.cxd5  cxd5  , which is a mistake from White. We have a fantastic pawn center and can continue hunting Black's knight with ...d4,  which is covered here. }
