1. e4 e5 { 1.e4 was a good move from White, let's copy them. } 2. Nf3
{ Developing and attacking the e5-pawn. } 2... Nc6
{ Developing and defending the e5-pawn. } 3. Bc4 Nf6
{ We develop and attack the e4-pawn. This is called the Two Knights Defense. }
4. d3 Be7
{ We prefer the ...Be7 in this line, avoiding the annoying pin with Bg5 that often happens if we move the bishop somewhere else. }
5. Nc3 O-O 6. Be3 { 6.O-O  d6  transposes to a position that is covered here. }
6... d6
{ We protect the e5-pawn, which means that our c6-knight is free to move. This creates a strategic threat to play ...Na5 next and exchange White's strong light-squared bishop for the knight. }
7. Qd2 Na5
{ This move has multiple goals! We can trade the knight for the light-squared bishop and free up the c6-square to play ...c6. We only have to capture the bishop when White creates an escape square with a3 or a4. In other cases, it is more powerful to start attacking with ...c6, ...d5 or ...b5 straightaway. }
8. O-O-O { The most popular move at the 1600-level and a big mistake. } 8... c6
{ White's light-squared bishop cannot avoid the trade yet, so we can postpone it and wait for the right moment. We threaten to play ...d5 with tempo, followed by ...d4 forking the knight and the other bishop, winning a piece! }
