{ Developing and attacking the e5-pawn. } 2... Nc6
{ Developing and defending the e5-pawn. } 3. Bc4 Nf6
{ We develop and attack the e4-pawn. This is called the Two Knights Defense. }
4. d3 Be7
{ We prefer the ...Be7 in this line, avoiding the annoying pin with Bg5 that often happens if we move the bishop somewhere else. }
5. O-O O-O 6. Nc3
{ After  6.Re1  we will also play  6...d6  threatening ...Na5. When White creates an escape square for the bishop with  7.a4  we will still play  7...Na5  8.Ba2  and play  8...c5  grabbing more space on the queenside.   In variation  6.Re1  d6  7.a4  the idea with  7...Bg4  is less strong since after  8.c3  Black cannot put any more pressure on the pinned knight with ...Qf6 or ...Nd4. Our bishop isn't doing much when we cannot further attack the pinned knight. }
6... d6 { Now the e5-pawn is defended, so ...Na5 is a threat! } 7. h3
{ Almost all players at the 1600-level don't prevent their bishop from being trapped. }
7... Na5
{ Trapping White's strong light-squared bishop. This is the important strategic idea we are playing for, which also occurs sometimes in the Ruy Lopez. We would love to exchange White's strong bishop. As long White doesn't create an escape square, we don't have to capture the bishop immediately. Also, we are ready to start attacking with ...c6 followed by ...d5 or ...b5. }
8. Bb3 c6
{ We will wait with capturing the White's light-squared bishop until it tries to escape. After  9.Be3  we will play  9...d5  taking control of the center and threatening a fork with ...d4. }
