1. e4 e5 { 1.e4 was a good move from White, let's copy them. } 2. Nf3
{ Developing and attacking the e5-pawn. } 2... Nc6
{ Developing and defending the e5-pawn. } 3. Bc4 Nf6
{ We develop and attack the e4-pawn. This is called the Two Knights Defense. }
4. Ng5
{ This attacking move is the most popular move at the 1600-level! We will make sure that this risky approach from White backfires. }
4... d5
{ It's essential to block the bishop's diagonal to f7 and counter-attack in the center. }
5. exd5 b5
{ A brilliant move, chasing the bishop away to regain control in the center. We shouldn't play  5...Nxd5  because then White has among others the powerful  6.Nxf7  Kxf7  7.Qf3+  , attacking the king and increasing pressure on the knight on d5. }
6. dxc6 bxc4
{ We are happy to trade our knight for White's strong light-squared bishop. }
7. O-O { It's time to hunt White's misplaced knight on g5! } 7... h6 8. Nf3 e4
{ Hunting the knight again! } 9. Ne5 Bd6
{ We keep on hunting White's knight and kindly invite them to capture the c4-pawn. }
10. Nxc4
{ And now it's time to punish White for moving the knight five times. } 10...
Bxh2+ { A brilliant bishop sacrifice, also known as the Greek gift. } 11. Kxh2
Ng4+
{ When the king goes back with  12.Kg1  we play  12...Qh4  threatening checkmate with ...Qh2#.   Also  12.Kh3  is not a good idea for White when  12...Nxf2+  wins the queen with a discovered check.   That's why White's best defensive try is  12.Kg3  , we destroy him with  12...h5  followed by ...h4+. This chases the king to the h3-square when we have the same discovered check motif to win the queen. }
