[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1b) Italian Tactics and Model games "]
[Black "So, Wesley vs. Mamedyarov, Shakhriyar"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. Nc3 Nxe4 5. Nxe4 d5 6. Bd3 dxe4 7. Bxe4 Bd6
{ We studied these moves here. } 8. O-O O-O 9. Re1 Bg4 10. h3 Bh5
{ It's important not to play  10...Bxf3  11.Qxf3  since the bishop is much stronger than the knight. We are pinning the knight. }
11. g4 { White unpins the knight but weakens the king. } 11... Bg6 12. d3 f5
{ Mamedyarov immediately opens the f-file for the rook to attack. } 13. gxf5
{ This trade favors Black as the f-file opens up. } 13... Bxf5 14. Bxf5 Rxf5
15. Be3 Bc5
{ This doesn't blunder a piece, as Mamedyarov will win back the piece with a double attack. It would have been a bit better to play  15...Qe7  followed by ...Raf8 putting pressure on the knight. }
16. Bxc5 Qd5 { Double attack. } 17. Nd2 Qxc5 { Black threatens ...Qxf2+. } 18.
Ne4 { Attacking the queen and defending the f2-pawn. } 18... Qe7 19. c3 Raf8
20. Qb3+ Kh8
{ Mamedyarov doesn't want to play  21...Qf7  and allow the trade of queens as Black's king is safer than White's king. }
21. Qxb7 Nd8 22. Qb4
{ So wants to trade queens, and clearly, Mamedyarov doesn't want this. White's king is in danger, and keeping the queens on the board is essential to keep the attack going. So should have played  22.Qxa7  instead to grab the pawn and defend the f2-pawn one more time. }
22... Qh4 23. Ng3
{ Offering a trade of queens and threatening to capture the rook. } 23... Rf4
{ Safeguarding the rook and avoiding the trade of queens! } 24. Re4 Ne6
{ Planning to play ...Ng5 with a deadly attack. The knight and the queen are powerful in the attack together. }
25. Rxf4 exf4 { Also including the pawn into the attack. } 26. Re1 a5
{ Mamedyarov cannot play  26...fxg3  as the pawn is pinned and White plays  27.Qxh4  . Therefore Mamedyarov wants to chase the queen away from the b-file. }
27. Qe4 Ng5 { Bringing the knight into the attack with a tempo. } 28. Qe7 Kg8
{ A calm move to defend the rook. White's position is falling apart as Black threatens to capture the knight with ...fxg3 and to fork the king and rook with ...Nf3+. }
29. Re4 Nxh3+ { Winning a pawn with a check. } 30. Kg2 Ng5
{ A cool move to return to the g5-square. Black threatens ...Qh3+ followed by ...Nf3# mate. So resigned the game. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1b) Italian Tactics and Model games "]
[Black "Cros, Marc vs. Lopez, Ricardo"]
[Result "*"]

{ Ricardo  (Fenelzina)  is on top of the leaderboard for my White course Attacking repertoire for Club Player: 1.e4. Also, Ricardo was a beta tester for this course and is a very ambitious student who gives lots of useful feedback. This was one of the first games in which he tried out an opening from this course. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. d3 Be7 5. O-O O-O 6. Re1 d6
{ We covered everything in the course till here. We had the positional threat of ...Na5 to catch White's strong light-squared bishop. }
7. a4
{ A cunning move. White anticipates our idea and creates an escape square for the bishop. Also, White grabs more space on the queenside. }
7... Bg4
{ Pinning the knight. This move is very logical, but objectively it is not the best. As explained here, we would love to pin the knight when we can further put pressure on the knight with moves like ...Qf6 and ...Nd4! White cannot prevent that by playing  8.c3  , and our bishop isn't doing much anymore.  It would have been stronger to play   @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp1bppp/2np1n2/4p3/P1B1P3/3P1N2/1PP2PPP/RNBQR1K1 b - - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7...Na5  8.Ba2  c5  and grab more space. }
8. h3 { Attacking the bishop. } 8... Bh5 { Keeping the pin. } 9. Be3
{ A mistake. White's bishop is not doing much here, and Black will soon harass the bishop. This position is by no means easy to play for White. Black developed all the pieces and castled.  9.c3  would have been stronger to control the d4-square. }
9... d5
{ This is perfectly timed. After  10.exd5  Nxd5  , we are putting pressure on White's bishop. ...d5 is a typical idea, and we would love to play both ...e5 and ...d5 to open the diagonals for both bishops. }
10. exd5 Nxd5 11. Nbd2 Nxe3
{ Immediately grabbing the bishop pair. As White's bishop couldn't escape, Ricardo could have waited to capture the bishop and first play  11...Kh8  with the idea to play ...f5-f4 and trap the bishop. Therefore White would have to play  12.g4  , and after  12...Bxg4  , White's king is weaker, and Black can still gain the bishop pair. }
12. fxe3 Kh8 { A cunning move unpinning the f7-pawn. } 13. Ne4
{ A dubious move allowing ...f5 with tempo. } 13... f5 14. Ng3 Bg6
{ This move is a bit slow. Stronger would have been  14...Bxf3  15.Qxf3  Bd6  Black now threatens to win a piece with ...e4. }
15. e4 Bc5+ { Activating the bishop with a check. } 16. Kh2 f4
{ Kicking the knight away allows Black to play ...Bh5 again pinning the knight. }
17. Nf5 Qf6
{ 17...Bh5  pinning the knight would have been stronger. Black also prepares ...g6 and the knight on f7 is almost trapped. }
18. Qe2 Bh5 { Pinning the knight. } 19. c3
{ Preventing a ...Nd4 jump. Also, White wants to play b4 grabbing space on the queenside. }
19... a5 { Preventing b4. } 20. Rad1 Bxf3
{ By trading the knight, Black wants to play ...g6 next, harassing the other knight and not allowing the knight to retreat to h4. }
21. Qxf3 g6 { White's knight is in trouble. } 22. Nh6 Qh4 23. d4
{ 23.Nf7+  would have been stronger but after  23...Kg7  Ricardo will also win material as he can exchange the rook for the knight and bishop. }
23... exd4 24. Nf7+ Rxf7
{ A beautiful tactic. It looks like Black gives up an exchange; however, Black still has a cunning idea when White captures the rook. }
25. Bxf7 Ne5 { Forking the queen and the bishop. } 26. Qf1 Qg3+
{ Black first improves the queen before capturing the bishop. } 27. Kh1 Nxf7
{ Black captures the bishop and reaches a winning position. It would have been ever stronger to play  27...Ng4  threatening mate when after  28.hxg4?  Qh4#  finishes the game.   Therefore White will play  27...Ng4  28.Qg1  and now  28...d3  unleashes a discovered attack against the queen, which cannot move because it has to defend against mate. }
28. cxd4 Bb4 29. Re2 Nd6 30. e5 Nf5 31. Qf2 Qb3
{ Black threatens ...Qxd1+ and ...Ng3+. White cannot defend against both, so Black will gain more material. }
32. Rc2 Ne3 { Forking the rooks. } 33. Rdc1 Nxc2 34. Rxc2 Qe3 35. Qh4 Qe1+
{ Trading the queens is a good strategy here to simplify the position. White was threatening the annoying Qf6+. }
36. Qxe1 Bxe1 37. Rxc7 Rd8 38. e6 b6 39. Kg1 Bb4 40. Rd7 Rxd7
{ Black can safely trade the rooks as after  41.exd7  Be7  Black stops the pawn and has a winning endgame. A great game by Ricardo. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1b) Italian Tactics and Model games "]
[Black "andrijasi vs. MrBastK(Bas)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. Ng5 d5 5. exd5 b5 6. Bxb5 Qxd5 7. Bxc6+ Qxc6
8. O-O Bb7 9. Qf3 e4 10. Re1 Be7 { The course covered everything here. } 11.
Qe3 h6
{ An excellent move. The knight on g5 is often misplaced in the opening when White's light-squared bishop is no longer attacking the f7-pawn. }
12. Nh3
{ The knight is misplaced here. Knights are typically very poorly placed at the edge of the board, where they can only jump to a limited amount of squares.  12.Nf3  would have been better when Black cannot play  12...exf3  because of  13.Qxe7  mate. Therefore after  12.Nf3  Black plays  12...O-O  threatening to capture the knight again. }
12... g5
{ Bas restricts the knight even more. It would have been even stronger to play  12...O-O-O  to finish development and place the rook on the semi-open d-file. }
13. Nc3 O-O-O 14. Qxa7
{ White is greedy and gives Black the chance to march the e-pawn forward. }
14... e3 { Threatening ...Qxg2# mate. } 15. f3 exd2
{ Grabbing the pawn and forking the rook and bishop! } 16. Rxe7 d1=Q+ 17. Nxd1
Rxd1+
{ The rook enters the attack with a devasting effect. White was slow with development and will not be happy that their bishop is pinned now. }
18. Kf2 g4 { Blowing open the king's position. } 19. Nf4 gxf3 20. Rxc7+
{ White is desperate and sacrifices the rook to get some counterplay. } 20...
Kxc7 21. Nd3
{ An amazing game so far, Bas could have finished it off with  21...Qxc2  22.Kg3  Qxg2+  23.Kf4  Qg5  mate. }
21... fxg2
{ The first blunder by Bas! This allows White a discovered attack with a check to win the rook. }
22. Bf4+ Kd7 23. Rxd1 Qf3+ 24. Ke1
{ The position is very complicated! The computer says the best move for Black is  24...Ke6  to run safely towards the kingside. White's best reply is  25.Kd5  running safely towards the queenside. }
24... g1=Q+ { Oopssss White can capture the queen  25.Qxg1  . } 25. Kd2 Qfxd1+
{ The quickest mate would be  25...Ne4+  26.Kc1  Qgxd1  mate! } 26. Kc3 Nd5+
27. Kb3
{ Bas won on time! Also, next move, he can play  27...Qxa7  , and he is two queens and a rook ahead. }
