1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. Ng5 d5 5. exd5 b5 6. Bxb5 Qxd5 7. Nc3 Qxg2 8.
Rf1 Bg4 9. f3 Bd7
{ So far, we covered everything here, and Bas has an amazing position and threatens ...Qxg5. }
10. Nge4
{ White threatens to trade the knights on f6 and weaken the pawn structure. }
10... Nd4
{ 10...Nxe4  would have been stronger. Also, capturing another pawn with  10...Qxh2  would be good for Black. }
11. Bxd7+ { White should have played  11.Nxf6+  to weaken the pawn structure. }
11... Nxd7
{ The knight escapes, and White can no longer trade on f6. Also, Black has the deadly attacking plan of ...Be7-Bh4+. }
12. d3
{ White missed that it opens the second rank for the queen towards c2 allowing ...Nxc2+. }
12... Be7
{ The plan with ...Bh4+ is powerful; however, Bas could have already won the queen with  12...Nxc2+  13.Qxc2  Qxc2 }
13. Bd2 Bh4+ 14. Nf2 Nxf3+ { White is getting destroyed. } 15. Ke2 Nd4+ 16. Ke1
Nf6
{ Bringing the other knight into the attack and threatening ...Ng4 attacking the pinned knight one more time. }
17. Ne4 Ng4 18. c3 Nf3+ { Safeguarding the knight and giving a check. } 19. Ke2
f5 { Bas wants to eliminate the defending knight. } 20. Ng3
{ The knight blocks the bishop's diagonal towards f2. } 20... e4
{ Black has a devastating attack but plays a little bit carelessly.  20...O-O  would safeguard the king and activate the rook. Black can then continue attack without having to worry about its own king's safety. }
21. dxe4 fxe4
{ A big blunder  21...O-O  or  21...O-O-O  would have been best to safeguard the king and not allow any counterplay. }
22. Rg1
{ White blunders a checkmate. After  22.Qa4+  Black's king is in trouble. }
22... Qxf2#
{ And Bas won with a mate. Bas reached an excellent position from the opening and played a good game. The key mistake was that he castled too late and allowed White counterplay. }
