{ I would like to show you a model game in the most popular opening at 1600-level. The Italian opening with 4.Ng5! How do we turn the tables when White goes all in for the attack. In this bullet game, I mated the opponent in 17 moves. Of course, we only had 1 minute for the entire game, and it was more challenging to make good moves. Still, this game beautifully illustrates the attacking plan, and it also proves that a strong opponent didn't know how to deal with our recommendation. }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. Ng5 d5 5. exd5 b5 6. Bxb5 Qxd5 7. Bxc6+ Qxc6
8. O-O Bb7 9. f3 Bc5+ 10. Kh1 h6 11. Nh3 g5
{ Everything is covered in the course! Black already has a winning position. And remember that this is the position you can get when White plays 11 times the most played move in a row. }
12. Nf2 O-O-O
{ Finishing development and activating the rook on the open d-file. It would also have been fine to strike with  12...g4  immediately since White cannot capture the pawn as  13.fxg4  leads to  13...Qxg2#  . }
13. d3 g4
{ I continue with the typical attacking idea! The f3-pawn is under a lot of pressure. }
14. Nc3
{ The final mistake from White.  14.Nd2  was necessary to support the f3-pawn. After  14...Rhg8  , I aim all my forces at White's king, and my position is winning. }
14... gxf3 15. gxf3
{ 15.g3  didn't help either as after  15...Bxf2  16.Rxf2  Ng4  attacks the rook, which cannot move away since ...f2+ would lead to mate. }
15... Qxf3+
{ White's king is helpless, and I don't even need the queen to mate. } 16. Qxf3
Bxf3+ 17. Kg1 Rhg8+
{ Black resigned since  18.Bg5  Rxg5#  would finish the game. The power of the bishops and rooks in the attack is incredible. It's fantastic that we don't even need our queen to deliver checkmate, as all our other pieces are also attacking.  This is how you rip apart White's king safety and counter White after the aggressive   @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/4p3/2B1P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 4 4@@EndFEN@@  4.Ng5  attacking move they played here. }
