[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1b) Italian Tactics and Model games "]
[Black "Italian: Chapter Summary "]
[Result "*"]

{ In the chapter summary you can review the most important variations of each chapter! }
1. e4 e5 { 1.e4 was a good move from White, let's copy them. } 2. Nf3
{ Developing and attacking the e5-pawn. } 2... Nc6
{ Developing and defending the e5-pawn. } 3. Bc4 Nf6
{ We develop and attack the e4-pawn. This is called the Two Knights Defense. One key thing to remember is that White's light-squared bishop is powerful in Italian! We will hunt this bishop in every variation. }
4. Ng5
{ This attacking move is the most popular move at the 1600-level! We will make sure this risky approach from White will backfire.   4.Nc3  White falls for a famous trap.  4...Nxe4  We will regain the piece!  5.Nxe4  d5  Forking the bishop and knight and gaining control in the center.  6.Bxd5  The most popular move at the 1600-level, which is a mistake. Again we have managed to trade White's light-squared bishop which was their strongest minor piece.  6...Qxd5  7.Nc3  Qd6  We plan to play ...Bg4, creating a powerful pin on the knight and castling queenside when our rook is immediately strong on the open d-file.  8.O-O  Bg4  Creating a deadly pin on the knight!  9.h3  9...Bh5  We maintain the strong pin on the knight.  10.d3  O-O-O  We plan to play ...f5 and subsequently ...Nd4, putting more pressure on the pinned knight. By playing ...f5 first, we defend against White's defensive idea with g4.   4.d3  Be7  We prefer ...Be7 in this line, avoiding the annoying pin with Bg5.  5.O-O  O-O  6.c3  When White plays c3 or a3, the plan to play ...d6 and ...Na5, to catch White's light-squared bishop, doesn't work anymore. The light-squared bishop escapes to the c2 or a2-square. That's why we change our plan and play ...d5 instead!   6.Nc3  d6  Now the e5-pawn is defended, so ...Na5 is a threat!  7.h3  Almost all players at the 1600-level don't prevent their bishop from being trapped.  7...Na5  We don't have to capture the bishop directly if White doesn't create an escape square. Also, we are ready to start attacking with ...c6 followed by ...d5 or ...b5. Also, in this variation, we managed to trade White's light-squared bishop, their strongest minor piece in the Italian.  6...d5  Let's open the diagonal for the bishops.  7.exd5  Nxd5  8.Re1  Attacks the e5-pawn once again.  8...Bg4  Pinning the knight and developing the last minor piece.  9.h3  9...Bh5  10.g4  White chooses to open up his king's position to win the e5-pawn.  10...Bg6  11.Nxe5  11...Nxe5  12.Rxe5  12...c6  Black is ready to attack the White king, and White hasn't fully developed yet. White will regret being so greedy. We plan to attack with ...Bd6 and ...f5 activating our rook on the f-file. }
4... d5
{ It's essential to block the bishop's diagonal to f7 and counter-attack in the center. }
5. exd5 b5
{ A brilliant move, chasing the bishop away to regain control in the center. We shouldn't play  5...Nxd5  because then White has among others the powerful  6.Nxf7  Kxf7  7.Qf3+  , attacking the king and increasing pressure on the knight on d5. }
6. Bxb5
{ By far the most played move at the 1600-level! White should have retreated with Bf1. If the light-squared bishop moves somewhere else we go ...Nd4! The objectively best move and surprising move from White to retreat the bishop to its starting square is covered here but rarely played at the 1600-level. }
6... Qxd5
{ Recapturing the pawn and attacking the bishop as well as the g2-pawn. } 7.
Bxc6+
{ This is what you will face the most after every other move we have either capture the g2-pawn or the bishop. }
7... Qxc6 { We are still threatening to capture on g2. } 8. O-O Bb7
{ Threatening mate! } 9. f3
{ By far the most popular move at the 1600-level and Black is winning!   9.Nf3  The second most popular move at the 1600-level, and Black is also winning in this line.  9...O-O-O  We have the plan to play ...h5-h4-h3, trading White's g2-pawn. This weakens White's king, increases the pressure on the f3-knight, and activates our rook on the h-file. }
9... Bc5+
{ A deadly check! Black develops with tempo and takes a strong initiative in the game. }
10. Kh1 h6
{ A crucial move. We chase away the knight to the weak h3-square and start a pawn storm to demolish White king's position. White's knight on g5 is vulnerable when their light-squared bishop no longer attacks the f7-pawn. Also, in the variations here and here we start harrassing this knight. If we wouldn't play 10...h6, White has the chance to consolidate with d3-Ne4 and neutralise our powerful bishop and queen on the light-squares. }
11. Nh3 g5
{ Statistically, you are likely to get this position, according to the 1600-level database. This position arises when White plays the most popular move 11 times in a row. Black has a devastating mating attack and a winning position. We plan to castle queenside and play ...g4. Black cannot capture the g4-pawn due to checkmate on g2. Black's pieces are working nicely together and are all looking towards White's king. When our g- and h-pawn march down the board, White's king will be naked and mated soon. The computer already evaluates this position as -7. }
