[White "2a) Ruy Lopez"]
[Black "Ruy Lopez with 4.Bxc6 and 5.Nxe5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 { 1.e4 was a good move from White, let's copy them } 2. Nf3
{ White develops and attacks the e5-pawn. } 2... Nc6
{ Developing and defending the e5-pawn. } 3. Bb5
{ The Ruy Lopez, also known as The Spanish. } 3... a6
{ The Morphy Defence is the most popular response to the Ruy Lopez. We are forcing White to decide what to do with the light-squared bishop. }
4. Bxc6
{ The Exchange Variation. We are happy to trade our knight for the bishop! }
4... dxc6
{ By capturing with the d-pawn, we open lines for our light-squared bishop and queen. }
5. Nxe5 { The most popular move at the 1600-level and a significant mistake. }
5... Qe7
{ A sneaky move attacking the knight. In the database, by far the most popular move is  5...Qd4  when after  6.Nf3  Qxe4+  Black regains the pawn and has a better position.   After  5...Qe7  White's best reply is  6.Nf3  when after  6...Qxe4+  we reach that same position.   With  5...Qe7  we want to provoke White into making another mistake. }
6. d4
{ In 74% of the games at the 1600-level, White played 6. d4, however, this is a mistake. }
6... f6 { We attack the pinned knight! } 7. Qh5+
{ The most popular move at the 1600-level, which seems very strong. However, it's a big blunder because Black wins a piece! }
7... g6 { Attacking the queen! } 8. Nxg6
{ Our h-pawn is pinned, so we can't take the knight yet. } 8... Qxe4+
{ Double attack on the king and knight! } 9. Be3 Qxg6
{ Black is a piece up, thus winning! } *

