1. e4 e5 { 1.e4 was a good move from White, let's copy them } 2. Nf3
{ White develops and attacks the e5-pawn. } 2... Nc6
{ Developing and defending the e5-pawn. } 3. Bb5
{ The Ruy Lopez, also known as The Spanish. } 3... a6
{ The Morphy Defence is the most popular response to the Ruy Lopez. We are forcing White to decide what to do with the light-squared bishop. }
4. Bxc6
{ The Exchange Variation. We are happy to trade our knight for the bishop! }
4... dxc6
{ By capturing with the d-pawn, we open lines for our light-squared bishop and queen. }
5. Nc3
{ After  5.d4  exd4  6.Qxd4  Qxd4  7.Nxd4  Bd7  we are ready to castle queenside.   If White plays  5.d4  exd4  6.Nxd4  we can break White right to castle after  6...c5  7.Nf3  Qxd1+  . }
5... Bc5
{ White defends the e4-pawn in another way. In this particular line, we don't need to defend our e5-pawn. We make sure that White will experience an unpleasant attack after taking on e5. Again we delay 5...Bg4 because when White isn't castled yet we can't reply to 6.h3 with 6...Bg4  . }
6. O-O Bg4 { Creating a strong pin on the knight! } 7. h3
{ White chases our bishop away and hopes for a trade to resolve the pressure on the pinned knight. }
