[White "2a) Ruy Lopez"]
[Black "Ruy Lopez with 4.Ba4 and 5.d3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 { 1.e4 was a good move from White, let's copy them } 2. Nf3
{ White develops and attacks the e5-pawn. } 2... Nc6
{ Developing and defending the e5-pawn. } 3. Bb5
{ The Ruy Lopez, also known as The Spanish. } 3... a6
{ The Morphy Defence is the most popular response to the Ruy Lopez. We are forcing White to decide what to do with the light-squared bishop. }
4. Ba4 Nf6
{ We don't rush to attack the bishop another time with  4...b5  since White's light-squared bishop can put pressure on our center after  5.Bb3  Nf6  6.O-O  Nxe4?  7.Re1  Nc5  8.Bd5  White pins the knight and will regain the e5-pawn with a significant advantage.   Also after  4...b5  5.Bb3  Nf6  6.O-O  Nxe4?  7.Re1  d5  8.Nc3  Nxc3  9.dxc3  White is doing well and puts lots of pressure on our center. }
5. d3
{ By defending the e4-pawn, White threatens to trade on c6 and win the e5-pawn. That's why we chase away the bishop. }
5... b5 6. Bb3 Be7
{ When White chooses this d3-setup, we prefer to place our bishop on e7 to avoid an annoying pin on the knight after  6...Bc5  7.Bg5  .  We saw this idea as well in the Italian opening. }
7. O-O d6 { Threatening ...Na5 to trade the strong light-squared bishop. } 8.
Nc3 Na5
{ We manage to trade White's powerful bishop for the knight and have a strategical advantage. We plan to castle kingside and develop the light-squared bishop. }
*

