[White "2a) Ruy Lopez"]
[Black "Ruy Lopez mainline with 6.Re1 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 { 1.e4 was a good move from White, let's copy them } 2. Nf3
{ White develops and attacks the e5-pawn. } 2... Nc6
{ Developing and defending the e5-pawn. } 3. Bb5
{ The Ruy Lopez, also known as The Spanish. } 3... a6
{ The Morphy Defence is the most popular response to the Ruy Lopez. We are forcing White to decide what to do with the light-squared bishop. }
4. Ba4 Nf6
{ We don't rush to attack the bishop another time with  4...b5  since White's light-squared bishop can put pressure on our center after  5.Bb3  Nf6  6.O-O  Nxe4?  7.Re1  Nc5  8.Bd5  White pins the knight and will regain the e5-pawn with a significant advantage.   Also after  4...b5  5.Bb3  Nf6  6.O-O  Nxe4?  7.Re1  d5  8.Nc3  Nxc3  9.dxc3  White is doing well and puts lots of pressure on our center. }
5. O-O
{ The most popular move. White doesn't defend the e4-pawn, so we capture it. }
5... Nxe4
{ This variation is called the Open Spanish. We capture the pawn, but our goal is not to gain material. We are fine giving back the pawn to White in exchange for development. }
6. Re1
{ The most popular move at 1600-level, whereas on top level  6.d4  is the most popular. }
6... Nc5
{ We will manage to trade White's strong light-squared bishop once again. } 7.
Bxc6 dxc6
{ By capturing with the d-pawn, we open the lines for the bishop and queen. }
8. Nxe5
{ White threatens a discovered attack with Nxc6. We develop and defend against this idea. }
8... Be7 { Black is ready to castle kingside. } 9. d4 Ne6
{ We return the pressure to White and attack the d4-pawn. } 10. c3 O-O 11. Nd2
{ The most popular move at 1600-level, but this is a bit slow. After  11.Be3  , we again play  11...f6  , kicking White's knight away from the central e5-square. After  12.Nf3  or other knight retreats, we play  12...Re8  , bringing the rook to the center, and Black has a slight advantage. }
11... c5 { We attack the center by putting pressure on d4. } 12. Ndf3 cxd4
{ We trade our doubled c-pawn for White's central pawn. } 13. cxd4 Qd5
{ Our queen is placed beautifully. White cannot easily chase the queen away. We plan to play ...b6 and ...Bb7 to prepare a battery towards White's king and create threats with ...Qg2# mate. }
