[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2a) Ruy Lopez"]
[Black "Ruy Lopez mainline with 6.d4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 { 1.e4 was a good move from White, let's copy them } 2. Nf3
{ White develops and attacks the e5-pawn. } 2... Nc6
{ Developing and defending the e5-pawn. } 3. Bb5
{ The Ruy Lopez, also known as The Spanish. } 3... a6
{ The Morphy Defence is the most popular response to the Ruy Lopez. We are forcing White to decide what to do with the light-squared bishop. }
4. Ba4 Nf6
{ We don't rush to attack the bishop another time with  4...b5  since White's light-squared bishop can put pressure on our center after  5.Bb3  Nf6  6.O-O  Nxe4?  7.Re1  Nc5  8.Bd5  White pins the knight and will regain the e5-pawn with a significant advantage.   Also after  4...b5  5.Bb3  Nf6  6.O-O  Nxe4?  7.Re1  d5  8.Nc3  Nxc3  9.dxc3  White is doing well and puts lots of pressure on our center. }
5. O-O
{ The most popular move. White doesn't defend the e4-pawn, so we capture it. }
5... Nxe4
{ This variation is called the Open Spanish. We capture the pawn, but our goal is not to gain material. We are fine giving back the pawn to White in exchange for development. }
6. d4
{ White's idea is to open the e-file and start pinning our knight. We should agree to give back our e5-pawn. }
6... b5
{ We shouldn't play the greedy  6...exd4  , since after  7.Re1  d5  8.Nxd4  , White threatens both Nxc6 as well as f3, and we are in trouble. }
7. Bb3 d5
{ Placing a pawn in the center and supporting our knight on  e4!  Again we shouldn't play  7...exd4  since White will play  8.Re1  d5  and now the brilliant  9.Nc3  is very strong for White, when after  9...dxc3  10.Bxd5  , White has many threats and a big advantage. }
8. dxe5
{ White threatens to capture the d5-pawn. After  8.Re1  , we play  8...Be6  9.dxe5  Bc5  , and transpose to a line we will see soon. After  8.Nxe5  , we play similarly with  8...Nxe5  9.dxe5  and defend the d-pawn with  9...Be6  . }
8... Be6 { We develop and defend the d5-pawn. } 9. Nbd2 Nc5
{ We sidestep the tension and leave White with a misplaced knight on d2 that blocks their dark-squared bishop. }
10. c3 d4
{ Forcing the trade of White's strong bishop, without helping White to improve their misplaced knight on d2. We didn't want to capture with  10...Nxb3  , since  11.Nxb3  improves the position of their knight and opens up the diagonal for White's dark-squared bishop. }
11. Bxe6 Nxe6
{ Our knight is placed perfectly on e6! The knight is central, well-defended, and blocking the e5-pawn. }
12. cxd4 Ncxd4
{ Bringing the knight to the center and freeing the c-pawn. We prefer the knight on e6 to stay where it is. }
13. Nxd4 Qxd4
{ This recapture nicely activates the queen and attacks the e5-pawn. The position is balanced. Black is ready to bring the rook to the d-file, develop the bishop and castle kingside. }
