[White "2b) Ruy Lopez Tactics and Model games "]
[Black "Exercise 3: Ruy Lopez"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqk1nr/1pp2ppp/p1p5/2b1N3/4P3/2N5/PPPP1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 0 6"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Do you see a double attack? } 6... Qg5
{ Double attack on the knight and the g2-pawn.  6...Bxf2  7.Kxf2  Qd4+  is also good to win a pawn back.   The other double attack with  6...Qd4  doesn't work since White can defend with  7.Nd3  . }
7. d4
{ 7.Nf3  is a popular move at the 1600-level that loses after  7...Qxg2  threatening mate and capturing the rook. }
7... Qxg2 { Grabbing a pawn and worsening White's king safety. } 8. Rf1
{ The most popular move at the 1600-level and a big blunder. We will add another attacker to the rook! White should play  8.Qf3  when after  8...Qxf3  9.Nxf3  Bb4  pinning the knight, the position is balanced. Which bishop is best to move? }
8... Bh3 { Threatens ...Qxf1+, which wins the rook and is a devasting attack. }
9. Qd3 { Do we have to collect the rook already? } 9... Bxd4
{ A lovely move! There was no need to play  9...Qxf1  immediately, which is worse than our text move, but is still winning. White's rook on f1 is trapped anyway, and with the next move we will play ...Qxf1. }
