[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2b) Ruy Lopez Tactics and Model games "]
[Black "Exercise 7: Ruy Lopez"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2q1rk1/2p2ppp/p1n5/1pb1P1N1/4p3/1QP5/PP3PPP/R1B2RK1 b - - 0 13"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ The knight on g5 looks like a juicy target. But right now it's still defended by the bishop. What to do about that? }
13... e3
{ We interfere the defense of White's dark-squared bishop on the knight and are threatening ...Qxg5 and ...exf2+. Black has a winning position. }
14. Nf3 exf2+ { We win the pawn with a check and have a fantastic position. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2b) Ruy Lopez Tactics and Model games "]
[Black "Vescovi, Giovanni P vs. Kazhgaleyev, Murtas"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. O-O Bg4 6. h3 h5 7. d3 Qf6 8.
Nbd2 Ne7 9. Re1 Ng6 { Everything is covered in the course till here. } 10. hxg4
{ White made the mistake of capturing the bishop. Vescovi understood the idea, though; why not to play   @@StartFEN@@r2qkbnr/1pp2pp1/p1p5/4p2p/4P1b1/5N1P/PPPP1PP1/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.hxg4   as covered here. Vescovi captured the bishop now because he prepared for a defensive idea with the last two moves. After  10...hxg4  11.Nh2  Blocks the h-file, and  11...Qh4?  is no longer so strong since White can defend now with  12.Ndf1! }
10... hxg4 11. Nh2 Bc5
{ A great move threatening ...Qxf2+ as well as ...g3. The attacking idea with  11...Qh4  doesn't work now since White can still defend with  12.Ndf1 }
12. Nxg4
{ Another blunder by White, but either way, Black already had a winning advantage. After  12.Qe2  g3  threatens to capture the knight and ...gxf2+ forking the king and the rook.   The best defense for White was to return the knight with  12.Ndf3  when after  12...gxf3  13.Nxf3  Black has a winning position and can continue attacking along the h-file with the idea of  13...Rh5  followed by ...O-O-O, ...Rdh8 and ...Rh1#. }
12... Qh4
{ The queen comes to the h-file with a devastating effect. The threat is Qh1, mate! There is no way to escape for White. }
13. Kf1
{ White tries to run away from the checks, but it's too late to defend. } 13...
Qh1+ 14. Ke2 Nf4+ 15. Kf3 Qxg2#
{ An amazing game. It is cool that a strong grandmaster Vescovi can get checkmated in 15 minutes against our opening. It was a blitz game, and therefore the time factor could have made a difference. Kazhgaleyev showed this flexibility to play @@StartFEN@@r3kb1r/1pp2pp1/p1p2qn1/4p3/4P1p1/3P4/PPPN1PPN/R1BQR1K1 b kq - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11...Bc5!  It's important not to play like a robot and keep thinking about what is happening on the board.  11...Qh4  , which is usually the typical idea, would result in a lost position after  12.Ndf1  what we saw here. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2b) Ruy Lopez Tactics and Model games "]
[Black "Firouzja, Alireza vs. Vidit, Santosh Gujrathi"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. c3 Bc5 10. Nbd2 O-O 11. Bc2 Nxf2 12. Rxf2 Bxf2+ 13. Kxf2 f6
{ We covered everything in the course till here. } 14. Nf1
{ White opens the diagonal for the light-squared bishop and plans to reroute the knight to e3 at a later stage. }
14... fxe5 { We threaten ...e4 attacking the pinned knight. } 15. Kg1
{ Unpinning and bringing the king to safety. } 15... Bg4
{ Vidit immediately creates another pin on the knight. } 16. Ne3 Be6 17. b3 d4
{ Vidit keeps the attack going and hunts the knight. } 18. Qd3
{ White creates a big threat with Qxh7+ Black cannot play  18...dxe3  since after  19.Qxh7+  Kf7  20.Bxe3  Black's king is in massive trouble, and White has a winning position. }
18... g6 19. cxd4 Nxd4 20. Bb2 Nxf3+
{ This trade weakens White's pawn structure. } 21. gxf3 Rxf3 22. Qe2
{ It would have been best for White to trade queens with  22.Qxd8  as White's king is weakened. }
22... Qg5+ 23. Ng2 Raf8
{ Vidit brings the other rook into the game and threatens ...Rf2. } 24. h4 Qg3
25. Bxe5
{ Strong defense by Firouzja, grabbing the pawn and attacking the queen. }
25... Qg4
{ Black threatens ...Rf1+ when after Qxf1 ...Rxf1+ Rxf1 Black can play ...Qe2 forking the bishops. }
26. Re1 Bd5
{ Bringing the bishop into the attack. Black now threatens ...Rf1+ with a deadly attack. It was better to play  26...Rf1+  when after  27.Qxf1  Rxf1+  28.Kxf1  Qf3+  29.Kg1  Bd5  Black has a powerful attack on the light squares with the queen and bishop. }
27. Bd1
{ Fizouzja's idea is to pin the rook and prevent ...Rf1+ by defending the queen. White should have played  27.Qd2  to attack the bishop. }
27... Qf5
{ It would have been stronger to play  27...Qh3  keeping an eye on the knight and threatening ...Rf2 to start attacking the knight with the queen, rook, and bishop! }
28. Bd4
{ A final mistake from Firouzja! This allows a deadly pin on the knight. }
28... Rg3 29. Bc2 Qd7
{ Firouzja resigned as ...Rxg2+ is coming.  30.Be4  would lose a piece since after  30...Bxe4  31.Qxe4  Rg4  forces White to move the queen and we win the bishop. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2b) Ruy Lopez Tactics and Model games "]
[Black "Ruy Lopez: Chapter Summary "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 { 1.e4 was a good move from White, let's copy them } 2. Nf3
{ White develops and attacks the e5-pawn. } 2... Nc6
{ Developing and defending the e5-pawn. } 3. Bb5
{ The Ruy Lopez, also known as The Spanish. } 3... a6
{ The Morphy Defence is the most popular response to the Ruy Lopez. We are forcing White to decide what to do with the light-squared bishop. }
4. Ba4
{ 4.Bxc6  The Exchange Variation. We are happy to trade our knight for the bishop!  4...dxc6  By capturing with the d-pawn, we open lines for our light-squared bishop and queen.  5.O-O  By castling, White threatens to play Nxe5 on the next move.   5.Nxe5  The most popular move at the 1600-level and a significant mistake.  5...Qe7  Pinning the knight.  6.d4  In 74% of the games at the 1600-level, White played 6.d4, however, this is a mistake.   6.Nf3  Qxe4+  We capture the pawn with a check!  7.Qe2  Qxe2+  Trading queens breaks White's king safety.  8.Kxe2  Bg4   Pinning the knight, Black has a better position. The game could continue with  9.Re1  O-O-O  10.Kf1?  By far the most popular move at the 1600-level and a significant mistake. We play  10...Bxf3  , which weakens White's pawn structure, and Black has a huge advantage.  6...f6  We attack the pinned knight!  7.Qh5+?  The most popular move at the 1600-level, which seems very strong. However, it's a big blunder because Black wins a piece!  7...g6  Attacking the queen!  8.Nxg6  Our h-pawn is pinned, so we can't take the knight yet.  8...Qxe4+!  Double attack on the king and knight!  9.Be3  Qxg6  Black is a piece up, thus winning!  5...Bg4  Pinning the knight.  6.h3  White attacks the bishop and tries to get rid of the pin.  6...h5  A brilliant move, White wanted us to move the bishop, and we are not willing to go along with their plan! We kindly invite White to capture the bishop. If White has already castled, ...h5 is our typical reply to h3 in the Exchange Variation.  7.hxg4  Played in more than 30% of the 1600-level games, and a big mistake.  7...hxg4  8.Nxe5  The most popular move at the 1600-level, and we already have a forced checkmate.  8...Qh4  Threatening ...Qh1# mate.  9.f3  White tries to create an escape square for the king, but we will stop their plan.  9...g3  Taking away White's escape square and ...Qh1# is mate on the next move. }
4... Nf6 5. O-O
{ The most popular move. White doesn't defend the e4-pawn, so we capture it.   5.d3  By defending the e4-pawn, White threatens to trade on c6 and win the e5-pawn. That's why we chase away the bishop.  5...b5  6.Bb3  Be7  When White chooses this d3-setup, we prefer to play ...Be7 to avoid an annoying pin on the knight after Bg5 when we develop the bishop to another square. We saw this idea as well in the Italian opening.  7.O-O  d6  Threatening ...Na5 to trade the strong light-squared bishop.  8.Nc3  Na5  We manage to trade White's powerful bishop for the knight and have a strategic advantage. We plan to castle kingside and develop the light-squared bishop. }
5... Nxe4
{ This variation is called the Open Spanish. We capture the pawn, but our goal is not to gain material. We are fine giving back the pawn to White in exchange for development. }
6. d4
{ White's idea is to open the e-file and start pinning our knight. We should agree to give back our e5-pawn.   6.Re1  The most popular move at the 1600-level, whereas on top level 6.d4 is the most popular.  6...Nc5  We will manage to trade White's strong light-squared bishop ones again.  7.Bxc6  dxc6  By capturing with the d-pawn, we open the lines for the bishop and queen.  8.Nxe5  White threatens a discovered attack with Nxc6+. We develop and defend against this idea.  8...Be7  Black is ready to castle kingside.  9.d4  Ne6  10.c3  O-O  11.Nd2  The most popular move at the 1600-level, but this is a bit slow.  11...c5  We attack the center by putting pressure on d4.  12.Ndf3  cxd4  We trade our doubled c-pawn for White's central pawn.  13.cxd4  Qd5  Our queen is placed beautifully. White cannot easily chase the queen away. We plan to play ...b6 and ...Bb7 to prepare a battery towards White's king and create threats with ...Qg2# mate. }
6... b5
{ We shouldn't play the greedy capture exd4 as it opens up the e-file and our knight on e4 gets pinned. }
7. Bb3 d5
{ Placing a pawn in the center and supporting our knight on e4! Again we shouldn't be greedy and capture the d4-pawn. }
8. dxe5 { White threatens to capture the d5-pawn. } 8... Be6
{ We develop and defend the d5-pawn. } 9. c3
{ 9.Nbd2  Nc5  We sidestep the tension and leave White with a misplaced knight on d2 that blocks their dark-squared bishop.  10.c3  d4  Forcing the trade of White's strong bishop, without helping White to improve their misplaced knight on d2. We didn't want to play ...Nxb3 since after White recaptures with Nxb3 White improves the position of their knight and opens up the diagonal for their dark-squared bishop.  11.Bxe6  Nxe6  Our knight is placed perfectly on e6! The knight is central, well-defended, and blocking the e5-pawn.  12.cxd4  Ncxd4  Bringing the knight to the center and freeing the c-pawn. We prefer the knight on e6 to stay where it is.  13.Nxd4  Qxd4  This recapture nicely activates the queen and attacks the e5-pawn. The position is balanced. Black is ready to bring the rook to the d-file, develop the bishop and castle kingside. }
9... Bc5 { Developing the bishop and putting pressure on the f2-pawn. } 10.
Nbd2 O-O { Finishing development and inviting White to trade knights on e4. }
11. Bc2 Nxf2
{ We will scare our opponent by trading on f2, opening up White's king's position. }
12. Rxf2 Bxf2+
{ We capture the rook with a check! Waiting with the capture with  12...f6  first would also be fine and will most likely transpose to the same position. }
13. Kxf2 f6 { We open the f-file towards Black's king. } 14. exf6 Qxf6
{ We plan to play ...Rae8, ...Ne5 and attack with our queen and rooks on the open e- and f-files. The position is objectively equal with good attacking chances for Black. A sample line that shows Black's ideas is  15.Kg1  Rae8  , bringing the rook to the e-file,  16.Nb3  Ne5  , threatening to capture on f3. White gets mated after taking the knight on  e5  and after  17.Nbd4  , we pin the knight with  17...Bg4  and have a winning position. }
*

