1. e4 e5 { 1.e4 was a good move from White, let's copy them. } 2. Nf3
{ Developing and attacking the e5-pawn. } 2... Nc6
{ Developing and defending the e5-pawn. } 3. d4
{ White immediately puts pressure on the e5-pawn. We should capture the d4-pawn to get rid of the pressure. }
3... exd4 4. Bc4
{ The Scotch gambit. This is my recommendation in the White course, and we have to take it seriously. }
4... Nf6 { Developing and attacking the e4-pawn. } 5. e5
{ White puts pressure on us by attacking the knight. We reply with a counterattack! }
5... d5
{ Attacking the White bishop and also putting another pawn in the center. } 6.
Bb5
{ After  6.exf6  dxc4  , Black is doing well. We traded White's powerful light-squared bishop. }
6... Ne4 { The knight is safe on e4, supported by the d5-pawn. } 7. Nxd4
{ White recaptures the pawn and increases the pressure on our pinned knight. }
7... Bd7 { Developing and supporting the knight. } 8. O-O
{ A mistake from White! Now we have a forcing sequence to develop with tempo. }
8... Nxd4 { We force White to bring out the queen. } 9. Bxd7+ Qxd7 10. Qxd4 Bc5
{ A powerful move, attacking the queen and developing with tempo. After  11.Qd1  Qf5  is strong, attacking both the f2- and e5-pawn and Black has a big advantage. }
