[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3b) Scotch Tactics and Model games "]
[Black "Bromberger, Stefan vs. Predojevic, Borki"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 { 1.e4 was a good move from White, let's copy them. } 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
exd4 4. Nxd4 Qf6
{ In the course we used the other move order and reached the same position as in the game. There it was  4...Bc5  5.Be3  Qf6  6.c3! }
5. Be3 Bc5 6. c3 Nge7 7. Bc4 Ne5 8. Bb3 Qg6 9. O-O d5 10. Bf4
{ A cunning move, White now has the defensive idea to block Black's kingside attack with the bishop, and also they put pressure on the knight. }
10... Bh3 { Threatening ...Qxg2 mate. } 11. Bg3 { Defending against the mate. }
11... h5
{ So far, everything is covered here in the course.   Insisting on the mating attack. After  12.gxh3  h4  Black attacks the pinned bishop and will regain the piece. }
12. Ba4+ c6 { Blocking the check. } 13. exd5 h4
{ Black ignores what White is doing in the center and keeps the attack going. }
14. Bc2
{ White aims to chase away the queen from the g-file. This would allow White to safeguard the pinned dark-squared bishop. }
14... f5
{ Blocking the attack.  14...Qg5  wouldn't have worked as White could attack the queen again with  15.f4  , and the queen cannot stay on the g-file to maintain the pin on the bishop. }
15. Qe2
{ The first mistake in the game. White shouldn't have taken the bishop now with  15.gxh3  when after  15...hxg3  16.fxg3  , a dynamic and balanced middlegame arises. }
15... hxg3 16. fxg3
{ White now attacks the bishop and the knight on e5. Borki knows White will regain the piece either way so he decides to capture the g2-pawn and open the h-file for the rook. }
16... Bxg2 17. Kxg2 Ng4
{ Bringing the knight into the game and threatening ...Rxh2+. White's kingside is collapsing. }
18. Bxf5 Rxh2+ 19. Kf3 Ne5+
{ Black sacrifices the knight for a deadly attack. } 20. Qxe5 Qh5+
{ The king has nowhere safe to go. } 21. g4 Qh3+ 22. Kf4 g5+
{ 23.Kxg5  Qh6  is mate. } 23. Ke4 Re2+
{ Black sacrifices a rook to give mate. } 24. Nxe2 Qe3#
{ Checkmate. Grandmaster Bromberger got smashed off the board. A brilliant game from Grandmaster Borki, who didn't make a mistake in the entire game and showed how to crush the Scotch opening with Black. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3b) Scotch Tactics and Model games "]
[Black "Padmini, Rout vs. Khademalsharieh, Sarasadat"]
[Result "*"]

{ In this model game, I will share a game with my recommendation against the dangerous Scotch Gambit, which I recommend for White. So this is what will happen when students of both my courses play against each other. This game was played a classical game played at the FIDE woman world cup between IM Padmini and IM Khademalsharieh. }
1. e4 e5 { 1.e4 was a good move from White, let's copy them. } 2. Nf3 Nc6 3.
Bc4
{ The Italian opening. In my course for the White pieces, I recommend  3.d4  , but this game transposes to the same position a couple of moves later after  3...exd4  4.Bc4  Nf6  . }
3... Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. e5 d5 6. Bb5 Ne4 7. Nxd4 Bd7 8. Bxc6 bxc6 9. O-O Bc5 10.
f3 Ng5 11. f4 Ne4 12. Be3 Qb8
{ Everything was covered till here in both courses. } 13. b3
{ During the Woman World Cup Padmini and Khademalsharieh played a knock-out match against each other! This was their classical game, and after two games, the score was 1-1. The next day they faced each other again in the rapid playoff. Both players were so happy with their opening play that they repeated exactly the same variation until here. They repeated the exact recommendations from my White course versus my Black course, and none of the players decided to deviate. In the end, Khademalsharieh won the knock-out battle and eventually reached the fourth round of the Woman World Cup. }
13... O-O 14. Qd3
{ White wants to play Nd2 next and exchange Black's powerful knight.  14.Nd2  would also be possible, but we can still sidestep the trade with  14...Nc3  . }
14... f6 { Anticipating a potential attack from White with f5-f6. } 15. Nd2
{ Trading Black's powerful knight. } 15... Nxd2 16. Qxd2 Qb6
{ Increasing pressure on the d4-knight. } 17. c3
{ Creating a strategic threat of b4. If White would have one more move and could play b4 now, the position would be winning since White's bishop is untouchable in the center of the board, as Black cannot attack it with any pawns. Also, the bishop could later move to c5 controlling the f8-square to ensure White would win the battle for the f-file in case it would open up. }
17... a5 { Preventing b4. } 18. a3 { Preparing b4 again } 18... fxe5 19. fxe5
{ White still threatens to play b4! And also, e6 is a big threat. Black has to be very careful. }
19... Bxd4
{ Well-played Black trades the knight now and can kick the bishop after. } 20.
Bxd4 c5
{ Black holds the balance by immediately chasing the bishop.  20...Qa6?  would lose immediately after  21.e6  Bxe6  22.Qg5  Black will get mated. }
21. Bf2 Qc6
{ Supporting the d5-pawn and also unpinning the c5-pawn. The opening was played very well by both the remaining position is balanced. Here it's the most important factor which bishop is stronger. White can try to get the d4-square available for the bishop, and Black can reroute the bishop to the e4-square. These are excellent squares as they keep an eye on the opponent's king. }
22. Qe3 Rfe8 23. Rae1
{ Going for the trade with  23.Qxc5  Qxc5  24.Bxc5  Rxe5  would have been a bit better. White can then place the bishop on d4 and start attacking the g7-pawn. }
23... c4 24. bxc4 Qxc4 25. Bg3 Be6 26. Rf4 Qc6 27. Bf2
{ Rerouting the bishop to the d4-square. } 27... Rab8 28. Qd3 Bf7 29. Bd4 Bg6
{ Black's bishop also maneuvers to the strong e4-square. } 30. Qg3
{ The queen is keeping an eye on the g7-pawn forcing the bishop to stay on  g6  .  30...Be4  would be very dangerous as  31.e6  threatens mate. }
30... Qe6 31. Bc5 Rb5 32. Qf2 { Threatening Rf8 with a mate! } 32... h6
{ Black calmly sidesteps the attack by creating an escape square for the king and has no problems }
33. a4
{ A small strategical mistake. As White has the dark-squared bishop and Black the light-squared bishop, the pawn would be safer on a3. }
33... Rb3 34. Bd4 Reb8
{ 34...Ra3  would have been strong hunting the a4-pawn. } 35. h3 Kh7 36. Qg3
Rb1 37. Rxb1 Rxb1+ 38. Kh2 Ra1 { White cannot hold on to the pawn. } 39. c4
Rxa4 40. cxd5 Qxd5 41. Bb2 Ra2 42. Rf2 Qb5 43. Bc3 Rxf2 44. Qxf2 a4 45. e6 Qc4
46. Qg3 Qxe6 47. Qxc7 { Threatening mate. } 47... Bf7 48. Qg3 Qg6 49. Qxg6+
{ White correctly assessed that the endgame is a draw here. White's strategy is to block the a-pawn with the king and use the bishop to defend the h-and g-pawn. Since Black has the bishop of the opposite color, they can only attack the pawns with their king. }
49... Kxg6 50. Kg3 Bd5 51. Kf2 a3 52. g3 Kf7 53. h4
{ Now, White places both pawns on the dark squares. When the king runs towards the a-pawn, the bishop can always keep on protecting the g3-pawn. }
53... g6 54. Ke3 Ke6 55. Kd2 Kf5 56. Kc2 Ke4 57. Bb4 Kf3 58. Bd6 a2 59. Kb2
{ There is no way for Black to make progress! } 59... h5
{ The game ended in a draw, a fantastic game by both players. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3b) Scotch Tactics and Model games "]
[Black "Scotch: Chapter Summary "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 { 1.e4 was a good move from White, let's copy them. } 2. Nf3
{ Developing and attacking the e5-pawn. } 2... Nc6
{ Developing and defending the e5-pawn. } 3. d4
{ White immediately puts pressure on the e5-pawn. We should capture the d4-pawn to get rid of the pressure. }
3... exd4 4. Nxd4
{ 4.Bc4  The Scotch gambit. This is my recommendation in the White course, and a dangerous opening to face.  4...Nf6  Developing and attacking the e4-pawn.  5.e5  White puts pressure on us attacking the knight. We reply with a counterattack!  5...d5  Attacking the White bishop and also putting another pawn in the center.  6.Bb5  Ne4  The knight is safe on e4, supported by the d5-pawn.  7.Nxd4  White recaptures the pawn and increases the pressure on our pinned knight.  7...Bd7  Developing and supporting the knight.  8.Bxc6  bxc6  9.O-O  Bc5  Developing, putting pressure in the center, and preparing to castle.  10.f3  Ng5  11.f4  Ne4  Returning to the powerful e4-square. This is an outpost for the knight because none of White's pawns can attack the knight.  12.Be3  Qb8  Attacking the b2-pawn The position is equal with chances for both sides. }
4... Bc5
{ Attacking the knight! Trading the knights would be a mistake since White's queen would be powerful in the center attacking the g7-pawn and preventing our dark-squared bishop from developing. }
5. Nxc6
{ 5.Be3  White has a strong threat to capture our knight with Nxc6, which is a discovered attack on the dark-squared bishop on c5.  5...Qf6  Anticipating White's plan. Trading twice on d4 wouldn't be good for Black since White's queen would be powerful in the center and attack the g7-pawn.  6.c3  Nge7  Developing the knight and preparing to castle. Also, we prepare to strike in the center with ...d5.  7.Bc4   7.Be2  d5!  A strong move. Black strikes in the center and opens up the diagonal for the light-squared bishop.  8.exd5?  Nxd5  Threatening to capture White's light-squared bishop and break the pawn structure.  9.O-O  Nxe3  10.fxe3  Qh6  Attacking the e3-pawn. We will castle soon to safeguard our king. Black has a significant advantage.  7...Ne5  We immediately put pressure on the bishop!  8.Bb3  Qg6  Putting pressure on the g2- and e4-pawns.  9.O-O  d5   9...Qxe4  would be too dangerous since  10.Re1  is a strong reply, and our pieces are vulnerable on the e-file.  10.exd5??  The most played move at 1600-level, and Black is winning now!  10...Bh3  Threatening mate in one with ...Qxg2#!  11.g3  Qe4  Threatening ...Qg2# mate from another angle.  12.f3  White's only defensive idea.  12...Qxe3+  Black wins a piece and still has a powerful attack. The computer already gives -10. }
5... Qf6 { We are playing directly for the mate! } 6. Qf3
{ 6.Qe2  dxc6  It's standard to recapture with the d-pawn to open up the light-squared bishop and maintain connected pawns.  7.Nc3  Be6  Developing and preparing to castle queenside. After castling queenside, the rook will immediately be strong on the open d-file.  8.Be3  Ba3  A cunning idea! White cannot capture the bishop since we capture the knight and fork the king and the rook.  9.O-O-O ??  Qxc3  White cannot capture our queen since we are pinning the b2-pawn.  After  10.bxa3  Qxa3+  , Black has a devastating attack and a winning position.   The most-played move for White at the 1600-level and a big mistake.  9.Rb1  doesn't work either since  9...Bxb2  10.Rxb2  Qxc3+  forks the king and the rook. }
6... dxc6
{ We are only willing to trade queens on our terms. When White captures us, we can develop the knight and attack the e4-pawn. }
7. Qxf6
{ This is the most popular move at the 1600-level, which we are happy to face. }
7... Nxf6 8. Nc3
{ The most played move at the 1600-level, which is not so strong. We can immediately attack White's f2-pawn. }
8... Ng4 9. f3 Ne3
{ Threatening ...Nxc2+ with a fork on the king and rook.  9...Nf2?  doesn't work even though it looks strong, since after  10.Na4  Nxh1  11.Nxc5  Black's knight on h1 will be lost soon, and White has a big advantage. }
10. Bxe3 Bxe3
{ The dark-squared bishop annoyingly prevents White from castling. We continue with ...Be6 and castling queenside. Black has a slight advantage. }
*

