1. e4 e5 { 1.e4 was a good move by White, let's copy them. } 2. Nf3
{ White develops and attacks the e5-pawn. } 2... Nc6
{ Developing and defending the e5-pawn. } 3. Nc3
{ White develops the other knight. } 3... Nf6
{ We are going for the four knights game. } 4. Bb5
{ The four knights Ruy Lopez! } 4... Nd4
{ We immediately put pressure on White's strong light-squared bishop. We shouldn't go for  4...a6  since White already protected the e4-pawn and can play  5.Bxc6  bxc6  6.Nxe5  to win a pawn. }
5. Nxd4 exd4 { Attacking the knight! } 6. e5
{ White counter-attacks our knight. } 6... dxc3
{ We have to accept the trade of knights. } 7. exf6 Qxf6
{ We recapture the pawn and activate the queen. The intermediate  7...cxd2+  would help White quickly develop the dark-squared bishop and queen. After  8.Bxd2  Qxf6  9.O-O  White has a big lead in development, and Black is in trouble. }
8. dxc3 Bc5
{ We threaten mate, develop the bishop and prepare to castle. Black has no problems; after  9.Qe2  , we have to agree with a queen trade and play  9...Qe6  .  The trade of queens would open the f-file for our rook! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4a) 1.e4 e5 sidelines"]
[Black "Four Knights Ruy Lopez #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 { 1.e4 was a good move by White, let's copy them. } 2. Nf3
{ White develops and attacks the e5-pawn. } 2... Nc6
{ Developing and defending the e5-pawn. } 3. Nc3
{ White develops the other knight. } 3... Nf6
{ We are going for the four knights game. } 4. Bb5
{ The four knights Ruy Lopez! } 4... Nd4
{ We immediately put pressure on White's strong light-squared bishop. We shouldn't go for  4...a6  since White already protected the e4-pawn and can play  5.Bxc6  bxc6  6.Nxe5  to win a pawn. }
5. Nxd4 exd4 { Attacking the knight! } 6. Ne2
{ A big mistake, which is the most popular move at the 1600-level. } 6... c6
{ Chasing away the light-squared bishop! } 7. Bc4 Nxe4 8. Nxd4 d5
{ We place our pawn in the center and gain a tempo on the bishop! } 9. Bb3
{ 9...Nxf2  doesn't work here because after  10.Qe2  , forking the king and knight,  10...Ne4  doesn't save the knight since White can play  11.d3  attacking and winning the pinned knight. }
9... Qf6
{ Threatening ...Qxf2# mate as well as to capture the knight. White's best reply is to play  10.Nf3  back, and then we play  10...Bg4  creating a strong pin on the knight. Black has a significant advantage. }
*

