[Black "Four Knights Ruy Lopez #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 { 1.e4 was a good move by White, let's copy them. } 2. Nf3
{ White develops and attacks the e5-pawn. } 2... Nc6
{ Developing and defending the e5-pawn. } 3. Nc3
{ White develops the other knight. } 3... Nf6
{ We are going for the four knights game. } 4. Bb5
{ The four knights Ruy Lopez! } 4... Nd4
{ We immediately put pressure on White's strong light-squared bishop. We shouldn't go for  4...a6  since White already protected the e4-pawn and can play  5.Bxc6  bxc6  6.Nxe5  to win a pawn. }
5. Nxd4 exd4 { Attacking the knight! } 6. Ne2
{ A big mistake, which is the most popular move at the 1600-level. } 6... c6
{ Chasing away the light-squared bishop! } 7. Bc4 Nxe4 8. Nxd4 d5
{ We place our pawn in the center and gain a tempo on the bishop! } 9. Bd3
{ The most played move at the 1600-level, now Black has a winning tactic. }
9... Nxf2
{ A temporary sacrifice on f2! Usually, a sacrifice on the f2 or f7-squares is only a good idea when we can immediately gain back our material. }
10. Kxf2
{ After  10.Qe2+  , forking the king and the knight, our knight jumps back  10...Ne4  and after  11.Bxe4  we play  11...Qh4+  12.g3  Qxe4  , winning the bishop. }
10... Qh4+
{ Forking the king and the knight to win back the knight. If White tries to defend the knight with  11.Ke3  things only get worse for White.  11...Bc5  pins and attacks the knight, and after  12.c3  O-O  White's naked king will get mated soon after ...Re8+. }
*

