[White "4a) 1.e4 e5 sidelines"]
[Black "King's Gambit #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 { 1.e4 was a good move by White, let's copy them. } 2. f4
{ The King's Gambit. White plays risky chess by opening up diagonals towards the king. }
2... exf4
{ Opening up the kingside and immediately threatening a deadly check with ...Qh4+! }
3. Nf3
{ Preventing ...Qh4+. After White plays  3.Bc4  allowing  3...Qh4+  4.Kf1  we develop and attack with  4...Nf6  when after  5.Nf3  Qh6  we support the f4-pawn and plan to continue development with ...d6, ...Be7 and ...O-O. }
3... d5
{ As usual, we quickly play ...d5! By playing both ...e5 and ...d5 early, we ensure that we can develop all our pieces. }
4. exd5 Nf6
{ We want to take back the d5-pawn with our knight and immediately protect f4-pawn. }
5. c4
{ White defends the d5-pawn. After  5.Nc3  , we recapture the pawn with  5...Nxd5  .  White often falls for a trap after  6.Nxd5  Qxd5  7.d4  Be7  8.Bxf4  , they miss the trick  8...Qe4+  with a double attack on the king and bishop! }
5... c6 { We want to exchange the d5-pawn and develop our other knight. } 6.
dxc6 Nxc6 7. d4 Bg4
{ Pinning the knight and increasing the pressure on the center. } 8. d5
{ By far the most popular move at the 1600-level and a big mistake. } 8... Bb4+
{ Developing with a check! } 9. Nc3
{ After  9.Bd2  Black's best continuation is  9...Qb6  sacrificing the knight. After  10.dxc6  , we play  10...Ne4  threatening ...Qxf2 mate, subsequently White plays  11.Qe2  , and we reply with  11...O-O-O  . Black has a devasting attack and a winning position. }
9... Ne4 { We increase the pressure on the pinned knight! } 10. dxc6 Qe7
{ A brilliant move! We threaten ...Nxc3+ with a discovered attack to win the queen. Black has a winning position. After  11.Be2  , we continue with  11...Rd8  attacking the queen and after  12.Qc2  Bf5  , we threaten ...Nxc3 with a crushing attack. }
*

