[Black "Exercise 8: 1.e4 e5 Sidelines"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqkb1r/ppp2ppp/2n5/3pP3/4N3/5Q2/PPPP2PP/R1B1KBNR b KQkq - 0 6"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Should we capture the knight or play something else? } 6... Nd4
{ Attacking the queen and the c2-pawn. } 7. Qd3 dxe4
{ We capture the knight and attack the queen. } 8. Qxe4
{ What's the most aggressive developing move? } 8... Bf5
{ We attack the queen, and when she moves, ...Nxc2+ is coming with a fork on the king and rook. }
9. Qxb7 Rb8
{ Cashing in the rook with  9...Nxc2+  10.Kd1  Nxa1  gives an unexpected chance for White with  11.Bb5+  and after  11...Bd7  12.Bxd7+  Kxd7  White can give perpetual check starting with  13.Qd5+  . }
10. Qxa7 { How to win material? } 10... Nxc2+ 11. Kd1 Nxa1
{ Black is a rook up and White's has no dangerous checks. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4b) 1.e4 e5 sidelines Tactics and Model games "]
[Black "AraratKhidiryan vs. FinchEye"]
[Result "*"]

{ In the next game my student Marieke won against the bishop's opening while also showing great knowledge of the typical ideas in the Italian. }
1. e4 e5 2. Bc4 Nf6 3. Nc3 Nxe4 { This has been covered in the course here. }
4. Bxf7+
{ White plays this tempting move to weaken our king. White knows that after  4.Nxe4  d5  Black will win the piece back either way so White decides immediately capture on  f7  . White makes two big concessions though, they give up their light-squared bishop which is the best minor piece in these openings and also they give up the center. Black is already clearly better.   After  4.Qh5  we should play  4...Nd6  defending against the mate and attacking the bishop. }
4... Kxf7 5. Nxe4 d5 { Taking control in the center and attacking the knight. }
6. Ng3 Nc6 7. d3 Bd6
{ Marieke keeps developing and is ready to go for an artificial castle with ...Rf8 and ...Kg8. }
8. Nf3 Rf8 9. Ng5+ Kg8
{ Marieke managed to get the king to safety and still enjoys the strong center. She accomplished an artificial castle as the king and rook are placed as if she castled. }
10. c3 Bc5
{ Attacking the f2-pawn. Stronger was  10...h6  when the knight is trouble after  11.Nf3  Bg4  Black has a deadly pin. }
11. O-O Qf6
{ Again  11...h6  would have been very strong. As we also know from the Italian the knight on g5 is misplaced when White no longer has the light-squared bishop. Like in the variation here we have the idea of pinning the knight after  12.Nf3  Bg4  . }
12. Nf3
{ White should have played  12.c4  aiming to create a strong e4-square for the knight. This is a difficult move to play as it allows  12...Bxf2+  however after  13.Kh1  Black is also not too happy about the bishop being pinned. }
12... Bg4 { A deadly pin on the knight. } 13. Bg5 Bxf3 14. Qxf3 Qxf3
{ Very well spotted.  14...Qxg5  didn't work because after  15.Qxd5+  Kh8  16.Qxc5  White wins back the piece and is a pawn-up in material. }
15. gxf3 Rxf3 { Black is a pawn up and pressuring the f2-pawn. } 16. Rad1 Raf8
{ The last piece is included in the game and supports the attack on f2. } 17.
Nh1
{ Creative defense from White. It must be clear that things are not going well if you have to put your knight in the corner to defend. }
17... R8f5 18. Bh4 g5 19. Bg3 h5 { Threatening ...h4 to trap the bishop. } 20.
h4 gxh4 21. Bxh4 R5f4 22. Bg3 Rg4 { Pinning the bishop and threatening ...h4. }
23. Kh2 h4 { Marieke traps the bishop! The rest of the game is easy. } 24. d4
hxg3+ 25. Nxg3 exd4 26. cxd4 Bxd4 27. b3 Bxf2 28. Nh1 Bg3+ 29. Nxg3 Rgxg3 30.
Rxf3 Rxf3 31. Rxd5 Rf2+ 32. Kg3 Rxa2 33. Rd7 Ra3 34. Rxc7 Rxb3+ 35. Kg4 a5 36.
Kf4 a4 37. Rc8+ Kf7 38. Ra8 a3 39. Ke4 Ke6 40. Ra4 Rb4+ 41. Rxb4 Nxb4
{ Marieke knew the typical ...Nxe4 trick which we saw in the Italian opening and the Bishop's opening and did well to go for an artificial castle with ...Rf8 and ...Kg8. One idea she didn't execute perfectly is the idea knight-hunting idea on g5 with ...h6 and after Nf3 goes for the pin with ...Bg4. Overall a great game. }
