[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4b) 1.e4 e5 sidelines Tactics and Model games "]
[Black "Adhiban, Baskaran vs. Yu, Yangyi"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6
{ We will play  2...Nc6  and transpose after  3.Nc3  Nf6  to the variation in the game. }
3. Nc3 Nc6 { The four knights opening. } 4. Bb5 Nd4 5. Bc4 Bc5 6. Nxe5 Qe7 7.
Nf3 d5 8. Bxd5 Bg4 { We covered everything here. } 9. d3 Nd7
{ A fantastic move with the idea of ...Ne5 putting more pressure on the pinned knight. }
10. Be3
{ White should have played  10.h3  to resolve the pin, and after  10...Bxf3  11.gxf3  White has doubled pawns but also opened the g-file for the rook. }
10... Ne5
{ Yu continues with his plan to harass the pinned knight. White is in big trouble, and even after  11.Bxd4  Bxd4  12.Bb3  Bxc3+  13.bxc3  Black will play  13...Qf6  harassing the pinned knight again.   The computer suggests that White even can play  11.Nxd4!?  giving up the queen when after  11...Bxd1  12.Nf5  Qf6  13.Rxd1  Bxe3  14.Nxe3  White has two knights and two pawns in return for the queen. Black would have a better position there. }
11. Bxf7+
{ A move out of desperation! White struggles a lot with the knight on the knight and tries to deflect the knight. The idea from White is that  11...Qxf7  doesn't work since  12.Nxe5  breaks the pin and attacks the queen. That's why Black should play  11...Nxf7  . }
11... Nxf7 12. Nd5 { Adhiban tries to create some counterplay. } 12... Qd7
{ The queen sidesteps and keeps an eye on the c7-pawn. } 13. c3
{ White forces Black to unpin the knight and resolve the tension. } 13... Nxf3+
14. gxf3 Bxe3 15. Nxe3
{ The final mistake in the game.  15.fxe3  would have been much stronger since after  15...Bh5  White can resolve the pin on the f3-pawn by playing  16.Nf4! }
15... Bh5
{ Yu keeps the pin on the f3-pawn and threatens to add more attackers with ...Ne5 ...Ng5 or ...Qh3. }
16. Ng4 O-O-O { Finishing development and threatening ...Qxd3. } 17. d4 Ng5 18.
h4 Nxf3+ { Eliminating one of the defenders of the knight and winning a pawn. }
19. Qxf3 Rhf8
{ A classy move. Black could also capture the knight with  19...Bxg4  but knows that they will win the knight anyway. Yu first activates the rook. The rest of the game is easy for Yu. }
20. Qe3 Qxg4 21. Kd2 Rf3 22. Rag1 Qe6 23. Qe1 Qxa2 24. Kc2 Be8 25. Rxg7 Ba4+
26. Kc1 Qa1+
{ After  27.Kd2  Qxb2  is mate. A fantastic win by Yu. He showed how devastating the pin on the knight on f3 can be. And even later in the game, Yu was still putting pressure by pinning the f3-pawn. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4b) 1.e4 e5 sidelines Tactics and Model games "]
[Black "Adhiban, Baskaran vs. Carlsen, Magnus"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nxd4 Bb4 6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. Bd3 d5
{ My recommendation is  7...O-O  and the game transposes to that variation after  8.O-O  d5  9.exd5  cxd5  . }
8. exd5 O-O 9. O-O cxd5 10. Bg5 c6 { We learned the theory until here. } 11.
Qf3 Bd6 12. Rae1
{ Carlsen is fine with the trade after  12.Bxf6  Qxf6  13.Qxf6  gxf6  Black has a weakened pawn structure around the king, but White cannot set up an attack as the queens are already traded. Black has the bishop pair, and the position is open, which favors bishops over knights. }
12... Rb8 { Activating the rook and attacking the b2-pawn. } 13. b3 a5 14. h3
h6
{ Carlsen forces the issue and challenges Adhiban to trade off the bishop for the knight. }
15. Bxf6 Qxf6
{ Carlsen has to trade off the queens since after  15...gxf6  Black's king is much weaker than White's king. The side with the safer king benefits most from keeping the queens on the board. }
16. Qxf6 gxf6 17. Ne2 c5 18. Ng3 Rd8 19. Nf5 Bf8
{ Safeguarding the bishop and supporting the h6-pawn. } 20. Ne7+ Bxe7 21. Rxe7
Be6 22. Rd1 c4 23. Be2 a4
{ An amazing move! Carlsen sacrifices the pawn to enter with the rook on the b-file. }
24. bxa4 Bf5
{ 24...Rb2  doesn't work yet as White can reply with  25.Bxc4  as the d-pawn is pinned. }
25. Bf3
{ A big mistake from Adihban instead  25.c3  is better, putting the pawn on a safer square. }
25... d4 { The c-pawn is weak now! And Carlsen has strong d and c-pawns. } 26.
a5 { Adhiban should have defended with  26.Re2  . } 26... Bxc2 27. Rc1
{ 27...Bd3  to defend the c4-pawn would be a big mistake as White can play a6 followed by a7. }
27... Rb1
{ A cunning move! Carlsen forces an exchange of rooks to eliminate the defending rook on the back rank. }
28. Rxb1 Bxb1 29. Rc7 c3 30. Bd1 Ra8
{ It's a matter of technique the c and d-pawn are too strong, and Black can easily stop White's pawns. }
31. Rc5 Bxa2 32. Bc2 Be6 33. Kf1 Rc8 34. Rxc8+ Bxc8 35. Ke2 Ba6+ 36. Kf3 d3
{ A excellent victory by Carlsen, Adhiban played a solid opening with White, and Carlsen still managed to outplay Adhiban. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4b) 1.e4 e5 sidelines Tactics and Model games "]
[Black "Van den Dikkenberg, Erik vs. Todorovic, Bojan"]
[Result "*"]

{ This game was played in Titled Tuesday between FM Van den Dikkenberg and FM Todorovic. }
1. e4 e5 2. f4
{ I recommend  2...exf4  3.Nf3  d5  4.exd5  Nf6  in the game, the same moves were played in a different move order. I believe that the other move order is tricker as White frequently plays  4.e5?  which is a big mistake that we have seen here. }
2... d5 3. Nf3 exf4 4. exd5 Nf6 5. d4 Nxd5 6. c4 Bb4+ 7. Bd2 Ne3 8. Qa4+ Bd7
{ Everything was covered here White cannot play  9.Qxb4  since  9...Nc2+  wins the queen. }
9. Qb3 Bxd2+ 10. Nbxd2 O-O
{ By castling, Black safeguards the king and gets ready to bring the rook to the e-file and attack. Castling is a truly magical move in chess as it's the only move where we are allowed to move two pieces simultaneously. Black has a fantastic position the knight on e3 is powerful and prevents White from castling in both directions. }
11. Kf2
{ White decides to place the king on f2, foreseeing that castling won't be possible. }
11... Nc6 12. d5 Na5
{ The knight goes in the wrong direction. Black would like to include the knight in the attack on the king. Surely  12...Ne7  didn't look so attractive either as it blocks the queen. The computer suggests the cold-blooded  12...Qe7!  when White cannot capture the knight because after  13.dxc6  Ng4+  14.Kg1  Qc5+  15.Qe3  Qxe3  is mate. }
13. Qc3 b6 14. b4 Nb7 15. Bd3 c5
{ The idea is that Black wants to consolidate the knight on the d6-square and not allow White to attack it with c5. }
16. b5 Nd6 { The knight regroups to a better position. } 17. Rhe1 Re8 18. Kg1
{ White mentioned to castle artificially spending many moves. The Black's knight on e3 is still very powerful, taking away important squares from White, blocking the e-file, and attacking the g2-pawn. }
18... Qf6
{ A dubious decision. Black ruins their pawn structure by trading queens. Possibly opening up the g-file gives some attacking ideas with ...Kh8 and ...Rg8. Stronger is  18...Bf5  trading the bishop when after  19.Bxf5  Ndxf5  Black can start to bring the queen into the attack with ...Qd6 and ...Qg6. Also, the queen trade goes against the rule that we shouldn't trade queens when our king is safer. White's king is less safe as Black's knight is targetting the g2-pawn. }
19. Qxf6 gxf6 20. a4
{ White wants to play a5 with the idea to overload Black's rook on e8. After that, White has the possibility to open the a-file trading the on b6, after which Black's rook on e8 should be able to recapture. If White could play a5 and move again, they would play g3 to eliminate the other defender of Black's powerful knight. }
20... a6 { Black counters on the a-file. } 21. a5
{ White tries to make a queen, but this plan doesn't work. } 21... axb5 22.
axb6 bxc4 23. b7 Rxa1 24. Rxa1 cxd3
{ Black correctly assessed that the b7-pawn is not dangerous. } 25. Ra8
{ White threatens to promote, but Black still has time to snatch the pawn. }
25... Nxb7 26. Ra7 Bc8 27. Kf2 c4 { And it's easily winning for Black now. }
28. g3 c3 29. Nb3 d2 30. Ke2 d1=Q+
{ Todorovic got a dominating position out of the opening with the powerful knight. He never let the advantage slip and won an instructive game. Black could have played stronger by keeping the queens on the board. It is a common mistake that too much focus is spent on trading pieces when you are ahead. Although trading pieces with a material advantage can make converting the game into a win easier, you shouldn't allow favorable trades for your opponent and make concessions.  With @@StartFEN@@r2qr1k1/p2b1ppp/1p1n4/1PpP4/2P2p2/2QBnN2/P2N2PP/R3R1K1 b - - 4 18@@EndFEN@@  18...Qf6  here, Black allowed concessions by weakening the pawn structure and by trading queens even though Black's king was safer. In my course, for the White pieces, I also shared an instructive game where Howell converted a position with a material advantage while avoiding multiple trades which would be slightly favorable for the opponent. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4b) 1.e4 e5 sidelines Tactics and Model games "]
[Black "1.e4 e5 sidelines: : Chapter Summary "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 { 1.e4 was a good move by White, let's copy them. } 2. Nc3
{ White develops the knight and defends the e4-pawn.   2.Nf3  White develops and attacks the e5-pawn.  2...Nc6  Developing and defending the e5-pawn.  3.Nc3  White develops the other knight.  3...Nf6  We are going for the four knights game.  4.Bb5  The four knights Ruy Lopez!   4.Bc4  The fourth knights Italian. This is the most popular move at the 1600-level, which is not so strong. We transpose to the Italian opening.  4...Nxe4   We can capture the e4-pawn since after  5.Nxe4  we play  5...d5  forking the knight and the bishop. This variation has already been covered here in the chapter regarding the Italian opening.   4.d4  The four knights Scotch!  4...exd4  5.Nxd4  Bb4  We create a strong pin on the knight and are threatening to win the e4-pawn. We don't play ...Bc5 like in the Scotch since pinning the knight is stronger.  6.Nxc6  bxc6  This time, we recapture with the b-pawn since capturing with the d-pawn allows White to trade queens and we lose our right to castle.  7.Bd3  O-O  Safeguarding the king!  8.O-O  d5  9.exd5  cxd5  10.Bg5  c6  Strengthening the center and Black has no problems to develop the pieces. We can continue with ...Be7 to unpin the knight, followed by ...Rb8 activating the rook and attacking the b2-pawn.  4...Nd4  We immediately put pressure on White's strong light-squared bishop.  5.Nxd4   5.Nxe5  The second most popular move at the 1600-level and a mistake. We attack along the e-file.  5...Qe7  6.Nf3  White's knight on c3 is still defending the e4-pawn.  6...Nxb5  First, we trade White's strong light-squared bishop.  7.Nxb5  Qxe4+  And we capture the pawn with a check!  8.Qe2  Qxe2+  We trade queens and make sure White cannot castle anymore.  9.Kxe2  White is still threatening Nxc7+, so we should defend against this idea.  9...Nd5  Defending the c7-pawn.  10.c4  White chases away our knight!  10...a6  We counter-attack the knight and have a better position.  5...exd4  Attacking the knight!  6.Ne2  A big mistake, which is the most popular move at the 1600-level.   6.e5  White counter-attacks our knight.  6...dxc3  We have to accept the trade  7.exf6  Qxf6  We recapture the pawn and activate the queen. The intermediate capture on with ...cxd2+ would help White quickly develop the dark-squared bishop and queen and we would be in trouble.  8.dxc3  Bc5   We threaten mate, develop the bishop and prepare to castle. Black has no problems; after  9.Qe2  , we have to agree with a queen trade and play  9...Qe6  .  The trade of queens would open the f-file for our rook!  6...c6  Chasing away the light-squared bishop!  7.Bc4  Nxe4  8.Nxd4  d5  We place our pawn in the center and gain a tempo on the bishop!  9.Bd3  The most played move at the 1600-level, now Black has a winning tactic.  9...Nxf2  A temporary sacrifice on f2! Usually, a sacrifice on the f2 or f7 squares is only a good idea when we can immediately gain back our material.  10.Kxf2   After  10.Qe2+  , forking the king and the knight, our knight jumps back  10...Ne4  and after  11.Bxe4  we play  11...Qh4+  12.g3  Qxe4  , winning the bishop.  10...Qh4+   Forking the king and the knight to win back the knight. If White tries to defend the knight with  11.Ke3  things only get worse for White.  11...Bc5  pins and attacks the knight, and after  12.c3  O-O  White's naked king will get mated soon after Black plays ...Re8+.   2.f4  The King's Gambit. White plays risky chess by opening up diagonals toward the king.  2...exf4  Opening up the kingside and immediately threatening a deadly check with ...Qh4+!  3.Nf3  Preventing ...Qh4+  3...d5  As usual, we quickly play ...d5! By playing both ...e5 and ...d5 early, we ensure that we can develop all our pieces.  4.exd5  Nf6  We want to take back the d5-pawn with our knight and immediately protect the f4-pawn.  5.c4   White defends the d5-pawn. After  5.Nc3  , we recapture the pawn with  5...Nxd5  .  White often falls for a trap after  6.d4  Be7  7.Nxd5  Qxd5  8.Bxf4  , they miss the trick  8...Qe4+  with a double attack on the king and bishop!   5.Bc4  Nxd5  We regain the d5-pawn.  6.O-O  Be6  Developing the bishop and supporting the knight!  7.d4  Ne3!   A lovely discovered attack. After  8.Bxe3  , we play  8...Bxc4  , attacking both White's bishop and the rook! Black wins material and has a huge advantage.  5...c6  We want to exchange the d5-pawn and develop our other knight.  6.dxc6  Nxc6  7.d4  Bg4  Pinning the knight and increasing the pressure on the center.  8.d5?  By far the most popular move at the 1600-level and a big mistake.  8...Bb4+  Developing with a check!  9.Nc3   After  9.Bd2  Black's best continuation is  9...Qb6  sacrificing the knight. After  10.dxc6  , we play  10...Ne4  threatening ...Qxf2# mate, subsequently White plays  11.Qe2  and we reply with  11...O-O-O  .  Black has a devasting attack and a winning position.  9...Ne4  We increase the pressure on the pinned knight!  10.dxc6  Qe7   A brillant move! We threaten ...Nxc3+ with a discovered attack to win the queen. Black has a winning position. After  11.Be2  , we continue with  11...Rd8  attacking the queen and after  12.Qc2  Bf5  , we threaten ...Nxc3 with a crushing attack.   2.d4  White plays an early d4! We will capture the pawn.  2...exd4  3.c3  The Danish Gambit. White wants to play attacking chess and sacrifice a pawn.  3...d5  The Capablanca Defense. We open the diagonals to be able to develop all pieces.  4.exd5  White should recapture the pawn.   4.Qxd4  White attacks the d5-pawn.  4...Nf6  Developing and defending the d5-pawn.  5.e5   5.Bg5  White pins the knight.  5...Nbd7  A lovely move, supporting the pinned knight and also threatening ...Bc5 developing with tempo.  6.e5  White attacks the pinned f6-knight. However, tactics won't work out for White.  6...Bc5  Developing with tempo.  7.Qf4  White's only move to keep on defending the e5-pawn.  7...Qe7   Pinning the e5-pawn, so that White can no longer win the knight. Black has a massive lead in development and a huge advantage. After  8.Nf3  , we can play  8...h6  , forcing  9.Bxf6  exf6  . This attacks the e5-pawn another time, thus winning it.  5...Ne4  Black has parried White's initiative and is already starting an attack himself. We threaten ...Bc5 attacking the queen and the f2-pawn.  6.Nf3  The most played move at the 1600-level, losing the important f2-pawn. All other popular moves at the 1600-level are big mistakes as well; they all allow ...Bc5.  6...Bc5  Attacking the queen and increasing the pressure on the f2-pawn. Black has a winning position.  4...Qxd5  5.cxd4  Nc6  Black starts attacking the isolated d4-pawn. We transpose to this variation in the Albin Countergambit.   2.Bc4  This will likely transpose to the Italian.  2...Nf6  We develop the knight and attack the e4-pawn.  3.d3  Nc6  Threatens ...Na5 to trade White's strong light-squared bishop.  4.Bg5   When White plays  4.c3  or  4.a3  to create an escape square for the bishop, we reply with  4...d5  and open the diagonal for our light-squared bishop.  4...Na5  We trade White's strong light-squared bishop for the knight. }
2... Nf6 { We develop the knight and attack the e4-pawn. } 3. f4
{ The Vienna gambit! } 3... d5
{ Striking back in the center and opening the diagonal for all our pieces. We shouldn't play  3...exf4  this time, since White has the strong  4.e5  , attacking our knight. }
4. fxe5 { White grabs the pawn and attacks our knight. } 4... Nxe4
{ We capture the e4-pawn and threaten a dangerous check with ...Qh4+! } 5. Qf3
{ White increases the pressure on the knight! } 5... Nc6
{ A lovely move to trick White. } 6. Nxe4
{ It seems like we are losing a pawn, but we have a strong intermediate move now.   6.Bb5  White pins the knight.  6...Be6  Preparing castling queenside.  7.Nxe4  We happily sacrifice this pawn to get a powerful bishop in the center!  7...dxe4  8.Qxe4  Bd5   White should defend the g2-pawn by  9.Qe2  , but then we give an annoying check with  9...Qh4+  and White can't even play  10.g3  because after  10...Qe4  , we trap the rook! }
6... Nd4 { Attacking the queen and the c2-pawn. } 7. Qd3 dxe4
{ We capture the knight and attack the queen. } 8. Qxe4 Bf5
{ We attack the queen, and when she moves, ...Nxc2+ is coming with a fork on the king and rook. }
