[White "5a) Albin Countergambit"]
[Black "Albin Countergambit 3.e3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ The second most popular move at 1600-level. White puts the pawn in the center and wants to play e4 next move to occupy the whole center. }
1... d5 { We copy White and prevent them from playing e4. } 2. c4
{ The Queens Gambit has started, White challenges our center pawn. White is not giving up the pawn for free since after  2...dxc4  , our pawn is vulnerable, and White has two center pawns and could play  3.e4  grabbing a big center and threatening Bxc4 to recapture our pawn. We won't do that. It's time to shock your opponent and get into a fighting position. }
2... e5
{ Surely your opponent didn't see that one coming. We go for a surprising and attacking opening called the Albin Countergambit. We immediately open the lines for all pieces to activate them with lightning-fast development.   Objectively speaking, this opening is a bit dubious. However, practically it's amazing to surprise our opponent on the second move and enter a position where they can fall for countless tricks. Studying the database with over 50 million 1600-level games, I can ensure you that it gives excellent chances to reach winning positions. Carlsen recently played it in a blitz game and World Championship challenger Nepomniachtci even in five blitz games. The pressure is on White now, and they have to immediately deal with the tension in the center. }
3. e3
{ A passive move from White. They didn't take the challenge to capture our pawn. }
3... exd4
{ We trade the pawns! When White recaptures, their d4-pawn can become vulnerable as no other pawns can protect it. }
4. exd4
{ Let's talk a bit more about the position before making more moves. In the last two moves, the position changed in a way that both e-pawns disappeared from the board. This benefits us more since our dark-squared bishop is not blocked, whereas the c4-pawn blocks White's light-squared bishop. The position is easy to play for Black. The knights can develop to the most natural squares with ...Nf6 and ...Nc6. When White also develops their knights with Nf3 and Nc3, we can create pins with our bishops by playing ...Bg4 and ...Bb4. After  4.Qxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  Nc6  6.Qd1  Bb4  Black has a lead in development and a better position. }
4... Nc6 { We develop and increase the pressure on the d4-pawn. } 5. cxd5 Qxd5
{ We are attacking the d4-pawn. } 6. Nf3
{ Those of you who also studied my White course: Attacking repertoire for Club Players: 1.e4 already know that this position has a potential danger for us. White threatens to play Nc3 chasing the queen and subsequently wants to play d5 hunting our knight. We have to react accurately! }
6... Bg4 { Pinning the knight and putting more pressure on the d4-pawn. } 7.
Nc3 Bxf3
{ It would be a mistake to retreat the queen when White gets a big lead in development.  7...Bb4  to pin the knight would be a sound alternative. I like  7...Bxf3  better as it gives us more attacking chances. }
8. Nxd5
{ White has to capture the queen. After  8.gxf3  Qxd4  Black is a pawn up with a good position. }
8... Bxd1 9. Nxc7+
{ White forks the king and rook. In the end, their knight will be misplaced on a8. }
9... Kd7
{ Getting the king off the back rank allows us the possibility to grab the knight on a8 with the rook one day. }
10. Nxa8 Bh5 { We get our bishop back to safety. } 11. d5
{ White is hunting our knight. Defending the pawn with  11.Be3  would be a mistake since we strike with  11...Bb4+  and White is in big trouble. }
11... Nd4
{ The position is very similar to the position in my White Chessable course coming from the Alapin Barmen's defense. The only difference with the position here is that we don't have the e7-pawn, which benefits us as our dark-squared bishop can develop. Luckily there is no need to worry about the dangerous rook sacrifice I am recommending in my White course with  12.Bf4?  since  12...Bb4+  13.Bd2  Nc2#  is a brilliant mate to finish the game.   White's only good move is, therefore,  12.Bd3  defending against the fork when we play  12...Bg6  to trade the defending bishop and reinforce the threat of the fork with ...Nc2+.   In the White course the variation goes: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.c3  d5  3.exd5  Qxd5  4.d4  cxd4  5.cxd4  Nc6  6.Nf3  Bg4  7.Nc3  Bxf3  8.Nxd5  Bxd1  9.Nc7+  Kd7  10.Nxa8  Bh5  11.d5  Nd4  There, I recommend  12.Bf4  a brilliant rook sacrifice when after  12...Nc2+?  13.Kd2  Nxa1  14.Bb5+  Kd8  15.Bc7+  White has a devastating attack and winning position. }
