{ Surely your opponent didn't see that one coming. We go for a surprising and attacking opening called the Albin Countergambit. We immediately open the lines for all pieces to activate them with lightning-fast development.   Objectively speaking, this opening is a bit dubious. However, practically it's amazing to surprise our opponent on the second move and enter a position where they can fall for countless tricks. Studying the database with over 50 million 1600-level games, I can ensure you that it gives excellent chances to reach winning positions. Carlsen recently played it in a blitz game and World Championship challenger Nepomniachtci even in five blitz games. The pressure is on White now, and they have to immediately deal with the tension in the center. }
3. dxe5
{ The critical try for White against the Albin Countergambit. We push the d-pawn forward, gaining space and making it more difficult for White to develop the light-squared bishop. We shouldn't play  3...dxc4  when White plays  4.Qxd8+  Kxd8  We lost our rights to castle, and the c4-pawn is weak. }
3... d4
{ We aim to regain the e5-pawn. We are better when succeeding in this due to a better pawn structure. At this point, both our bishops can develop freely, whereas White's light-squared bishop is still stuck. }
4. e3
{ The second most popular move at the 1600-level, however, it is a mistake. White wants to get rid of the d4-pawn and develop the light-squared bishop. After e3, we always play ...Bb4+ to break down White's pawn structure and open up the king's position.  4...dxe3  would be a significant mistake since White plays  5.Qxd8+  Kxd8  6.Bxe3  and we are unable to castle and a pawn down.   After  4.e4  Nc6  5.Nf3  we can play  5...Nge7  and go for our typical plan ...Ng6-Ngxe5 to regain the pawn. }
4... Bb4+ 5. Bd2 { White blocks the check. } 5... dxe3
{ We kindly invite White to capture our bishop, setting up a massive trick. }
6. fxe3
{ White has a weakened pawn structure now and many pawn islands. Also, we can go for the attack immediately now that the f2-pawn is gone. }
6... Qh4+ { Forcing White to play g3. } 7. g3 Qe4
{ We attack both the rook and the e3-pawn. } 8. Nf3 Bg4
{ Brining another piece to the attack to pin the knight. We'll later capture the e3-pawn. }
9. Be2 { After  9.Bg2  , we can play  9...Qxe3  as the bishop is pinned. } 9...
Bxd2+
{ We trade our hanging bishop. White cannot play  10.Qxd2  to defend the e3-pawn since  10...Bxf3  wins a piece. }
10. Nbxd2 Qxe3
{ The queen hampers White's development, so Black has a great position. We are ready to play ...Nc6 and castle queenside bringing the rook to the open d-file. }
