{ The second most popular move is a challenging one because we can never play ...Bb4+ anymore. This position can also be reached by @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/8/4P3/2Pp4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.a3  Nc6  5.Nf3  . }
5... Nge7 { We go for the standard plan to play ...Nge7-Ng6-Ngxe5. } 6. b4
{ White plans to play Bb2 and b5 to win the d4-pawn. After  6.Bg5  h6  7.Bh4  g5  8.Bg3  Nf5  Black can march the g and h-pawns forwards attacking White's knight and bishop. }
6... Ng6 { We continue our standard plan and get ready to regain the e5-pawn. }
7. Bb2
{ White develops and wants to win the d4-pawn. White's strategy is that they are fine giving back the e5-pawn if they can win the d4-pawn when White remains a pawn up. }
7... a5
{ A cunning move! Before we capture the e5-pawn, we provoke White to play b5. It gives us the possibility to develop with ...Bc5 later. }
8. b5 { White attacks the knight. } 8... Ncxe5
{ We regain the pawn and also attack the c4-pawn! Please note that we are threatening to capture the pawn without any trouble in this case. In earlier variations here this wasn't possible because of the fork with Qa4+. }
9. Nxe5 Nxe5 10. e3
{ A cunning move from White, increasing the pressure on the pinned d4-pawn and opening the diagonal for the light-squared bishop to protect the c4-pawn.   After  10.Bxd4  we regain the pawn with  10...Nxc4  .   Also after  10.Qxd4  Qxd4  11.Bxd4  Nxc4  , we gain the pawn back, and Black has no troubles. }
10... Bc5
{ A crazy and brilliant move. White's king is still stuck in the middle, and that's why we want to provoke White to capture on d4 with the pawn forking our knight and bishop. }
11. exd4
{ White captures the d4-pawn forking the knight and bishop. Surely, your opponent will think they have a winning position now; however, in reality, White is in big danger. }
11... Bg4
{ Ignoring White's threats and developing the bishop with tempo, attacking the queen. }
12. f3
{ White attacks the other bishop as well, we ignore all the hanging pieces and are going after the king. }
12... Qh4+ { Check! } 13. g3
{ The most logical move from White, also attacking our queen. It seems like we left all the pieces hanging for no reason. Even though White's moves look cunning, they made three significant mistakes in a row, and we reach a winning position. Let's destroy White with a devastating attack. }
13... Nxf3+
{ We continue attacking the king and capture the pawn with a check. } 14. Qxf3
{ White is fine giving up the queen in case they can capture our queen. Luckily we don't have to cooperate with that plan. Also, after  14.Kf2  Qf6  15.dxc5  Nd4+  16.Kg1  Bxd1  Black is a queen up. }
14... Qe7+
{ A brilliant intermediate move, safeguarding our queen and ensuring we will win White's queen on the next move. We shouldn't capture the queen on the previous move with  14...Bxf3?  Because in the end, we lose the bishop:  15.gxh4  Bxh1  16.dxc5  , and we are down in material. }
