[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5b) Albin Countergambit Tactics and Model games "]
[Black "Exercise 2: Albin Countergambit"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b1kbnr/ppp2ppp/2n5/3q4/3P4/5N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 6"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ White is threatening to chase away our queen with Nc3 to subsequently play d5 hunting the knight. How can we react in a precise way? }
6... Bg4 { Pinning the knight and putting more pressure on the d4-pawn. } 7.
Nc3 Bxf3
{ 7...Bb4  to pin the knight would be a sound alternative. I like  7...Bxf3  better as it gives us more attacking chances. }
8. Nxd5
{ White has to capture the queen. After  8.gxf3  Qxd4  Black is a pawn up with a good position. }
8... Bxd1 9. Nxc7+
{ White forks the king and rook. In the end, their knight will be misplaced on a8. }
9... Kd7
{ Getting the king off the back rank allows us the possibility to grab the knight on a8 with the rook one day. }
10. Nxa8 Bh5 { We get our bishop back to safety. } 11. d5
{ White is hunting our knight. Defending with  11.Be3  would be a mistake since we strike with  11...Bb4+  and White is in big trouble. }
11... Nd4
{ The position is very similar to the position in my White Chessable course coming from the Alapin Barmen's defense. Here the game went @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.c3  d5  3.exd5  Qxd5  4.d4  cxd4  5.cxd4  Nc6  6.Nf3  Bg4  7.Nc3  Bxf3  8.Nxd5  Bxd1  9.Nc7+  Kd7  10.Nxa8  Bh5  11.d5  Nd4  There, I recommend  12.Bf4  a brilliant rook sacrifice when after  12...Nc2+?  13.Kd2  Nxa1  14.Bb5+  Kd8  15.Bc7+  White has a devastating attack and winning position.  The only difference with the position here is that we don't have the e7-pawn, which benefits us as our dark-squared bishop can develop. Luckily there is no need to worry about such tricks from White here when White plays   @@StartFEN@@N4bnr/pp1k1ppp/8/3P3b/3n4/8/PP3PPP/R1B1KB1R w KQ - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Bf4?  now than  12...Bb4+  13.Bd2  Nc2#  is a brilliant mate to finish the game. White's only good move is, therefore,   @@StartFEN@@N4bnr/pp1k1ppp/8/3P3b/3n4/8/PP3PPP/R1B1KB1R w KQ - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Bd3  defending against the fork when we play  12...Bg6  to trade the defending bishop and reinforce the threat of the fork on c2. }
