[Black "Exercise 3: Albin Countergambit"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/8/3p4/2PQ4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1B1KBNR b KQkq - 0 4"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ White looks better developed and threatens to win the d5-pawn. How can we go for lightning-fast development and set up a nasty trick? }
4... Nc6
{ Sacrificing the d5-pawn in exchange for lightning-fast development. } 5. Qxd5
Be6 { Developing and attacking the queen. } 6. Qxd8+
{ After  6.Qb5  a6  7.Qxb7  Nd4  we threaten a checkmate and deadly for with  Nc2  . White can defend with  8.Qe4  Nf6  9.Qd3  Bxc4  10.Qd1  with a balanced fighting position. }
6... Rxd8
{ Black has sufficient compensation for the pawn, White has to be extremely careful now. After the three most popular moves at the 1600-level Black, all gets a winning position. I also won several times in online blitz games with this trick against strong opponents. Our deadly plan is ...Nb4-Nc2# threatening mate as well as a fork on the king and the rook. }
7. e3
{ The most popular move at the 1600-level and Black reaches a winning position. Also, the second and third most popular move at the 1600-level allows the same tactic for Black. White's best move would be  7.Bf4  anticipating our idea to defend with the Rc1 next move. We reply with  7...Bxc4  regaining the pawn. }
7... Nb4
{ White can't prevent the fork with ...Nc2+, so Black is winning. After  8.Ke2  Bxc4+  9.Kf3  Bxf1  we win the bishop. }
