[SetUp "1"]

{ How do we go for a devastating attack? } 9... Nb4
{ Threatening ...Nc2+ forking the king and rook. We don't have to be scared that White can capture the d4-pawn since we are planning to castle queenside creating a powerful pin on the knight. }
10. Nbxd4
{ 10.Nfxd4  O-O-O  is more or less the same. The pin on the knight is deadly, and we threaten ...c5 and ...Nc2+. }
10... O-O-O
{ We threaten ...c5 attacking the pinned knight as well as ...Nc2+ with a deadly fork. Black has a winning position, and the computer already gives -8. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5b) Albin Countergambit Tactics and Model games "]
[Black "Exercise 7: Albin Countergambit"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqkb1r/ppp2ppp/2n3n1/4P3/1PPp4/P4N2/1B2PPPP/RN1QKB1R b KQkq - 0 7"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ White played great so far and threatens to win the d4-pawn. How do we turn the tables? }
7... a5
{ A cunning move! Before we capture the e5-pawn, we provoke White to play b5. It gives us the possibility to develop with ...Bc5 later. }
8. b5 { White attacks the knight. } 8... Ncxe5
{ We regain the pawn and also attack the c4-pawn! Please note that we are threatening to capture the pawn without any trouble in this case. In earlier variations, when White's pawn was still on b2 instead of b5 ...Nxc4 wouldn't be a threat since White can fork the king and knight with Qa4+. }
9. Nxe5 Nxe5 10. e3
{ A cunning move from White, increasing the pressure on the pinned d4-pawn and opening the diagonal for the light-squared bishop to protect the c4-pawn. After  10.Bxd4  Nxc4  or  10.Qxd4  Qxd4  11.Bxd4  Nxc4  , we gain the pawn back, and Black has no troubles. }
10... Bc5
{ A crazy and brilliant move. White's king is still stuck in the middle, and that's why we want to provoke White to capture on d4 with the pawn forking our knight and bishop. }
11. exd4
{ White captures the d4-pawn forking the knight and bishop. Surely, your opponent will think they have a winning position now; however, in reality, White is in big danger. White's strongest move is  11.Bxd4  which has been covered here. }
11... Bg4
{ Ignoring White's threats and developing the bishop with tempo, attacking the queen. }
12. f3
{ White attacks the other bishop as well, we ignore all the hanging pieces and are going after the king. }
12... Qh4+ { Check! } 13. g3
{ The most logical move from White, also attacking our queen. It seems like we left all the pieces hanging for no reason. Even though White's moves look cunning, they made three significant mistakes in a row, and we reach a winning position. Let's destroy White with a devastating attack. }
13... Nxf3+
{ We continue attacking the king and capture the pawn with a check. } 14. Qxf3
{ White is fine giving up the queen in case they can capture our queen. Luckily we don't have to cooperate with that plan. Also, after  14.Kf2  Qf6  15.dxc5  Nd4+  16.Kg1  Bxd1  Black is a queen up. }
14... Qe7+
{ A brilliant intermediate move, safeguarding our queen and ensuring we will win White's queen on the next move. We shouldn't capture the queen on the previous move with  14...Bxf3?  Because in the end, we lose the bishop:  15.gxh4  Bxh1  16.dxc5  , and we are down in material. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5b) Albin Countergambit Tactics and Model games "]
[Black "Exercise 8: Albin Countergambit"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2qk2r/1pp2ppp/8/pPb1n3/2PP2b1/P7/1B1Q1PPP/RN2KB1R b KQkq - 0 12"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ White has a double attack on the bishop and knight. How will we counterattack? }
12... Qh4
{ Black's next move is castling queenside, and if White prevents that by taking either the knight or the bishop, we play ...Rd8 with a devastating effect. }
13. dxe5
{ A better move for White would be  13.dxc5  when Black still keeps a strong initiative and advantage as explained here. }
13... Rd8
{ We bring the rook to the d-file with a deadly effect. After  14.g3  Rxd2  15.gxh4  Rd1#  it's mate. }
14. Qc2 Rd1+
{ 14...Qxf2  15.Qxf2  Rd1  might be an even nicer way to finish the game! } 15.
Qxd1 Qxf2# { A fantastic checkmate in 15 moves. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5b) Albin Countergambit Tactics and Model games "]
[Black "Mamedyarov, Shakhriyar vs. Nepomniachtchi, Ian"]
[Result "*"]

{ This model game is a clash between the chess titans Mamedyarov and Nepomniachtchi. The World Champion challenger showed how to time the typical Albin Countergambit ideas to perfection and dominate the opening. }
1. d4 d5 2. c4 e5 3. dxe5 d4 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. a3 Nge7
{ We have covered the theory here. The World champion participant Nepomniachtchi follows our repertoire against Memedyarov. }
6. Bg5
{ Memedyarov immediately makes a dubious move. His idea is to pin the knight and prevent Black's plan of ...Ne7-Ngxe5. The bishop on g5 can easily be attacked, which we will see soon. }
6... Bg4 { Nepo continues development. } 7. Nbd2 h6
{ Unpinning the knight! After  8.Bxe7  Qxe7  Black has the bishop pair and is ready to castle queenside and regain the pawn with ...Nxe5. }
8. Bh4 g5 { Nepo unpins the knight. } 9. Bg3 Nf5
{ As seen in the course here, when the bishop is on g3, we prefer to go ...Nf5 putting pressure on the bishop. }
10. Qc2 Qe7
{ Nepo increases the pressure on the e5-pawn and gets ready to castle queenside. Also ...Bg7 is about to come adding another attacker to the pawn. Meanwhile, White still struggles to develop the light-squared bishop. Black already is clearly better here. }
11. Qe4 h5
{ A cunning move! Nepo doesn't only defend the bishop but also has the idea to trap White's bishop with ...h4. }
12. h3
{ Mamedyarov is forced to create an escape square on h2 for the bishop, and therefore he needs to allow a significant weakening of his pawn structure. }
12... Nxg3 { Destorying White's pawn structure. } 13. fxg3 Bd7
{ The best square to retreat with the bishop. After 13 moves, Black has a winning position. Nepo destroyed White's pawn structure, and the White's bishop is crying on its starting square, still blocked by the pawns. Also, Black has the bishop pair, and the e5-pawn will fall. }
14. e3 { Mamedyarov tries to wake up the bad bishop. } 14... dxe3 15. Qxe3 g4
{ Nepo opens the h6-c1 diagonal to develop and ensure a powerful role for the dark-squared bishop. }
16. hxg4 Bxg4 17. Be2 O-O-O
{ It's beautiful that the rook immediately exerts pressure on the open d-file. }
18. Qc3 Bg7
{ And Black's last piece develops! The e5-pawn will drop soon, and Black's rooks and bishops are monsters on such an open board. }
19. O-O-O Nxe5
{ The cunning  19...Bf5  would have been even stronger, which glues White's king to the c1-square. }
20. Qc2 Nc6 21. Bd3 Kb8
{ This is a bit passive.  21...Qe3  attacking the bishop would have been stronger. }
22. Rhe1 Qf6 23. Ne4 Qh6+ 24. Kb1 Nd4
{ Attacking the queen and the pinned knight. } 25. Qf2 Qb6
{ Nepo brings the queen over to the b-file and exerts more pressure on the b2-pawn. }
26. Neg5
{ Nepo has a spectacular combination to reach a winning position. After  26...Nxf3  27.Qxb6  Nxe1!!  28.Qb5  Nxd3  Black gets a knight, bishop, and rook in return for the queen and is winning. }
26... Rhe8 { This is a big mistake as it allows Nxf7. } 27. Nxf7 Nxf3
{ Another mistake. Nepo was still winning after  27...Qb3  when  28.Nxd8  doesn't work because of  28...Rxe1  29.Qxe1  and  29...Nc2!!  Black threatens ...Qxb2 mate and ...Nxe1. This is extremely difficult to find in a blitz game, and Nepo missed it. }
28. Qxb6 axb6 29. gxf3 Rxe1 30. Rxe1 Rxd3 31. fxg4 hxg4
{ After this long sequence of exchanges, a more or less equal endgame occurred which ended in a draw. }
32. Re8+ Ka7 33. Rg8 Bf6 34. Rg6 Rf3 35. Rxg4 Rf1+ 36. Kc2 Rf2+ 37. Kd3 Bxb2
38. Rf4 Rg2 39. Rf3 Bxa3 40. Ng5 c6 41. Ne4 Bb4 42. Rf2 Rg1 43. Ke2 Ka6 44. Kf3
b5 45. Rb2 c5 46. cxb5+ Kxb5 47. g4 Kc6 48. g5 Kd5 49. Re2 b5 50. Nf6+ Kd4 51.
Ng4 Rf1+ 52. Nf2 Rg1 53. Ng4 Rf1+ 54. Nf2 Rg1 55. Nh3 Rf1+
{ The opening was fantastic by Nepo. He completely dominated Mamedyarov with the Albin Countergambit. Unfortunately, the advantage slipped away to a draw. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
