[Round "?"]
[White "5b) Albin Countergambit Tactics and Model games "]
[Black "Wojtaszek, Radoslaw vs. Morozevich, Alexander"]
[Result "*"]

{ Top GM Morozevich, played countless games with the Albin Countergambit. Also, he popularized the famous ...Ne7-Ng6-Ngxe5 ideas which we play in many lines. Let's have a look at his game against top GM Wojtaszek. }
1. d4 d5 2. c4 e5 3. dxe5 d4 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. a3 Nge7
{ The typical Morozevich idea of ...Nge7-Ng6-Nxe5. } 6. b4 Ng6 7. Bb2 a5
{ As discussed in the course, it is important to provoke b5. } 8. b5 Ncxe5 9.
Nxe5 Nxe5 10. Qxd4 Qxd4 11. Bxd4 Nxc4
{ Everything is covered  here  (variation/17936664/#/10/w/1.3)  (.) } 12. e3
Be6
{ Morezevich immediately prepares for a queenside castle activating the rook on the d-file. }
13. Be2 O-O-O 14. O-O Kb8 15. Rc1 { Wojtaszek attacks the knight! } 15... Nd6
16. b6 c6 { 16...cxb6?  17.Bxb6  would lose a pawn. } 17. Be5
{ Pinning the knight. } 17... f6
{ Morezevich chases the bishop away from the central square.  18.Bxd6?  Bxd6  would benefit Black as it would break the pin and give Black the bishop pair. }
18. Bg3 h5
{ Threatening ...h4 with the idea to force the bishop to capture on d6. } 19.
h3 { Creating an escape square for the bishop. } 19... Kc8
{ Unpinning the knight. } 20. Nc3 Nc4 { Attacking the b6-pawn. } 21. Na4
{ 21.Bc7  would have been a bit stronger attacking the rook and defending the b6-pawn. }
21... Nd2 { Threatening ...Nb3 forking both rooks. } 22. Rxc6+
{ A spectacular move. White wants to promote the strong b-pawn. Unfortunately, it doesn't work out for White. }
22... bxc6 23. Ba6+ Kd7 24. Rd1
{ Pinning the knight. After  24.b7  Black can play  24...Bd6  and has full control of the promotion square. }
24... Ke8
{ Unpinning the knight and threatening a discovered attack with ...Nf3+. } 25.
b7 { White is about to promote the pawn. } 25... Nf3+
{ A powerful discovered attack and Black wins material. } 26. gxf3 Rxd1+
{ Grabbing the rook with a check. } 27. Kg2 Rb1
{ Black is just in time to defend and give up the rook for White's past pawn. Black is up so much material that after exchanging the rook for the pawn Black still has a winning advantage.  27...Rd8?  Wouldn't have worked since White can play  28.Bc7!  With the idea to eliminate the rook and promote the pawn after. }
28. Nc3 Rxb7 29. Bxb7 Kd7 30. Na4 Bd6
{ Black has a winning endgame so Wojtaszek resigned. Wojtaszek is known as one of the best-prepared grandmasters, and clearly, Morozevich didn't have any problems in the opening. }
*

[Event "?"]
