[White "5b) Albin Countergambit Tactics and Model games "]
[Black "Nesterov, Arseniy vs. Maksimovic, Bojan"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e5 3. dxe5 d4 4. a3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Nge7 6. b4 Ng6 7. Bb2 a5 8. b5
Ncxe5 9. Nxe5 Nxe5 10. e3 Bc5 11. exd4 Bg4 12. Qd2 Qh4
{ So far, we have covered everything in the course here. } 13. Be2 O-O-O
{ Pinning the d-pawn. } 14. Qf4
{ White pins the bishop and threatens to capture the knight. } 14... g5
{ A brilliant move. By attacking the queen, White has difficulties maintaining the pin on the bishop.  15.Qxe5  doesn't work since  15...Rhe8  creates a deadly pin along the e-file. }
15. Qe4 { White keeps pinning the bishop! } 15... f5
{ Black attacks the queen again, and now the queen is no longer able to keep on pinning the bishop. }
16. Qe3 Rhe8
{ Another spectacular move, activating the last piece in the attack. After  17.dxc5  Nd3+  wins the queen.   Also  17.dxe5  doesn't work wince  17...Bxe3  wins the queen. }
17. O-O Bxe2 18. Qxe2 Ng4 { Black threatens ...Rxe2 and ...Qh2#. } 19. Qxg4
Qxg4 { Black wins the queen and has a winning position. } 20. dxc5 Qxc4 21. Bf6
Qxf1+ { A way to finish in style with a queen sacrifice. } 22. Kxf1 Rd1#
{ This is how you play the Albin countergambit! Grandmaster Nesterov was checkmated in 22 moves. I love that grandmaster Nesterov even played one of the most critical variations against the opening but couldn't handle the sneaky traps recommended in the course. The @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/1pp2ppp/8/pP2n3/2Pp4/P3P3/1B3PPP/RN1QKB1R b KQkq - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...Bc5  move confused White, and Maksimovic played an amazing game. }
