[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5b) Albin Countergambit Tactics and Model games "]
[Black "Albin Countergambit: Chapter Summary"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ The second most popular move at the 1600-level. White puts the pawn in the center and wants to play e4 next move to occupy the whole center. }
1... d5 { We copy White and prevent them from playing e4. } 2. c4
{ The Queens Gambit has started, White challenges our center pawn. } 2... e5
{ Surely your opponent didn't see that one coming. We go for a surprising and attacking opening called the Albin Countergambit. We immediately open the lines for all pieces to activate them with lightning-fast development. Objectively speaking, this opening is a bit dubious. However, practically it's amazing to surprise our opponent on the second move and enter a position where they can fall for countless tricks. Studying the database with over 50 million 1600-level games, I can ensure you that it gives excellent chances to reach winning positions. Carlsen recently played it in a blitz game and World Championship challenger Nepomniachtci even in five blitz games. The pressure is on White now, and they have to immediately deal with the tension in the center. }
3. dxe5
{ The critical try for White against the Albin Countergambit. We push the d-pawn forward, gaining space and making it more difficult for White to develop the light-squared bishop.   3.cxd5  White forces us to bring out the queen.  3...Qxd5  We capture the pawn back. The queen is well-placed in the center, and we are putting pressure on the d4-pawn.  4.Nc3  The most popular move at the 1600-level, which doesn't work so well.  4...Qxd4  We gladly capture the d4-pawn.  5.Qxd4  White should trade the queens to prevent us from trading queens and breaking their right to castle.  5...exd4  6.Nb5  White threatens Nxc7+, forking the king in the rook and Nxd4. We will play a cunning intermediate move.  6...Bb4+  Developing with a check!  7.Bd2  White has to block the check.  7...Bxd2+  We trade bishops breaking White's right to castle.  8.Kxd2  White's king can be vulnerable on the d-file.  8...Na6  We develop and defend the c7-pawn.  9.Nxd4  White regained the pawn after a long journey with the knight.  9...c5  Forcing White's knight to move for the fourth time.  10.Nb5  Nf6  Black has a slight lead in development and a better endgame. We plan to play ...Be6 and castle queenside immediately, bringing the rook to the open d-file with a check.   3.Nc3  White attacks the d5-pawn.  3...exd4  We capture and force White to bring out the queen.  4.Qxd4  At this point, the position is not looking so good. White is attacking our d5-pawn three times. Let's turn the tables.  4...Nc6!  Sacrificing the d5-pawn in exchange for lightning-fast development.  5.Qxd5  Be6  Developing and attacking the queen.  6.Qxd8+  Rxd8  Black has sufficient compensation for the pawn, White has to be extremely careful now. I also won several times in online blitz games with this trick against strong opponents. Our deadly plan is ...Nb4-Nc2+.  7.e3  The most popular move at the 1600-level and Black reaches a winning position. Also, the second and third most popular move at the 1600-level allows the same tactic for Black.  7...Nb4  White can't prevent the fork with ...Nc2+, so Black is winning. }
3... d4
{ We aim to regain the e5-pawn. We are better when succeeding in this due to a better pawn structure. At this point, both our bishops can develop freely, whereas White's light-squared bishop is still stuck. }
4. Nf3
{ 4.e3  The second most popular move at the 1600-level, however it is a mistake. White wants to get rid of the d4-pawn and develop the light-squared bishop. After e3, we always play ...Bb4+ to break down White's pawn structure and open up the king's position. Capturing the pawn would be a significant mistake since White can trade queens and we are unable to castle and a pawn down.  4...Bb4+  5.Bd2  White blocks the check.  5...dxe3  We kindly invite White to capture our bishop, setting up a massive trick.  6.fxe3  White has a weakened pawn structure now and many pawn islands. Also, we can go for the attack immediately now that the f2-pawn is gone.   6.Bxb4?  The most popular move at the 1600-level. White greedily captures the bishop, and now we will see a brilliant trick.  6...exf2+  A cunning move. White cannot recapture the pawn since we would win the queen.  7.Ke2  White places the king on an awkward square to keep protecting the queen.  7...fxg1=N+!!  This is fantastic. We promote to a knight with a check, giving no time to White to exchange the queens. Promoting to a queen will only result in an equal endgame. When we don't give a check, White first trades the queens and then recaptures.  8.Rxg1  Bg4+  This deadly check wins the queen.  6...Qh4+  Forcing White to play g3.  7.g3  7...Qe4  We attack both the rook and the e3-pawn.  8.Qf3  Defends both the rook and the pawn. We shouldn't forget that our bishop is still hanging.  8...Bxd2+  First, we exchange bishop, and subsequently, we win a pawn.  9.Nxd2  9...Qxe5  Black is doing great and has a better pawn structure. The knights can develop to the natural squares with ...Nf6 and ...Nc6, and we are ready to castle. }
4... Nc6
{ White has many replies here. Our general plan is to win the pawn back with ...Ne7-Ng6-Ngxe5. And a rule of thumb is that we play ...Bb4+ after White plays e3. }
5. a3 Nge7 { We go for the standard plan to play ...Nge7-Ng6-Ngxe5. } 6. b4 Ng6
{ We continue our standard plan and get ready to regain the e5-pawn. } 7. Bb2
{ White develops and wants to win the d4-pawn. White's strategy is that they are fine giving back the e5-pawn if they can win the d4-pawn when White remains a pawn up. }
7... a5
{ A cunning move! Before we capture the e5-pawn, we provoke White to play b5. It gives us the possibility to develop with ...Bc5 later. }
8. b5 { White attacks the knight. } 8... Ncxe5
{ We regain the pawn and also attack the c4-pawn! Please note that we are threatening to capture the pawn without any trouble in this case. When White's pawn was still on b2 instead of b5 like here ...Nxc4 wouldn't be a threat since White can fork the king and knight with Qa4+. }
9. Nxe5 Nxe5 10. e3
{ A cunning move from White, increasing the pressure on the pinned d4-pawn and opening the diagonal for the light-squared bishop to protect the c4-pawn. If White immediately captured the d4-pawn Black will also regain the c4-pawn. }
10... Bc5
{ A crazy and brilliant move. White's king is still stuck in the middle, and that's why we want to provoke White to capture on d4 with the pawn forking our knight and bishop. }
11. exd4
{ White captures the d4-pawn forking the knight and bishop. Surely, your opponent will think they have a winning position now; however, in reality, White is in big danger. }
11... Bg4
{ Ignoring White's threats and developing the bishop with tempo, attacking the queen. }
12. f3
{ White attacks the other bishop as well, we ignore all the hanging pieces and are going after the king. }
12... Qh4+ { Check! } 13. g3
{ The most logical move from White, also attacking our queen. It seems like we left all the pieces hanging for no reason. Even though White's moves look cunning, they made three significant mistakes in a row, and we reach a winning position. Let's destroy White with a devastating attack. }
13... Nxf3+
{ We continue attacking the king and capture the pawn with a check. } 14. Qxf3
{ White is fine trading queens as so many other pieces are still hanging. Luckily we don't have to cooperate with that plan. }
14... Qe7+
{ A brilliant intermediate move, safeguarding our queen and ensuring we will win White's queen on the next move. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6a) London"]
[Black "Jobava London: 2.Nc3 "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nc3
{ The Jobava London! We play in a similar style as against the London and will attack in the center with  2...c5  . }
2... c5
{ We attack the center immediately. We don't have to be afraid to lose the c-pawn since we can often regain it and overtake the center when White's pawn is no longer on d4. }
3. dxc5
{ At the 1600-level grabbing the pawn is the most popular move. After  3.Nf3  Nc6  4.dxc5  Nf6  we transpose to the position here.   After  3.Bf4  White has a plan to play Nb5 and go the fork with Nc7+. We reply with  3...Nc6  4.e3  cxd4  4.exd4  Bf5  when we can defend against  5.Nb5  with  5...Rc8   After  3.e4  dxe4  4.d5  Nf6  we can continue development with ...g6, ...Bg7 and ...O-O. }
3... Nf6
{ If we go for the knight hunt immediately with  3...d4  White can play  4.Ne4  and support the c5-pawn.   By playing  3...Nf6  we prevent the knight from jumping to the center square and will threaten to go ...d4 after. }
4. Bg5
{ The most popular move at 1600-level, which is a mistake. White increases the pressure on the d5-pawn, however, we were planning to push the pawn either way. After  4.Nf3  Nc6  5.e3  e5  Black has a strong center and is threatening to play ...Bxc5.  6.Bb5  pins the knight and threatens Nxe5 so we reply with  6...Bg4  also pins the knight. }
4... d4
{ Hunting the knight. White is already in trouble. After  5.Nb5?  Qa5+  wins a piece.   After  5.Bxf6  exf6  6.Ne4  Bf5  Black has a significant lead in development and will regain the c5-pawn. }
*

