{ The London system is known as one of the most solid openings for White, let's immediately increase the pressure. }
2... c5 { Attacking the center. } 3. e3
{ Strengthening the center. White can also play  3.c3  with the same idea. Then we continue in the same fashion: developing our knights to the natural squares with ...Nc6 and ...Nf6. }
3... Nc6 { We start by developing our knights to their natural squares. } 4.
Nf3 Nf6 { Develops the other knight. } 5. Bb5
{ White allows us to put pressure.  5.c3  Qb6  transposes to the mainline, which we will see soon.   5.c4  is not so strong since White weakens the d4-pawn. We reply with  5...Bg4  pinning the knight and after  6.Be2  we play  6...dxc4  adding another attacker to the d4-pawn. }
5... Qa5+ { Forking the king and the bishop. } 6. Nc3
{ Defending against both threats, we will harrass White's pinned knight now. }
6... Ne4
{ Increasing the pressure on the pinned knight! White has to be precise here. }
