[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6a) London"]
[Black "London: 3.e3 with 4.c3 and 5.Nf3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4
{ The London system is known as one of the most solid openings for White, let's immediately increase the pressure. }
2... c5 { Attacking the center. } 3. e3
{ Strengthening the center. White can also play  3.c3  with the same idea. Then we continue in the same fashion: developing our knights to the natural squares with ...Nc6 and ...Nf6. }
3... Nc6 { We start by developing our knights to their natural squares. } 4. c3
{ The London is known for this V-shaped pawn structure. It's meant to be solid, but we'll see that Black has strong attacking ideas against this setup.  4.Bb5  is harmless since we can continue with  4...Nf6  and Black benefits from the trade with  5.Bxc6+  bxc6  . We can play ...Ba6 later to prevent White from casting. }
4... Nf6
{ This position can also be reached by @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2pp4/3P1B2/8/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKBNR w - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  3.c3  Nc6  4.e3  Nf6  . }
5. Nf3 Qb6
{ Attacking the b2-pawn. We don't give White time to get into their comfort zone and play all the standard London moves. }
6. Qb3 { Active way of protecting b2. } 6... c4
{ Offering a favorable queen trade for us, which opens up our rook. } 7. Qxb6
axb6
{ We reached a positional endgame. Black is a bit better and focuses on the queenside. The rook is already great on the half-open a-file. We will play ...Bf5, pointing to White's queenside, and we will march our b-pawns to trade them and open up the queenside even more. }
8. Nbd2 Bf5 { Developing the bishop outside of the pawn chain. } 9. Be2 e6
{ Opening up the dark-squared bishop, directly pointing to White's queenside. }
10. O-O
{ White finished development but doesn't have a good plan to continue. } 10...
b5 { Black is ready to march the b-pawn to weaken White's queenside. } 11. b3
{ The most played move at the 1600-level but not great because our dark-squared bishop can infiltrate now! After  11.Ne5  , we continue  11...b4  , trading our doubled pawn.   After  11.a3  , we can't play ...b4 anymore, so we continue developing with  11...Be7  .  We plan to reroute the knight with ...Nd7-Nb6-Na4 attacking the b2-pawn. }
11... Ba3
{ Threatening ...Bb2, attacking the rook and the c3-pawn. White can't prevent losing the c3-pawn, so Black is winning. }
