[White "6a) London"]
[Black "London: 3.e3 with 4.c3 and 5.Nf3 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4
{ The London system is known as one of the most solid openings for White, let's immediately increase the pressure. }
2... c5 { Attacking the center. } 3. e3
{ Strengthening the center. White can also play  3.c3  with the same idea. Then we continue in the same fashion: developing our knights to the natural squares with ...Nc6 and ...Nf6. }
3... Nc6 { We start by developing our knights to their natural squares. } 4. c3
{ The London is known for this V-shaped pawn structure. It's meant to be solid, but we'll see that Black has strong attacking ideas against this setup.  4.Bb5  is harmless since we can continue with  4...Nf6  and Black benefits from the trade with  5.Bxc6+  bxc6  . We can play ...Ba6 later to prevent White from casting. }
4... Nf6
{ This position can also be reached by @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2pp4/3P1B2/8/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKBNR w - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  3.c3  Nc6  4.e3  Nf6  . }
5. Nf3 Qb6
{ Attacking the b2-pawn. We don't give White time to get into their comfort zone and play all the standard London moves. }
6. Qc2 { The most popular move at the 1600-level, however, this is a mistake. }
6... Bf5 { Development with tempo and setting up a nice trick. } 7. Qxf5 Qxb2
{ Traps the rook and gives Black a winning position. However, we have to be very careful with taking the rook. If we take too soon, White will retreat with Qc2 and trap our queen in the corner later by castling and moving the b1-knight. }
8. Be2
{ This is White's most tricky try. It prepares to castle, so we can't take the rook yet. }
8... e6
{ Taking the rook is very bad here. After  8...Qxa1?  , White can play  9.Qc2  , and we can't prevent White from trapping our queen, for example,  9...e6  10.O-O  c4  11.Nbd2  and the queen is lost. Before taking the rook, we first attack White's queen to improve our position. If White is able to retreat with Qc2 we should play ...e6 and ...c4 before cashing in the rook. }
9. Qd3 c4
{ Attacking the queen again as planned! By including ...e6 and ...c4, we open up the diagonal for our dark-squared bishop, which can later help to rescue the queen. }
10. Qd2 Qxa1
{ Finally, we capture the rook! After  11.O-O  , White threatens to trap the queen. We have to play a few more accurate moves to save the queen.  11...Ne4  brings the knight with tempo and after  12.Qc2  , we have to play  12...Ba3  to create an escape square on b2. White can't prevent our queen from escaping, so he takes the bishop with  13.Nxa3  Qxc3  and the rescue operation is complete! We sacrificed the bishop to free the queen, but we are still much better because of the protected passed c4-pawn. }
