1. d4 d5 2. Bf4
{ The London system is known as one of the most solid openings for White, let's immediately increase the pressure. }
2... c5 { Attacking the center. } 3. e3
{ Strengthening the center. White can also play  3.c3  with the same idea. Then we continue in the same fashion: developing our knights to the natural squares with ...Nc6 and ...Nf6. }
3... Nc6 { We start by developing our knights to their natural squares. } 4. c3
{ The London is known for this V-shaped pawn structure. It's meant to be solid, but we'll see that Black has strong attacking ideas against this setup.  4.Bb5  is harmless since we can continue with  4...Nf6  and Black benefits from the trade with  5.Bxc6+  bxc6  . We can play ...Ba6 later to prevent White from casting. }
4... Nf6
{ This position can also be reached by @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2pp4/3P1B2/8/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKBNR w - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  3.c3  Nc6  4.e3  Nf6  . }
5. Nf3 Qb6
{ Attacking the b2-pawn. We don't give White time to get into their comfort zone and play all the standard London moves. }
6. Qc2 { The most popular move at the 1600-level, however, this is a mistake. }
6... Bf5 { Development with tempo and setting up a nice trick. } 7. Bd3
{ The most popular move at the 1600-level, which is a big mistake.  7.Qb3  is also often played, but it makes little sense because it loses a tempo. We have already seen this position where our bishop was still on c8. So we have a very favorable version now. We again play  7...c4  forcing the queen trade and reaching the same endgame with a tempo more. }
7... Bxd3
{ Trading the bishops to deflect the White queen from protecting the b2-pawn. }
8. Qxd3 Qxb2 { Not only taking a pawn but also trapping the rook! } 9. O-O Qxa1
{ The position is different here than in the previous variation. There we could play both ...e6 and ...c4 to rescue the queen with our bishop. In this position, we can grab the rook immediately and also rescue the queen. Playing  9...c4  first would be a mistake since after  10.Qd2  Qxa1  11.Qc2  we are too late to rescue the queen with our bishop as our pawn is still on e7. }
10. Qc2
{ White threatens to remove the b1-knight to trap our queen in the corner. We have to get her out. }
10... cxd4
{ We use our pawn now to safeguard the queen. The idea is that after  11.Nbd2  , our queen escapes with  11...Qxc3  . }
11. cxd4 Ne4
{ Our knight supports the c3-square so that our queen can escape! } *

