{ This position can also be reached by @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2pp4/3P1B2/8/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKBNR w - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  3.c3  Nc6  4.e3  Nf6  . }
5. Nd2
{ Unlike the other variations, we can no longer trap White's rook on a1 with the ...Qb6-Qxb2 plan. That's why we copy our opponent Londen's idea to get a strong bishop out! }
5... Bf5
{ In this line, we prevent Qc2 before playing ...Qb6. Compared to the mainline,  5...Qb6  is less attractive, since after  6.Qb3  c4  7.Qc2  Bf5  8.Qxf5  Qxb2  , the rook isn't trapped. }
6. Ngf3 Qb6
{ We will very likely transpose to lines we have seen earlier. Transpositions arrive after  7.Qb3  c4  8.Qxb6  axb6  to the variation here  .  In this situation we even have the same position endgame where we already gained an extra tempo with the ...Bf5 move.   Also  7.b3  cxd4  8.exd4  transposes to the variation here  . }
