[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6b) Reversed Jobava London and Reti opening: 1.Nf3"]
[Black "Delayed London 2.Nf3 and 3.Bf4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ The second most popular move at 1600-level. White puts the pawn in the center and wants to play e4 next move to occupy the whole center. }
1... d5 { We copy White and prevent them from playing e4. } 2. Nf3
{ White develops the knight and delays c4. Since we are playing the Albin Countergambit after  2.c4  , we must have a reply to  2.Nf3  where White cannot transpose into the standard d4-mainlines. }
2... Bf5
{ An aggressive move that Carlsen and Nepomniachtchi both tried several times. The idea behind the ...Bf5 move is that we want to develop the light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain before we play ...e6. }
3. Bf4 { White also goes for a London set-up. } 3... e6
{ Preparing to develop the dark-squared bishop. We are happy that our light-squared bishop is already out of the pawn chain. }
4. e3 Bd6 { Neutralizing Black's strong dark-squared bishop. } 5. Bg3
{ This is a typical retreat in the London. White's idea is that after  5...Bxg3  6.hxg3  , their rook on the h-file is activated. Therefore we will wait to capture that bishop until White has castled kingside. We continue development. }
5... Nf6 6. Nbd2
{ A standard move in the London. White's knight cannot put much pressure on our center with Nc3, therefore White wants to play Nbd2 and c3 instead and build a solid center. }
6... O-O 7. c3 c5
{ We propose a favorable pawn trade. After  8.dxc5  Bxc5  Black has a better position because of the two center pawns. We can prepare to slowly play ....e5 and gain complete control in the center. It wouldn't make sense to play ...Nc6 since the knight can't put any pressure on the well-protected d4-pawn. }
8. Ne5
{ The most popular move at the 1600-level. Black is already doing very well. }
8... Nc6
{ 9.Nxc6  bxc6  would give us doubled pawns. Still, this trade is more beneficial for Black since it opens the b-file, which allows us to create pressure against the b2-pawn. Also, whenever we play ...cxd4 trading the pawns, we get rid of our doubled pawns. }
9. Ndf3 c4
{ A fantastic prophylactic move preventing White from playing Bd3 and exchanging powerful bishop. We outplayed White in the London, and now Black is the only one to remain with a powerful London bishop while we managed to neutralize White's London bishop. When White tries to break down our pawn structure with  10.b3  , we strike with  10...Nb4  threatening ...Nxc2+ when after  11.cxb4  Bxb4+  Black has a devesting attacking, and the computer already gives  -8. }
*

