[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6b) Reversed Jobava London and Reti opening: 1.Nf3"]
[Black "Reversed Jobava London: 3.e3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ The second most popular move at 1600-level. White puts the pawn in the center and wants to play e4 next move to occupy the whole center. }
1... d5 { We copy White and prevent them from playing e4. } 2. Nf3
{ White develops the knight and delays c4. Since we are playing the Albin Countergambit after  2.c4  , we must have a reply to  2.Nf3  where White cannot transpose into the standard d4-mainlines. }
2... Bf5
{ An aggressive move that Carlsen and Nepomniachtchi both tried several times. The idea behind the ...Bf5 move is that we want to develop the light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain before we play ...e6. }
3. e3
{ A slow move for White getting ready to develop their light-squared bishop and castle. The disadvantage for White is that it locks in their dark-squared bishop. }
3... e6 4. c4 Nc6
{ The reversed Jobava London is started. The Jobava London is typically a set-up where White plays with d4, Nc3, and Bf4, and we copied the same set-up with Black. It's time to put White under pressure immediately. We put massive pressure on White since we plan to play ...Nb4-Nc2+ forking the king and rook. }
5. cxd5
{ 5.Nc3  is the most played move, which transposes to the variation we want after  5...Nb4  .   If White closes the position with  5.c5  , we first play  5...a6  , preventing White from pinning the knight with Bb5. White has more space on the queenside, and our strategy is to grab space on the kingside. A sample line to illustrate our plan is  6.a3  g5  7.Be2  g4  8.Nfd2  h5  9.b4  Bg7  10.O-O  Nf6  11.Nc3  and now Black is ready to open the center with  11...e5  12.dxe5  Nxe5  , and Black has an advantage. }
5... exd5 { We recapture with the pawn and still plan to go ...Nb4-Nc2+ next. }
6. Bb5 { White pins the knight! A prophylactic move to prevent ...Nb4. } 6...
Bd6
{ We continue to develop, and when we castle we unpin our knight at the same time.  6...Nf6  would be dangerous since White can increase the pressure on the pinned knight with  7.Ne5  . }
7. Nc3
{ White continues development. The trade after  7.Bxc6+  bxc6  benefits Black more as it opens the b-file for the rook. }
7... Nf6 { Developing and getting ready to castle. } 8. O-O O-O
{ By castling, we unpin the knight. After the most played move at the 1600-level  9.Re1  , we can play  9...Nb4  again, going for the fork with ...Nc2. If White plays  9.Bd2  , we can reply  9...Ne7  transferring the knight to g6 to start attacking the kingside. Also, we can play ...c6 attacking the bishop and stabilizing the center. Black has a very comfortable position. }
