{ White develops the knight and delays c4. Since we are playing the Albin Countergambit after  2.c4  , we must have a reply to  2.Nf3  where White cannot transpose into the standard d4-mainlines. }
2... Bf5
{ An aggressive move that Carlsen and Nepomniachtchi both tried several times. The idea behind the ...Bf5 move is that we want to develop the light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain before we play ...e6. }
3. c4
{ The critical try for White. This is only the third most popular move at the 1600-level. }
3... e6
{ We support the pawn in the center and open the diagonal to develop our other bishop. We shouldn't be greedy and play  3...dxc4  since after  4.Nc3  Nf6  5.e3  e6  6.Bxc4  White regained the pawn and has a strategical advantage as White has one more center pawn. Center pawns on e and d-files are typically stronger than pawns outside the center. }
