{ White develops the knight and increases the pressure on the center.  4.e3  Nf6  would transpose to the previous variation. }
4... Nc6
{ The reversed Jobava London started. The Jobava London is typically a set-up where White plays with d4, Nc3, and Bf4, and we copied the same set-up with Black. It's time to put White under pressure immediately. We are planning to play ...Nb4-Nc2+ forking the king and rook. }
5. Bf4
{ White defends against  5...Nb4  since they can play  6.Rc1  .   That's why we continue developing instead.  5.e3  is the most popular move at the 1600-level when we happily transpose to the variations we have seen here and play  5...Nb4  . }
5... Nf6 6. e3
{ If White tries to copy our strategy instead with  6.Nb5  threatening the fork with Nc7+, we counter the attack with  6...Bb4+  and either White's knight or bishop should retreat. Black has a great position and wins the c4-pawn after  7.Nc3  dxc4  . }
6... Bb4 { We develop the bishop and pin the knight. } 7. a3
{ White forces the trade, we are fine with that since we gain a tempo as  7.a3  doesn't develop anything. White strongest move is to play  7.Rc1  when we increase the pressure on the pinned knight with  7...Ne4  . GM Li won a great game in this position with Black against GM Melkumyan. Now at the 1600-level, the most popular move is  8.a3  , which is a big mistake since after  8...Nxc3  9.bxc3  Bxa3  10.Ra1  Bb2  Black is a pawn up and has a double attack on the rook and c3-pawn. }
7... Bxc3+
{ The trade weakens White's pawn structure, and we maintain the initiative. }
8. bxc3 O-O
{ Black has a lead in development. After  9.cxd5  , the most played move at the 1600-level, we reply with  9...Nxd5  with a double attack on the bishop and c3-pawn.   If White instead goes  9.Be2  , we can do the same thing with  9...dxc4  10.Bxc4  Nd5!  Attacking the bishop and c3-pawn. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6b) Reversed Jobava London and Reti opening: 1.Nf3"]
[Black "King's Indian Attack: 1.Nf3 with 2.g3 "]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3
{ We have discussed everything after  1.d4  and will now look at  1.Nf3  and  1.c4  .   These openings can often transpose into each other. Since we play the Albin Countergambit after  1.d4  , I carefully selected variations against  1.Nf3  and  1.c4  where White cannot transpose back in other  1.d4  mainlines, which we don't know. With  1.Nf3  , White goes for a slower opening and prevents us from playing ...e5.   As a rule of thump, we will always play ...e5 or ...d5 on the first move. We prefer to play ...e5, but only when Black play  1.d4  or  1.Nf3  and prevents that we will go  1...d5  . }
1... d5 2. g3
{ White aims for a solid set-up to fianchetto the bishop and castle quickly. We go for a London set-up with Black, bringing the bishop out before closing the pawn chain with ...e6.  2.d4  is more popular, and this transposes to all the positions we have covered in this chapter with  2...Bf5  . White sometimes played  2.e4?  playing for an opening trick. After  2...dxe4  3.Ng5  , I recommend  3...e5  giving back the pawn when after  4.Nxe4  Nc6  Black has better development and a better position. }
2... Bf5
{ We ensure that we don't lock in our light-squared bishop behind the pawn chain. }
3. Bg2
{ White continues with their plan and gets ready to castle. Now that our light-squared bishop is out, we can play ...e6 supporting the center and opening the diagonal for our dark-squared bishop. }
3... e6 4. O-O
{ White is quick with castling; however, they are not putting pressure on us yet. We also like to develop the pieces on the kingside and castle. }
4... Nf6
{ In this variation, we have to be a little bit patient with Black. We love to attack in every variation, but what White did so far is very solid, and they didn't give us any targets to attack yet. All I can teach you here is to make sure you also develop your pieces to proper squares so that you are ready for a fair battle later in the game. We develop the knight and are preparing to castle. }
5. d3 Be7
{ Black is ready to castle and has a comfortable position. An idea to follow up is preserving the bishop by playing ...h6, such that it can retreat with ...Bh7 after a possible Nh4.   The game could continue with  6.Nbd2  O-O  7.Re1  h6  when White frequently played  8.e4  and after  8...dxe4  9.dxe4  Nxe4  10.Nxe4  Qxd1  11.Rxd1  Bxe4  Black is a pawn-up.   The move  5...Bd6  would be risky since White has tactical ideas to fork the bishop and knight. A sample line where it could go wrong for us is  6.Nbd2  O-O  7.Re1  c6?  7.e4  dxe4  9.dxe4  Bg6  10.e5  and White has the fork winning a piece. }
