[Black "Reti Opening: 1.Nf3 with 2.c4 "]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3
{ We have discussed everything after  1.d4  and will now look at  1.Nf3  and  1.c4  .   These openings can often transpose into each other. Since we play the Albin Countergambit after  1.d4  , I carefully selected variations against  1.Nf3  and  1.c4  where White cannot transpose back in other  1.d4  mainlines, which we don't know. With  1.Nf3  , White goes for a slower opening and prevents us from playing ...e5.   As a rule of thump, we will always play ...e5 or ...d5 on the first move. We prefer to play ...e5, but only when Black play  1.d4  or  1.Nf3  and prevents that we will go  1...d5  . }
1... d5 2. c4
{ We can't play  2...Bf5  here because White is attacking our center pawn, and after  3.cxd5  Qxd5  4.Nc3  White would be better. We will grab more space in the center and push our d-pawn forward. }
2... d4 3. e3
{ White's most popular move at the 1600-level is to challenge this pawn. We will quickly bring our knight to support the center. }
3... Nc6 { Developing and supporting the d4-pawn. } 4. exd4 Nxd4 5. Nxd4 Qxd4
{ Our queen nicely blocks White from playing d4. } 6. Nc3 e5
{ We put the e-pawn in the center and get ready to develop and castle. After ...Bc5 we are already threatening a mate with ...Qxf2#. }
