[White "6c) London and Reti: Tactics and Model games  "]
[Black "Xiong, Jeffery vs. So, Wesley"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6
{ A different move order was used as in the course. We typically reach this position after   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.Bf4  c5  3.e3  Nc6  4.Nf3  Nf6  . }
5. c3 Qb6 6. Qb3 c4 7. Qc2 Bf5 8. Qc1 e6
{ We covered in the course everything till here. } 9. Nbd2 Rc8 10. h3 Be7 11.
Be2 O-O 12. O-O Qa5 13. b3 Ba3 { This ...Ba3 idea has been seen here. } 14. Qd1
Bb2 { The rook is trapped. } 15. bxc4 Qxc3
{ An excellent move which is stronger than the immediate  15...Bxa1  since after White plays  16.Qxa1  defends the c3-pawn. With  15...Qxc3  , which was played, So wins the c3-pawn, and the rook remains trapped. So So, can win the exchange anyway as the rook remains trapped. }
16. Rb1 Bxb1 17. Qxb1 Qb4 18. Bd3 Bc3 19. Qc2 Bxd2 20. Nxd2 dxc4 21. Nxc4 Rfd8
22. Rb1 Qe7 23. Qb2 Nd5 24. Bg3 b5
{ So makes use of a nice tactic that after  25.Qxb5  Nc3  forks the queen and rook. }
25. Na3 a6 26. Nc2 Na5 27. e4 Nc3 28. Re1 Na4 29. Qa1 Rc3 30. Re3 Nc4 31. Bxc4
Rxc4 32. Ne1 Rcxd4 33. Kh2 Rd1 34. Qe5 f6 35. Qh5 Qf7 36. Qg4 e5 37. Nf3 h5 38.
Qh4 Nb6 39. Ra3 Nc4 40. Rxa6 Ra1 { Threatening ...Rd1 and Rdh1 mate. } 41. Nxe5
Nxe5
{ 41...Rdd1  Threatening mate wouldn't work because of  42.Ra8+  Kh7  43.Rh8+!  Sacrificing the rook to be able to capture the queen with a check after  43...Kxh8  44.Nxf7+  White won the queen and can defend against the mate on the next move. }
42. Bxe5 { Black cannot capture the bishop as the f6-pawn is pinned. } 42...
Rxa2 43. Rxf6 gxf6 44. Bxf6
{ White goes all in for the attack but doesn't have enough material left to achieve anything. }
44... Rdd2 45. Qg5+ Kh7 46. Qf5+ Qg6 47. Qe6 Ra7 48. Qb6 Rf7
{ Black consolidated and has a large material advantage. Xiong resigned the game. }
