[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6c) London and Reti: Tactics and Model games  "]
[Black "Melkumyan, Hrant vs. Li, Chao B"]
[Result "*"]

{ This game will cover the Jobava London with Black in a game between two top GMs. }
1. Nf3 d5 2. d4 Bf5 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 Nc6 5. Bf4 Nf6 6. e3 Bb4 7. Rc1 Ne4
{ Grandmaster Li Chao follows our recommendation. } 8. Bd3
{ This logical development move from White is a mistake. White is in trouble after  8...dxc4  when  9.Bxc4  Nxc3  10.bxc3  Ba3  11.Ra1  Bb2  traps the rook and wins an exchange for Black. }
8... dxc4 9. Bxe4
{ White gives up the beautiful bishop, which is a significant concession. Also, it won't be easy to regain the c4-pawn. }
9... Bxe4 10. O-O Bd3 11. Ne2 O-O 12. Ne1
{ White threatens Nxd3 winning a pawn. Also, the light-squared bishop doesn't want to move as the c4-pawn is hanging. }
12... Bxe2
{ 12...Bxe1  would have been stronger. Black's light-squared bishop is better than the dark-squared bishop as it protects the c4-pawn. }
13. Qxe2 b5 { Black holds on to the extra pawn. } 14. b3
{ White challenges the pinned c4-pawn.  14...cxb3  cannot be played because of  15.Rxc6  . }
14... Na5 { Supporting the c4-pawn. } 15. bxc4
{ This is a mistake as it allows the knight to become active.  15.Rb1  would have been stronger, keeping the knight on the passive a5-square. }
15... Nxc4 16. Nd3 Bd6 17. Rb1 a6 18. a4 Qd7
{ Defending the b5-pawn and keeping the pawn structure intact.  18...bxa4  wins a pawn but has the disadvantage that Black's pawn structure is weak and the c- and a-pawns cannot protect each other. }
19. Rfc1 Rfb8 20. h3 h6 21. Ra1 Qe8 22. Qf3 Nb6 23. axb5 axb5 24. Rxa8 Rxa8 25.
Bxd6 cxd6 26. Qc6
{ White proposes a trade of queens to infiltrate with the rook. Li accesses correctly that the rook is not dangerous. }
26... Qxc6 27. Rxc6 Nc4 28. g4 g5 29. Rc7 Ra1+ 30. Kg2 Rb1 31. Rb7 Rb3
{ A cunning move, forcing the knight to move to a passive square. } 32. Ne1 Kg7
33. Nf3 Rb1 34. Rc7 Kf6 35. h4 gxh4 36. Nxh4
{ This trade improves White's pawn structure as Black gets another pawn island. On the other hand, Black benefits that White's knight is out of play and has difficulties defending against Black's strong past-pawn. }
36... Nd2 37. Nf3 Ne4
{ a great move! Li doesn't trade the knights because Black's knight is stronger. Black threatens ...Rb2 targetting the weak f2-pawn. }
38. Rc2
{ The rook is forced backward and is no longer targetting the f7-pawn. } 38...
b4 { And the pawn starts running! } 39. Nd2
{ White is the one who forces the exchange of knights now. } 39... Nxd2 40.
Rxd2
{ The endgame is now very different compared to when Li would have played   @@StartFEN@@8/2R2p2/3ppk1p/1p6/3P2P1/4PN2/3n1PK1/1r6 b - - 2 37@@EndFEN@@  37...Nxf3  38.Kxf3  here. In that case, White's rook would have been active on c7, targetting the f7-pawn, which restricts Black's king from moving forward. That's why White could hold that endgame with precise play. Li correctly judged that he shouldn't trade the knight there. Now Melkumyan decided to force the trade of knights; this is sensible as Black's knight is stronger. The concession is that White's rook is passive now, and the endgame is winning for Black. }
40... Kg5 41. Kf3 b3 42. Rd3 d5
{ 42...b2  would have been inaccurate as White can place its rook on the best defensive square with  43.Rb3  . }
43. Rc3 f5
{ Li creates another past pawn to win the game. The rest is a matter of technique. }
44. gxf5 Kxf5 45. Rc8 b2 46. Rf8+ Kg6 47. Rg8+ Kf7 48. Rb8 h5 49. Kg2 h4 50.
Rb7+ Kf6 51. f3 h3+
{ The pawn is poisoned, as after  52.Kxh3  Rh1+  53.Kg2  b1=Q  wins the game. }
52. Kh2 Rf1 53. Rxb2 Rxf3 54. e4
{ White will lose the e-pawn either way, so at least wants to make sure that Black gets doubled pawns. }
54... dxe4 55. Rb5 Rd3
{ White's rook is cutting off Black's king, which cannot walk forward.  55...Rf5  56.Rb8  Rh5  would have been easier, as it allows Black's king to slowly walk towards the d4-pawn. }
56. Rh5 Rf3
{ 56...e3  57.Re5  Rxd4  58.Rxe3  Rh4  would have been more convincing. } 57.
Re5 Re3 58. Rh5 Ke7
{ A big mistake to go backward with the king. White could hold the game now. The winning plan is to play  58...Rd3  when after  59.Rb5  we can play  59...e3  60.Re5  Rxd4  61.Rxe3  Rh4  and Black wins the game with the h and e-pawns. The king shouldn't go backward since it gives up the protection of the e5-square giving White more options to defend with Re5. }
59. Ra5 Kd6 60. Re5 Kd7 61. Rh5 Rd3 62. Re5 Rxd4 63. Kxh3 Kd6 64. Ra5
{ With accurate play White should be able to hold this endgame. } 64... Rd2 65.
Kg3 e5 66. Rb5 Ra2 67. Kg4 Rf2 68. Kg3 Rf4 69. Ra5 Ke6 70. Rb5
{ 70.Ra6+  would have been better when after  70...Kf5  71.Ra3  Black cannot make progress. }
70... Kf5
{ Black returns the favor,  70...Rf3+  would have been winning now when after  71.Kg4  Rf1  White's king is too far up the board to defend. Black now threatens ...e3! And giving checks doesn't help as Black's king will get closer to the pawns and help them promote.   After  70...Rf3+  71.Kg2  Black has the f4-square available for the king and can support the pawns to promote. }
71. Rb3 Ke6 72. Rb5 e3 73. Rb3 Re4 74. Rb1 Kd5 75. Kf3 e2 76. Re1
{ 76.Kf2  would have made a draw after  76...e1Q+  77.Rxe1  Rxe1  78.Kxe1  Kd4  79.Kd2  Ke4  80.Ke2  Black has opposition and makes a draw. }
76... Kd4
{ After  77.Rxe2  Rxe2  78.Kxe2  Ke4!  Black has opposition and will win the game. }
77. Kf2 Kd3 78. Kf3 Rf4+ { White resigned! } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6c) London and Reti: Tactics and Model games  "]
[Black "London: Chapter Summary "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4
{ The London system is known as one of the most solid openings for White, let's immediately increase the pressure. }
2... c5 { Attacking the center. } 3. e3
{ Strengthening the center. We continue developing our knights with ...Nc6 and ...Nf6. }
3... Nc6 { We start by developing our knights to their natural squares. } 4. c3
{ The London is known for this V-shaped pawn structure. It's meant to be solid, but we'll see that Black has strong attacking ideas against this setup.  4.Bb5  is harmless since we can continue with  4...Nf6  and Black benefits from the trade with  5.Bxc6+  bxc6  .  We can play ...Ba6 later to prevent White from castling. }
4... Nf6
{ This position can also be reached by @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/8/2pp4/3P1B2/8/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKBNR w - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  3.c3  Nc6  4.e3  Nf6  . }
5. Nd2
{ Unlike the other variations, we can no longer trap White's rook on a1 with the ...Qb6-Qxb2 plan. That's why we copy our opponent Londen's idea to get a strong bishop out!   5.Nf3  Qb6  Attacking the b2-pawn. We don't give White time to get into their comfort zone and play all the standard London moves.  6.Qc2  The most popular move at the 1600-level, however, this is a mistake.   6.Qb3  Active way of protecting b2.  6...c4  Offering a favorable queen trade for us, which opens up our rook.  7.Qxb6  axb6  We reached a positional endgame. Black is a bit better and focuses on the queenside. The rook is already great on the half-open a-file. We will play ...Bf5, pointing to White's queenside, and we will march our b-pawns to trade them and open up the queenside even more.  8.Nbd2  Bf5  Developing the bishop outside of the pawn chain.  9.Be2  e6  Opening up the dark-squared bishop, directly pointing to White's queenside.  10.O-O  White finished development but doesn't have a good plan to continue.  10...b5  Black is ready to march the b-pawn to weaken White's queenside.  11.b3  The most played move at the 1600-level but not great because our dark-squared bishop can infiltrate now!  11...Ba3  Threatening ...Bb2, attack the rook and the c3-pawn. White can't prevent losing the c3-pawn, so Black is winning.  6...Bf5  Development with tempo and setting up a nice trick.  7.Bd3?   The most popular move at the 1600-level, which is a big mistake.  7.Qb3  is also often played, but it makes little sense because it loses a tempo. We have already seen this position where our bishop was still on c8. So we have a very favorable version now. We again play  7...c4  forcing the queen trade and reaching the same endgame with a tempo more.  7...Bxd3  Trading the bishops to deflect the White queen from protecting the b2-pawn.  8.Qxd3  Qxb2  Not only taking a pawn but also trapping the rook!  9.O-O  Qxa1  Black won the rook, but we have to take care of our queen. White will try to trap her.  10.Qc2  White threatens to remove the b1-knight to trap our queen in the corner. We have to get her out.  10...cxd4   The idea is that after  11.Nbd2  , our queen escapes with  11...Qxc3  .  11.cxd4  Ne4  Our knight supports the c3-square so that our queen can escape!   5.Bd3  Qb6  Attacking the b2-pawn.  6.Qc2  c4  Driving away the bishop such that we can develop our bishop to that diagonal.  7.Be2  Bf5  Developing with tempo.  8.Qc1   White can't capture the bishop because then Black traps the rook in the corner. After  8.Qd2?  , we attack with  8...Ne4  9.Qc1  g5  , putting pressure on the bishop!  8...e6  Black has a lead in development and a slight advantage. }
5... Bf5
{ In this line, we prevent Qc2 before playing ...Qb6. Compared to the mainline,  5...Qb6  is less attractive since after  6.Qb3  c4  7.Qc2  Bf5  8.Qxf5  Qxb2  , the rook isn't trapped. }
6. Qb3
{ A good move to prevent  6...Qb6  which doesn't work since  7.dxc5  wins a pawn for White. }
6... Qd7 { The best way to protect the b7-pawn. } 7. Ngf3 c4
{ Gaining space with tempo. White's best reply is to drop the queen back to the starting square, so Black is doing perfectly fine. We can continue with ...e6 and ...Bd6, neutralizing White's London bishop on f4 and preparing to castle kingside. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6c) London and Reti: Tactics and Model games  "]
[Black "Reversed Jobava London + Reti Opening: Chapter Summary "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
{ The second most popular move at the 1600-level. White puts the pawn in the center and wants to play e4 next move to occupy the whole center.   1.Nf3  d5  2.g3  White aims for a solid set-up to fianchetto the bishop and castle quickly. We go for a reserved London set-up, bringing the bishop out before closing the pawn chain with ...e6.  2...Bf5  We ensure that we don't lock in our light-squared bishop behind the pawn chain.  3.Bg2  White continues with their plan and gets ready to castle. Now that our light-squared bishop is out, we can play ...e6 supporting the center and opening the diagonal for our dark-squared bishop.  3...e6  4.O-O  White is quick with castling; however, they are not putting pressure on us yet. We also like to develop the pieces on the kingside and castle.  4...Nf6  In this variation, we have to be a little bit patient with Black. We love to attack in every variation, but what White did so far is very solid, and they didn't give us any targets to attack yet. All I can teach you here is to make sure you also develop your pieces to proper squares so that you are ready for a fair battle later in the game. We develop the knight and are preparing to castle.  5.d3  Be7  Black is ready to castle and has a comfortable position. An idea to follow up is preserving the bishop by playing ...h6, such that it can retreat to with ...Bh7 after a possible Nh4. The bishop is safer on e7 than d6 since White has tactical ideas to fork the bishop and knight. }
1... d5 { We copy White and prevent them from playing e4. } 2. Nf3
{ White develops the knight and delays c4. This position can also be reached by @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Nf3  d5  2.d4 }
2... Bf5
{ An aggressive move that Carlsen and Nepomniachtchi both tried several times. We avoid getting into d4-mainlines and sidestep a lot of theory. The idea behind the ...Bf5 move is that we want to develop the light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain before we play ...e6. }
3. c4
{ The critical try for White. This is only the third most popular move at the 1600-level.   3.Bf4   This looks similar to London. However, with the inclusion of Nf3 and ...Bf5, we can't reply with  3...c5  because White can play  4.dxc5  , and we can't play  4...e5  because White firmly controls the e5-square.  3...e6  Preparing to develop the dark-squared bishop. We are happy that our light-squared bishop is already out of the pawn chain.  4.e3  Bd6  Neutralizing Black's strong dark-squared bishop.  5.Bg3  This is a typical retreat in the London. White's idea is that after a trade of bishops on g3 their rook on the h-file is activated. Therefore will wait to capture that bishop until White has castled kingside. We continue development.  5...Nf6  6.Nbd2  A standard move in the London.  6...O-O  7.c3  c5  We propose a favorable pawn trade. If White trades on c5 Black has a better position because of the two center pawns. We can prepare to slowly play ...e5 and gain complete control in the center. It wouldn't make sense to play ...Nc6 before we go ...c5 since the knight can't put any pressure on the well-protected d4-pawn.  8.Ne5  The most popular move at the 1600-level. Black is already doing very well.  8...Nc6  The trade of knights would give us doubled pawns. Still, this trade is more beneficial for Black since it opens the b-file, which allows us to create pressure against the b2-pawn. Also, whenever we play ...cxd4 trading the pawns, we get rid of our doubled pawns.  9.Ndf3  c4   A fantastic prophylactic move preventing White from playing Bd3 and exchanging powerful bishop. We outplayed White in the London, and now Black is to only one to remain with a powerful London bishop while we managed to neutralize White's London bishop. When White tries to break down our pawn structure with  10.b3  , we strike with  10...Nb4  threatening ...Nxc2+ when after  11.cxb4  Bxb4+  Black has a devesting attacking, and the computer already gives  -8.   3.e3  A slow move for White getting ready to develop their light-squared bishop and castle. The disadvantage for White is that it locks in their dark-squared bishop.  3...e6  4.c4  Nc6  The reversed Jobava London is started. The Jobava London is typically a set-up where White plays with d4, Nc3, and Bf4, and we copied the same set-up with Black. It's time to put White under pressure immediately. We put massive pressure on White since we plan to play ...Nb4-Nc2+ forking the king and rook.  5.Nc3  The most popular move at the 1600-level. White clearly didn't see our plan coming.  5...Nb4  Black threatens the fork on the king and the rook with ...Nc2+, and White is in big trouble.  6.Qa4+   White most popular move at the 1600-level, however, this check doesn't do much, and we can block it with the pawn. The computer already says that White's best move is  6.Kd2  defending against the fork with the knight. This shows that things have already gone entirely wrong for White. At the 1600-level this is seldom played.  6...c6  We block the check and reinforce the threat of ...Nc2+ forking the king and the rook.  7.e4  White blocks the bishops diagonal to defend against the fork.  7...Bxe4  We reinforce the threat of ...Nc2+ forking the king and rook.  8.Nxe4  White eliminates the bishop to defend however this will give our opponent some new problems.  8...dxe4  We attack the knight, and when the knight moves, we play ...Qxd4. Black has a winning position. }
3... e6
{ We support the pawn in the center and open the diagonal to develop our other bishop. We shouldn't be greedy and play  3...dxc4  since after  4.Nc3  Nf6  5.e3  e6  6.Bxc4  White regained the pawn and has a strategic advantage as White has one more center pawn. Center pawns on e and d-files are typically stronger than pawns outside the center. }
4. Nc3 { White develops the knight and increases the pressure on the center. }
4... Nc6
{ The reversed Jobava London started. The Jobava London is typically a set-up where White plays with d4, Nc3, and Bf4, and we copied the same set-up with Black. It's time to put White under pressure immediately. We are planning to play ...Nb4-Nc2+ forking the king and rook. }
5. Bf4
{ White defends against  5...Nb4  since they can play  6.Rc1  . That's why we continue developing instead.   5.e3  is the most popular move at the 1600-level when we happily transpose to the variations we have seen  here  (variation/18971254:#/3/w/1.5)  and play  5...Nb4  . }
5... Nf6 6. e3 Bb4 { We develop the bishop and pin the knight. } 7. a3
{ White forces the trade, we are fine with that since we gain a tempo. } 7...
Bxc3+
{ The trade weakens White's pawn structure, and we maintain the initiative. }
8. bxc3 O-O
{ Black has a lead in development. After  9.cxd5  , the most played move at the 1600-level, we reply with  9...Nxd5  with a double attack on the bishop and c3-pawn. If White doesn't play that we still threaten ...dxc4 followed by ...Nd5! }
