[White "7a) English opening: 1.c4"]
[Black "English Opening: 2.Nc3 with 3.Nf3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5
{ Let's play the reversed Sicilian. We used the rule of thumb that we play  1...e5  against every more from White except 1.d4 or 1.Nf3 when 1...e5 would blunder the pawn. }
2. Nc3
{ Those of you who also have the White course know that we fight the Sicilian with the Alapin. In this position, it would work yet to go for the reversed Alapin since after  2...c6  , White plays  3.Nf3  attacking our e5-pawn when we don't have our signature knight-hunting move  3...e4  attacking that knight since White captures with  4.Nxe4  .  We keep in mind that we want to go for the Alapin idea later on, but first, we develop the knight. }
2... Nf6 { Developing and also getting ready to castle. } 3. Nf3
{ White develops and attacks the pawn, which prevents our reversed delayed Alapin ideas. In these positions, we have the knight-hunting idea  3...e4  , which doesn't work yet since after  4.Ng5  Qe7  5.Qc2  , we are losing the e4-pawn. So instead, we develop the other knight to support the pawn. We keep in mind that at some point, we would like to hunt White's knight with ...e4. }
3... Nc6
{ We have another four knights variations on the board. We plan to play ...Bb4 next targetting the knight and getting ready to castle. Only when White plays  4.e4  we reply with  4...Bc5  and target the weak d4-square. }
4. e3 Bb4 5. Qc2
{ 5.d4  exd4  6.exd4  d5  would transpose to the variation we have seen here in the Albin countergambit.   To  5.Nd5  , we can reply with  5...e4  hunting the knight. }
5... Bxc3
{ After  5...O-O  White can play  6.Nd5  attacking the bishop when after  6...Nxd5  7.cxd5  White is attacking our knight and e5-pawn. I would rather avoid this by capturing the knight.   Also, after  5...O-O  6.Nd5  now the knight hunt with  6...e4  doesn't work since White can win the pawn with  7.Nxf6+  Qxf6  8.Qxe4  . }
6. Qxc3 Qe7
{ We defend the e5-pawn and are ready to castle and play ...d5 next. I like this more than  6...d6  since we would prefer to push the pawn to ...d5 directly at a later stage. }
7. Be2 O-O 8. O-O d5
{ We get our other pawn in the center, and after  9.cxd5  Nxd5  , we are gaining a tempo on the queen. Black has a comfortable position. }
