[White "7a) English opening: 1.c4"]
[Black "English Opening: 2.Nc3 with 3.Nf3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 e5
{ Let's play the reversed Sicilian. We used the rule of thumb that we play  1...e5  against every more from White except 1.d4 or 1.Nf3 when 1...e5 would blunder the pawn. }
2. Nc3
{ Those of you who also have the White course know that we fight the Sicilian with the Alapin. In this position, it would work yet to go for the reversed Alapin since after  2...c6  , White plays  3.Nf3  attacking our e5-pawn when we don't have our signature knight-hunting move  3...e4  attacking that knight since White captures with  4.Nxe4  .  We keep in mind that we want to go for the Alapin idea later on, but first, we develop the knight. }
2... Nf6 { Developing and also getting ready to castle. } 3. Nf3
{ White develops and attacks the pawn, which prevents our reversed delayed Alapin ideas. In these positions, we have the knight-hunting idea  3...e4  , which doesn't work yet since after  4.Ng5  Qe7  5.Qc2  , we are losing the e4-pawn. So instead, we develop the other knight to support the pawn. We keep in mind that at some point, we would like to hunt White's knight with ...e4. }
3... Nc6
{ We have another four knights variations on the board. We plan to play ...Bb4 next targetting the knight and getting ready to castle. Only when White plays  4.e4  we reply with  4...Bc5  and target the weak d4-square. }
4. g3
{ We cannot play  4...e4  yet since after  5.Ng5  both knights attack the e4-pawn, and we would lose it. That's why we wait with our ...e4 knight-hunting idea. }
4... Bb4 { Developing and preparing to castle. } 5. Bg2
{ White fianchettos the bishop, which means that the knight-hunting idea still doesn't work since after  5...e4  6.Ng5  Bxc3  7.bxc3  White still has two attackers on the e4-pawn, and we would lose the pawn. That's why we castle and get ready to defend the pawn with ...Re8  . }
5... O-O 6. O-O
{ Now we are ready for our master plan and start the knight-hunt. } 6... e4
{ Our signature knight-hunting move. Those of you who also studied the White course are already familiar with this idea. Generally speaking, White's knight's best places are c3 and f3, and we would like to hunt these knights from their comfortable squares. In the White course, we mercilessly went for the same strategy hunting Black's knights on c6 and f6. }
7. Ng5
{ White has three attackers on the e4-pawn. We should eliminate the c3 knight now. }
7... Bxc3 { Eliminating one of the attackers. } 8. bxc3 Re8
{ Since the rook can help, we can sufficiently defend the pawn. } 9. Qc2
{ White adds the queen as an attacker so we should defend with the queen as well. }
9... Qe7
{ Since the knight on g5 is misplaced, White has to trade the e4-pawn to ensure the knight can come back to f3. At 1600-level, most of the White players didn't know how to handle this position properly. }
10. d4
{ One of the most popular moves at 1600-level. White should play d3 or f3 to trade our e4-pawn and create a safe square for the knight to retreat to f3. In that case, the position will be balanced. }
10... h6
{ We kick the knight to the edge of the board, forcing it to move for the third time. After  11.Nh3  Na5  Black can already win the c4-pawn and has a significant advantage. }
