1. c4 e5
{ Let's play the reversed Sicilian. We used the rule of thumb that we play  1...e5  against every more from White except 1.d4 or 1.Nf3 when 1...e5 would blunder the pawn. }
2. Nc3
{ Those of you who also have the White course know that we fight the Sicilian with the Alapin. In this position, it would work yet to go for the reversed Alapin since after  2...c6  , White plays  3.Nf3  attacking our e5-pawn when we don't have our signature knight-hunting move  3...e4  attacking that knight since White captures with  4.Nxe4  .  We keep in mind that we want to go for the Alapin idea later on, but first, we develop the knight. }
2... Nf6 { Developing and also getting ready to castle. } 3. d3 c6
{ We go for the reversed delayed Alapin and will play ...d5 on the next move. After  3.e3  , I recommend  3...Bb4  to develop and prepare to castle. We will see similar ideas here. }
4. Nf3 { White attacks the e5-pawn, but we still continue with our plan. } 4...
d5
{ We grab the full center. We allow White to capture the e5-pawn since we have a sneaky trap. }
5. Nxe5
{ A big blunder from White. We eventually want to fork the king and knight, so we should first chase away the other knight. }
5... d4 { Going for our plan to win a piece. } 6. Ne4 Qa5+
{ Forking the king and knight to win a piece. Here it would also work to first trade knight with  6...Nxe4  7.dxe4  and then go for  7...Qa5+  .  In the mainline, it is important to play ...Qa5 immediately. }
