1. c4 e5
{ Let's play the reversed Sicilian. We used the rule of thumb that we play  1...e5  against every more from White except 1.d4 or 1.Nf3 when 1...e5 would blunder the pawn. }
2. Nc3
{ Those of you who also have the White course know that we fight the Sicilian with the Alapin. In this position, it would work yet to go for the reversed Alapin since after  2...c6  , White plays  3.Nf3  attacking our e5-pawn when we don't have our signature knight-hunting move  3...e4  attacking that knight since White captures with  4.Nxe4  .  We keep in mind that we want to go for the Alapin idea later on, but first, we develop the knight. }
2... Nf6 { Developing and also getting ready to castle. } 3. d3 c6
{ We go for the reversed delayed Alapin and will play ...d5 on the next move. After  3.e3  , I recommend  3...Bb4  to develop and prepare to castle. We will see similar ideas here. }
4. Nf3 { White attacks the e5-pawn, but we still continue with our plan. } 4...
d5
{ We grab the full center. We allow White to capture the e5-pawn since we have a sneaky trap. }
5. cxd5 cxd5 6. Nxe5
{ For White, this variation is objectively fine, however, we have many sneaky tricks. }
6... d4
{ Going for the same plan to chase the knight and threaten a fork with ...Qa5+. }
7. Qa4+
{ This is a strong intermediate check by White, which prevents our idea to fork with ...Qa5+ later. The most played move at the 1600-level is  7.Ne4  where we win the knight again with the same tactic  7...Qa5+  forking the king and knight. }
7... Nc6
{ We are setting up another trick for White, inviting them to capture the knight twice. }
8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. Ne4
{ The most-played move at the 1600-level is  9.Qxc6+  when after  9...Bd7  we win a piece since we are attacking the queen and knight. }
9... Rb8 10. Qxc6+ Bd7
{ We are attacking the queen. The position is tough to play for White, but they can get an opening advantage by playing very well. After  11.Nd6+  Ke7  12.Qc5  Ke6  we are threatening to win the knight with ...Bxd6  13.Qc4+  is the only move for White when they should spot that we cannot play  13...Kxd6  since they have  14.Bf4+  Ke7  15.Qc5+  Ke8  16.Qe5+  winning the rook.   So instead, we play  13...Nd5  with a complicated middlegame where White is objectively better. At the 1600-level nobody managed to find all these ideas with White, and most even played something that loses an entire knight. }
