1. c4 e5
{ Let's play the reversed Sicilian. We used the rule of thumb that we play  1...e5  against every more from White except 1.d4 or 1.Nf3 when 1...e5 would blunder the pawn. }
2. Nc3
{ Those of you who also have the White course know that we fight the Sicilian with the Alapin. In this position, it would work yet to go for the reversed Alapin since after  2...c6  , White plays  3.Nf3  attacking our e5-pawn when we don't have our signature knight-hunting move  3...e4  attacking that knight since White captures with  4.Nxe4  .  We keep in mind that we want to go for the Alapin idea later on, but first, we develop the knight. }
2... Nf6 { Developing and also getting ready to castle. } 3. g3
{ The most popular move at the 1600-level. And this is good news for us since now we can go for the delayed reserved Alapin. }
3... c6
{ Let's go for the reversed delayed Alapin and get the same ideas as in the White course. The plan is to play ...d5 getting a strong pawn center and getting ready to hunt White's knights. }
4. Bg2 d5
{ We follow up with our Alapin plan and get our two strong pawns in the center. Also, we are ready for ...d4 hunting White's knight. }
5. cxd5
{ In 80% of the games at the 1600-level, White traded these pawns without thinking about it much. This is actually a mistake from White, as it gives us the c6-square for the knight to develop. }
5... cxd5
{ Black has a lovely pawn center and can start the knight-hunting ideas. We will play ...d4 next regardless of what White plays. When White play  6.d4  exd4  7.Qxd4  Nc6  we develop with tempo, and after  8.Qd1  d4  kicks the knight from the comfortable c3-square. White is under pressure, and Black already has an advantage.   Even after  6.Qb3  d4  is fine when  7.Bxb7  Bxb7  8.Qxb7  Nbd7  we sacrifice a pawn. After White's most played moves at the 1600-level  9.Nb5?  Rc8  10.Qxa7  Bc5!  Black has a massive lead in development and a winning position. }
