[White "7b) Larsen's, Sokolosky, Van 't Kruijs, Bird's opening "]
[Black "Larsen's opening: 1.b3 "]
[Result "*"]

1. b3
{ This chapter will cover all the sidelines which you won't face often.  1.b3  ,  1.b4  ,  1.g3  ,  1.e3  ,  1.f4  we reply always with  1...e5  .   As a rule of thumb, we will play 1...e5 in all cases except when White plays  1.Nf3  or  1.d4  when we play  1...d5  . }
1... e5 2. Bb2 { White attacks the e5-pawn. } 2... Nc6
{ We develop and defend the pawn. } 3. e3 d5
{ We don't hesitate to grab the pawn center. We can develop the bishops anywhere when our pawns are on e5 and d5. }
4. Bb5
{ White pins the knight and threatens to capture the e5-pawn. This was White's idea of 1.b3 to get counterplay against the e5-pawn with the fianchetto bishop. But we are prepared. }
4... Ne7
{ We protect our pinned knight and want to recapture it with the other knight. }
5. Bxe5
{ White accepts the challenge and captures the pawn. After  5.Nf3  , we play  5...e4  hunting the knight. }
5... a6 { We force White to trade the strong bishop and unpin our knight. } 6.
Bxc6+ Nxc6 { We recapture and put pressure on the bishop gaining a tempo. } 7.
Bb2 Qg5
{ Attacking the g2-pawn and preparing to the castle queenside. White is under a lot of pressure, and their king is still in the middle. }
8. Qf3
{ White needs to defend the g2-pawn. After  8.g3  , White's light-squares are weak for the rest of the game, which means we have great attacking changes with the light-squared bishop and queen. We will play  8...Bg4  developing and attacking the queen. }
8... Bg4 { We develop and attack the queen. } 9. Qg3
{ White pins the bishop and threatens h3. } 9... Bd6
{ We develop with tempo attacking the queen. } 10. f4 Qg6
{ After  11.h3  Qxc2  12.Bxg7  Rg8  13.Qxg4  , we can win back the piece with  13...Bf8  attacking the pinned bishop, and Black has a better position.   If White plays  11.d3  , we can play  11...d4  , blocking the bishops diagonal when after  12.exd4  O-O  the e-file is open, and we threaten ...Rae8+ with a devastating attack. We keep the rook on f8 even though it looks passive since after White trades of queens in the variation with  13.h3  Rae8+  14.Kf2  Bd7  15.Qxg6  fxg6  the rook is active now on the f-file. }
