1. b4 e5 { Our typical reply. } 2. Bb2
{ Now  2...Nc6  doesn't work since White attacks with  3.b5  Nd4  4.e3  , and White wins a pawn. }
2... Bxb4
{ We agree to trade the b-pawn for the central e5-pawn, even though it is a strategic disadvantage. White needs to spend a lot of time to win the e5-pawn, so we get a lead in development. }
3. Bxe5 Nf6
{ We develop and prepare to castle. We want to continue with ...O-O ...d5 ...c5 and after we will gain a tempo on the bishop with ...Nc6!. We would first like to play ...c5 before we play ...Nc6 to avoid that our c-pawn is stuck behind the knight. A sample line could be  4.e3  O-O  5.Nf3  d5  6.Be2  c5  7.O-O  Nc6  8.Bb2  Ba5  When we plan to play ...d4 blocking White's dark-squared bishop. Also, we can play ...Bc7, ...Qd6 and ...Bg4 setting up a mating attack. }
