1. f4 e5 { We play 1...e5 even though White can capture the pawn. } 2. fxe5
{ White accepts the pawn sacrifice.  2.e4  would transpose to the King's Gambit covered here. }
2... d6
{ We are giving up another pawn to start a big attack. After  3.Nf3  dxe5  4.Nxe5  Bd6  5.Nf3  , we transpose to the variation here.   When after  2.Nf3  dxe5  White plays  3.e4  , we reply with  3...Bc5  keeping the bishop on a diagonal that prevents White from casting, and White can't pay  4.Nxe5  since we strike with  4...Qh4+  . }
3. exd6 Bxd6 { Threatening mate with ...Qh4+! } 4. Nf3
{ After a careless move like  4.Nc3  Qh4+  5.g3  Bxg3+  6.hxg3  Qxg3#  is mate. }
4... Nf6
{ We are going to play ...Ng4. White can't stop that with  5.h3  because after  5...Bg3  , it's mate! }
5. e3
{ After  5.g3  we immediately want to destroy White's pawn structure on the kingside and play  5...h5  after  6.Bg2  h4  7.Nxh4  Rxh4  8.gxh4  Ne4  We will deliver mate soon!   White could also play  5.d4  Ng4  6.Qd3  with the idea that  6...Bxh2?  no longer works after  7.Nxh2  Qh4+  8.g3  .  In that case, we will play @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp2ppp/3b4/8/3P2n1/3Q1N2/PPP1P1PP/RNB1KB1R b KQkq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6...c5  challenging White's center. }
5... Ng4
{ At the 1600-level, White almost always plays a move allowing the tactical combination here with ...Bxh2. }
6. Be2
{ The most popular move at 1600-level, however, this is a big blunder. White should play  6.d4  making space for the king when we reply with  6...Qe7  pressuring the e3-pawn. }
6... Bxh2 { We are threatening ...Bg3+, so White has to capture the bishop. }
7. Rxh2
{ Half of the games at the 1600-level continued with  7.Nxh2  when  7...Qh4+  8.Kf1  Qf2#  is mate. }
7... Nxh2 { Winning the rook. } 8. Nxh2 Qh4+
{ Our tactical justification, forking the king and the knight. } 9. Kf1 Qxh2
{ We are an exchange up and have a winning position. } *

