1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. e4 Bc5 4. Nf3 Ng4 5. d4 exd4 6. Nxd4 Nxf2 7. Kxf2 Qf6+
8. Ke3 Nc6 { This was all covered in the here. } 9. Ne2
{ Defending the pinned knight! Instead  9.Nb5  would have been more active when we reply with  9...O-O  as covered here. }
9... O-O
{ Black safeguards its king and gets ready to include the rook into the attack along the e-file. }
10. b3 Qe5
{ Not the best move, but it has the idea to attack later with ...f5 attacking the pinned e4-pawn.  10...Re8  would have been stronger immediately putting pressure on White's king. }
11. g4 d5
{ A strong move! Black wants to open the position as quickly as possible now that White's king is still in the middle. }
12. cxd5 Nxd4 13. Nxd4 Bxg4
{ Grabbing the pawn and developing with tempo. White's queen cannot recapture since after  14.Qxg4  Qxd4+  is forking the king and the rook. }
14. Qd3 f5
{ Attacking the pinned e4-pawn and activating the rook on the f-file. } 15. Bb2
fxe4 16. Qc4
{ 16.Qxe4  doesn't work since after  16...Rf3+  White cannot capture the rook since both the knight and queen are pinned. After  17.Kd2  Qxe4  Black wins. }
16... Qf4# { Mate! White got absolutely destroyed in this game. } *

