1. e4
{ The opening developing with a different move order but returns to the recommendation in our course later. }
1... e5 2. c4 Nf6 3. Nc3 Bc5 4. Nf3 Ng4 5. d4 exd4 6. Nxd4 Nxf2 7. Kxf2 Qf6+ 8.
Ke3 Nc6
{ Another model game from this position. Everything is covered in the course. I love that this game was played in the German Youth championship under 10, and Farokhi already played at a very high level. }
9. Be2
{ White gives up on the knight. It would have been more stubborn to keep defending with  9.Nb5  . }
9... Nxd4
{ Black threatens ...Nc2+, which is a double check and attacks the rook. } 10.
Kd2 { The king sidesteps out of the discovered attack. } 10... O-O
{ Black ensures to get a safe king! } 11. Rf1 Qg5+ { Double attack. } 12. Ke1
Qxg2 13. h4 { White tries to save the hanging h-pawn. } 13... Qg3+ 14. Kd2 Re8
{ Black is not in a hurry to play  14...Qxh4  but first wants to wake up the sleeping pieces. }
15. h5 Bb4 { Pinning the knight and threatening ...Rxe4. } 16. Bd3 Qg2+ 17. Ke1
d6 { Getting ready to include the bishop is the game with ...Bg4  . } 18. Bd2
Bg4 { Developing with tempo. } 19. Qa4 Nf3+ 20. Rxf3 Bxc3
{ It would also have been fine to play  20...Bxf3  when White cannot play capture the bishop with  21.Qxb4  since  21...Qg1  22.Bf1  Qg3#  is mate. }
21. Bxc3 Bxf3 22. Qc2 Bxe4 23. Bxe4
{ White's best option would be  23.Qxg2  , but after  23...Bxg2+  , the endgame is clearly winning for Black. }
23... Qxc2 { A cunning move that wins the queen as the bishop is pinned. } 24.
h6 Rxe4+ 25. Kf1 Qe2+ 26. Kg1 Rg4+ 27. Kh1 Qg2#
{ A nice checkmate to finish the game. } *

