1. c4 e5
{ Let's play the reversed Sicilian. We used the rule of thump that we play ...e5 against every more from White except 1.d4 or 1.Nf3 when 1...e5 would blunder the pawn. Even after 1.f4, we go 1...e5 and sacrifice the pawn. }
2. Nc3
{ Those of you who also have the White course now that we fight the Sicilian with the Alapin. In this position, it wouldn't work yet to go for the reversed Alapin since after  2...c6  , White plays  3.Nf3  attacking our e5-pawn when we don't have our signature knight-hunting move  3...e4  attacking that knight since White captures with  4.Nxe4  .  We keep in mind that we want to go for the Alapin idea later. And first, develop the knight.   2.g3  Nf6  We develop the knight and will go for a delayed reversed Alapin.  3.Bg2  c6  We are planning to play ...d5 next move and grab a strong center.  4.Nc3  Transposition  4...d5  We gladly grab our powerful center. This variation will transpose to the variation covered here later in this chapter. }
2... Nf6 { Developing and also getting ready to castle. } 3. g3
{ The most popular move at the 1600-level. And this is good news for us since now we can go for the delayed reserved Alapin.   3.e4  By playing e4, White weakens the d4-square. So we are directing our pieces to this strong square.  3...Bc5  4.Nf3  Ng4  It's time to give your opponent a heart attack. We are threatening ...Nxf2 forking the queen and rook.  5.d4  White has to block the bishop's diagonal.  5...exd4  We capture the pawn and attack the knight.  6.Nxd4   The most-played move at the 1600-level, however, this is a big mistake. By capturing the d4-pawn, our bishop becomes more powerful, and White allows us a strong sacrifice. The best move for White is  6.Na4  when after  6...Bb4+  7.Bd2  Qe7  Black attacks the e4-pawn and has a slight advantage.  6...Nxf2  We sacrifice on the f2-square, forking the queen and rook. When we sacrifice a piece on the f2-square, we want to have a direct follow-up to regain the material.  7.Kxf2  Qf6+  Double attack on the king and knight. We are forcing the king forward to keep on protecting the knight.  8.Ke3  Nc6   By adding another attacker to the pinned knight, we win back the piece and keep a strong initiative because of the White's weak king. Black has a winning position. After  9.Ncb5  O-O  we White's knight keeps on being pinned, and we threatening ...a6 eliminating the defending knight to win the piece.   3.d3  c6  We go for the reversed delayed Alapin and will play ...d5 next move.  4.Nf3  White attacks the e5-pawn, and still we will continue with our plan.  4...d5  We grab the full center. We allow White to capture the e5-pawn since we have a sneaky trap.  5.cxd5   5.Nxe5  A big blunder from White. We eventually want to fork the king and knight, so we should first chase away the other knight.  5...d4  Going for our plan to win a piece.  6.Ne4  Qa5+  Forking the king and knight to win a piece.  cxd5  6.Nxe5  For White, this variation is objectively fine, however, we have many sneaky tricks.  6...d4  7.Qa4+   This is a strong intermediate check by White, which prevents our idea to fork with ...Qa5+. The most played move at the 1600-level is  7.Ne4  when we win the knight again with the same tactic  7...Qa5+  forking the king and knight.  7...Nc6  We are setting up another trick for White, inviting them to capture the knight twice.  8.Nxc6  bxc6  9.Ne4   The most-played move at the 1600-level is  9.Qxc6+  when after  9...Bd7  we win a piece since we are attacking the queen and knight.  9...Rb8  10.Qxc6+  Bd7   We are attacking the queen. The position is tough to play for White, but they can get an opening advantage by playing very well. After  11.Nd6+  Ke7  12.Qc5  Ke6  we are pinning the knight and threatening to win the knight with ...Bxd6  13.Qc4+  is the only move for White when they should spot that we cannot play  13...Kxd6  since they have  14.Bf4+  Ke7  15.Qc5+  Ke8  16.Qe5+  winning the rook. So instead, we play  13...Nd5  with a complicated middlegame where White is objectively better. Nobody at the 1600-level managed to find all these ideas with White, and most even played something that loses an entire knight.   3.Nf3   White develops and attacks the pawn, which prevents our reversed delayed Alapin ideas. In these positions, we have the knight-hunting idea  3...e4  , which doesn't work yet since after  4.Ng5  Qe7  5.Qc2  , we are losing the e4-pawn. So instead, we develop the other knight to support the pawn. We keep in mind that at some point, we would like to hunt White's knight with ...e4.  3...Nc6   We have another four knights variation on the board. We plan to play ...Bb4 next targetting the knight and getting ready to castle. Only when White plays  4.e4  we reply with  4...Bc5  and target the weak d4-square.  4.g3   We cannot play  4...e4  yet since after  5.Ng5  both knights attack the e4-pawn, and we would lose it. That's why we wait with our ...e4 knight-hunting idea.   4.e3  Bb4  5.Qc2   5.d4  exd4  6.exd4  d5  would transpose to the variation we have seen here in the Albin countergambit. To  5.Nd5  , we can reply with  5...e4  hunting the knight.  5...Bxc3   After  5...O-O  White can play  6.Nd5  attacking the bishop when after  6...Nxd5  7.cxd5  White is attacking our knight and e5-pawn. I rather avoid this by capturing the knight. Also, after  5...O-O  6.Nd5  now the knight hunt with  6...e4  doesn't work since White can win the pawn with  7.Nxf6+  Qxf6  8.Qxe4  .  6.Qxc3  Qe7  We defend the e5-pawn and are ready to castle and play ...d5 next. I like this more than 6...d6 since we prefer to push the pawn to ...d5 directly at a later stage.  7.Be2  O-O  8.O-O  d5   We get our other pawn in the center, and after  9.cxd5  Nxd5  , we are gaining a tempo on the queen. Black as a comfortable position.  4...Bb4  Developing and preparing to castle.  5.Bg2   White fianchettos the bishop, which means that the knight-hunting idea still doesn't work yet since after  5...e4  6.Ng5  Bxc3  7.bxc3  White still has two attackers on the e4-pawn, and we would lose the pawn. That's why we castle and get ready to defend the pawn with ...Re8.  5...O-O  6.O-O  Now we are ready for our master plan and start the knight-hunt.  6...e4  Our signature knight-hunting move. Those who also studied the White course are already familiar with this idea. Generally speaking, White's knight's best places are c3 and f3, and we would like to hunt these knights from their comfortable squared. In the White course, we mercilessly went for the same strategy hunting Black's knights on c6 and f6.  7.Ng5  White has three attacks on the e4-pawn. We should eliminate the knight now.  7...Bxc3  Eliminating one of the attackers.  8.bxc3  Re8  Since the rook can help, we can sufficiently defend the pawn.  9.Qc2  White adds the queen as an attacker so we should defend with the queen as well.  9...Qe7  Since the knight on g5 is misplaced, White has to trade the e4-pawn to ensure the knight can come back to f3. At the 1600-level, most of the White players didn't know how to handle this position properly.  10.d4  One of the most popular moves at the 1600-level.  10...h6   We kick the knight to the edge of the board, forcing it to move for the third time. This is our idea whenever White didn't play d3 or f3 to trade our e4-pawn. After  11.Nh3  Na5  Black already wins the c4-pawn and has a significant advantage. }
3... c6
{ Let's go for the reversed delayed Alapin and get the same ideas as in the White course. The plan is to play ...d5 getting a strong pawn center and getting ready to hunt White's knights. }
4. Bg2 d5
{ We follow up with our Alapin plan and get our two strong pawns in the center. Also, we are ready for ...d4 hunting White's knight. }
5. cxd5
{ In 80% of the games at the 1600-level, White traded these pawns without thinking about it much. This is actually a mistake from White, as it gives us the c6-square for the knight to develop. }
5... cxd5
{ Black has a lovely pawn center and can start the knight-hunting ideas. We will play ...d4 next regardless of what White plays. When White play  6.d4  exd4  7.Qxd4  Nc6  develops with tempo, and after  8.Qd1  d4  kicks the knight from the comfortable c3-square. White is under pressure, and Black already has an advantage.   Even after  6.Qb3  d4  is fine when  7.Bxb7  Bxb7  8.Qxb7  sacrificing a pawn. We reply with  8...Nbd7  and after White's most played moves at the 1600-level  9.Nb5?  Rc8  10.Qxa7  Bc5!  Black has a massive lead in development and a winning position. }
