1. f4
{ 1.b3  e5  2.Bb2  Black attacks the e5-pawn.  2...Nc6  We develop and defend the pawn.  3.e3  d5  We don't hesitate to grab the pawn center. We can develop the bishops anywhere when our pawns are on e5 and d5.  4.Bb5  White pins the knight and threatens to capture the e5-pawn. This was White's idea to get counterplay against the e5-pawn with the fianchetto bishop. But we are prepared.  4...Nge7  We protect our pinned knight and want to recapture it with the other knight.  5.Bxe5   White accepts the challenge and captures the pawn. After  5.Nf3  , we play  5...e4  hunting the knight.  5...a6  We force White to trade the strong bishop and unpin our knight.  6.Bxc6+  Nxc6  We recapture and put pressure on the bishop gaining a tempo.  7.Bb2  Qg5  Attacking the g2-pawn and preparing to the castle queenside. White is under a lot of pressure, and their king is still in the middle.  8.Qf3  White needs to defend the g2-pawn.   After  8.g3  , White's light-squares are weak for the rest of the game, which means we have great attacking changes with the light-squared bishop and queen. We will play  8...Bg4  developing and attacking the queen.  8...Bg4  We develop and attack the queen.  9.Qg3  White pins the bishop and threatens h3.  9...Bd6  We develop with tempo attacking the queen.  10.f4  Qg6   After  11.h3  Qxc2  12.Bxg7  Rg8  13.Qxg4  , we can win back the piece with  13...Bf8  attacking the pinned bishop, and Black has a better position.   1.b4  e5  Our typical reply.  2.Bb2  Bxb4  We agree to trade a b-pawn for the central e-pawn, even though it is a strategic disadvantage. White needs to spend a lot of time to win the e-pawn, so we get a lead in development.  3.Bxe5  Nf6  We develop and prepare to castle. We want to continue with ...O-O ...d5 ...c5 and after we will gain a tempo on the bishop with ...Nc6. We would first like to play ...c5 before we play ...Nc6 to avoid that our c-pawn is stuck behind the knight.   1.g3  e5  We use the rule of thump and put the pawn in the center.  2.Bg2  d5  Black already grabbed the full center. Our plan to play ...Nf6 ...Bd6 to develop, support the center and prepare to castle quickly.   1.e3  e5  We use the rule of thump to play ...e5.  2.d4   White places the d-pawn in the center, we should go for the trade. After  2.b3  d5  3.Bb2  we transpose to the variation we have just seen here.  2...exd4  3.exd4  d5  We are now in the exchange French variation. This is not something to worry about. These pawn structures are already quite familiar to us since we faced them in the Albin Countergambit. After 3.c4 we already transpose to the Albin Countergambit.  4.Nf3  Nf6  We develop and prepare to castle.  5.Nc3  Bb4   Pinning the knight and getting ready to castle. After at the 1600-level frequently played  6.Bd2  O-O  7.a3  Bxc3  8.Bxc3  Re8+  9.Be2  Qe7  we pin the bishop and prevent White from casting. }
1... e5 { We play 1...e5 even though White can capture the pawn. } 2. fxe5 d6
{ We are giving up another pawn to start a big attack. } 3. exd6 Bxd6
{ Threatening mate with ...Qh4+! } 4. Nf3 Nf6
{ We are going to play ...Ng4 and attack! } 5. e3 Ng4
