{ What is the typical idea here? } 6... Nb4
{ We go for the fork threatening ...Nc2+ attacking the king and rook, and White is in trouble. }
7. e4 { White blocks the bishop's diagonal, preventing the fork. } 7... Bxe4
{ By capturing with the bishop, we reinforce the threat of ...Nc2+. } 8. Nxe4
dxe4 { We attack the knight. } 9. Ng5 Qxd4
{ A classy tactical combination. Our queen is indirectly protected because we have the fork. }
10. Qxd4 Nc2+ { Regaining the queen. } 11. Kd1 Nxd4
{ Black has a dominating position. } 12. Nxe4
{ White tries to regain one of the pawns but is still a pawn down. } 12...
O-O-O
{ Castling queenside immediately places our rook in a powerful position. We threaten ...Nb3+ with a discovered check to win the rook. White is in big trouble. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Theme based tactics drills "]
[Black "Exercise 3: Albin Countergambit: Double Attack "]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r3kb1r/ppp3pp/2n2q2/5b2/2Pp4/1N3N2/PP2PPPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 0 9"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ How do we go for a devastating attack? } 9... Nb4
{ Threatening ...Nc2+ forking the king and rook. We don't have to be scared that White can capture the d4-pawn since we are planning to castle queenside creating a powerful pin on the knight. }
10. Nbxd4
{ 10.Nfxd4  O-O-O  is more or less the same. The pin on the knight is deadly, and we threaten ...c5 and ...Nc2+. }
10... O-O-O
{ We threaten ...c5 attacking the pinned knight as well as ...Nc2+ with a deadly fork. Black has a winning position, and the computer already gives -8. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Theme based tactics drills "]
[Black "Exercise 4: Albin Countergambit: Double Attack"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/8/3p4/2PQ4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1B1KBNR b KQkq - 0 4"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ White looks better developed and threatens to win the d5-pawn. How can we go for lightning-fast development and set up a nasty trick? }
4... Nc6
{ Sacrificing the d5-pawn in exchange for lightning-fast development. } 5. Qxd5
Be6 { Developing and attacking the queen. } 6. Qxd8+
{ After  6.Qb5  a6  7.Qxb7  Nd4  we threaten a checkmate and deadly for with ...Nc2+. White can defend with  8.Qe4  Nf6  9.Qd3  Bxc4  10.Qd1  with a balanced fighting position. }
6... Rxd8
{ Black has sufficient compensation for the pawn, White has to be extremely careful now. After the three most popular moves at 1600-level Black gets a winning position. I also won several times in online blitz games with this trick against strong opponents. Our deadly plan is ...Nb4-Nc2+. }
7. e3
{ The most popular move at the 1600-level and Black reaches a winning position. Also, the second and third most popular move at the 1600-level allows the same tactic for Black. White's best move would be  7.Bf4  anticipating our idea to defend with the  Rc1  next move. We reply with  7...Bxc4  regaining the pawn. }
7... Nb4
{ White can't prevent the fork with ...Nc2+, so Black is winning. Also after  8.Ke2  Bxc4+  9.Kf3  Bxf1  Black wins a piece. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Theme based tactics drills "]
[Black "Exercise 5: Sidelines: Double Attack"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqk2r/ppp2ppp/3b4/8/6n1/4PN2/PPPPB1PP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 0 6"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ What trick do we have here? } 6... Bxh2
{ We are threatening ...Bg3+, so White has to capture the bishop. } 7. Rxh2
{ Half of the games at the 1600-level continued with  7.Nxh2  when  7...Qh4+  8.Kf1  Qf2#  is mate. }
7... Nxh2 { Winning the rook. } 8. Nxh2 Qh4+
{ Our tactical justification, forking the king and the knight. } 9. Kf1 Qxh2
{ We are an exchange up and have a winning position. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Theme based tactics drills "]
[Black "Exercise 6: Ruy Lopez: Double Attack "]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqk1nr/1pp2ppp/p1p5/2b1N3/4P3/2N5/PPPP1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 0 6"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Do you see a double attack? } 6... Qg5
{ Double attack on the knight and the g2-pawn.  6...Bxf2  7.Kxf2  Qd4+  is also good to win a pawn back. }
7. d4
{ 7.Nf3  is a popular move at the 1600-level that loses after  7...Qxg2  threatening mate and capturing the rook. }
7... Qxg2 { Grabbing a pawn and worsening White's king safety. } 8. Rf1
{ The most popular move at the 1600-level and a big blunder. We will add another attacker to the rook! White should play  8.Qf3  when after  8...Qxf3  9.Nxf3  Bb4  pinning the knight, the position is balanced. Which bishop is best to move? }
8... Bh3 { Threatens ...Qxf1+, which wins the rook and is a devasting attack. }
9. Qd3 { Do we have to collect the rook already? } 9... Bxd4
{ A lovely move! There was no need to play  9...Qxf1  immediately, which would be worse but also winning. White's rook on f1 is trapped anyway, and next move, we will play ...Qxf1. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Theme based tactics drills "]
[Black "Exercise 7: English Opening: Double Attack"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkb1r/pp1p1ppp/2p2n2/4p3/2P5/2NP1N2/PP2PPPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 4"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ How can we lure White into blundering a knight? } 4... d5
{ We grab the full center. We allow White to capture the e5-pawn since we have a sneaky trap. }
5. Nxe5
{ A big blunder from White. We eventually want to fork the king and knight, so we should first chase away the other knight.  5.cxd5  is the strongest move for White, which has been covered here. }
5... d4 { Going for our plan to win a piece. } 6. Ne4 Qa5+
{ Forking the king and knight to win a piece. Here it would also work if we first trade knights with  6...Nxe4  7.dxe4  and then go for  7...Qa5+  .  In the mainline, it is important to play ...Qa5+ immediately. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Theme based tactics drills "]
[Black "Exercise 8: Scotch: Double Attack "]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b1k2r/ppp2ppp/2p2n2/2b5/4P3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1B1KB1R b KQkq - 0 8"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Black is better developed. How can we make use of the fact that White's pieces are not coordinated yet? }
8... Ng4 9. f3 { How should the knight infiltrate White's position? } 9... Ne3
{ Threatening ...Nxc2+, forking the king and rook.  9...Nf2  doesn't work even though it looks strong, since after  10.Na4  Nxh1  11.Nxc5  Black's knight on h1 will be lost soon, and White has a big advantage. }
10. Bxe3 { The c2-pawn couldn't be defended in a convenient way. } 10... Bxe3
{ Black has a slight advantage. The dark-squared bishop prevents White from castling. We plan to develop the light-squared bishop and can either go for a kingside or queenside castle. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Theme based tactics drills "]
[Black "Exercise 9: Scotch: Double attack"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b1k2r/ppp1nppp/6q1/2bPn3/3N4/1BP1B3/PP3PPP/RN1Q1RK1 b kq - 0 10"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ We already have a lot of pieces directed toward the White's king, how can we add another attacker for the final knock-out blow? }
10... Bh3 { Threatening mate in one with ...Qg2#! } 11. g3
{ How can we take full advantage of our beautiful, light-square bishop? } 11...
Qe4 { Threatening mate! } 12. f3 { White's only defensive idea. } 12... Qxe3+
{ Black wins a piece and still has a powerful attack. The computer already gives -10. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Theme based tactics drills "]
[Black "Exercise 10: English opening: Double Attack + Pin"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqk2r/pppp1ppp/5n2/2b1p3/2P1P3/2N2N2/PP1P1PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 4"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ What tactical idea do we have here? } 4... Ng4
{ It's time to give your opponent a heart attack. We are threatening ...Nxf2 forking the queen and rook. }
5. d4 { White has to block the bishop's diagonal. } 5... exd4
{ We capture the pawn and attack the knight. } 6. Nxd4
{ The most-played move at the 1600-level, however, this is a big mistake. By capturing the d4-pawn, our bishop becomes more powerful, and White allows us a strong sacrifice. The best move for White is  6.Na4  when after  6...Bb4+  7.Bd2  Qe7  Black attacks the e4-pawn and has a slight advantage. }
6... Nxf2
{ We sacrifice on the f2-square, forking the queen and rook. When we sacrifice a piece on the f2-square, we want to have a direct follow-up to regain the material. }
7. Kxf2 Qf6+
{ Double attack on the king and knight. We are forcing the king forward to keep on protecting the knight. }
8. Ke3 Nc6
{ By adding another attacker to the pinned knight, we win back the piece and keep a strong initiative because of the White's weak king. Black has a winning position. After  9.Ncb5  O-O  White's knight keeps on being pinned, and we threaten ...a6 eliminating the defending knight to win the piece. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Theme based tactics drills "]
[Black "Exercise 11: 1.e4 e5 Sidelines: Pin"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqk2r/pppn1ppp/5n2/2bpP1B1/5Q2/2P5/PP3PPP/RN2KBNR b KQkq - 0 7"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ The pinned knight is heavily attacked. What's the most active way to defend? }
7... Qe7
{ Pinning the e5-pawn, so that White can no longer win the knight. Black has a massive lead in development and a huge advantage. After  8.Nf3  , we can play  8...h6  , forcing  9.Bxf6  gxf6  . This attacks the e5-pawn another time, thus winning it. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Theme based tactics drills "]
[Black "Exercise 12: Italian: Pin"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqkb1r/ppp2ppp/2n5/1B2N3/4p3/8/PPPP1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 0 7"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Attack is often the best defense. With that in mind what would you play here? }
7... Qg5 { Attacking and pinning the knight and also attacking the g2-pawn. }
8. Nxc6 { Discovered attacks are dangerous. } 8... Qxb5
{ Discovered attacks are dangerous, so we need to take measures. Black has a winning position. After  9.Nd4  we again attack the g2-pawn with  9...Qg5  . }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Theme based tactics drills "]
[Black "Exercise 13: Ruy Lopez: Pin"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b1kbnr/1pp2ppp/p1p3q1/4p1B1/4P3/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RN1Q1RK1 b kq - 0 7"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Our queen found a nice spot to attack from. How can we develop a piece in an attacking way? }
7... Bh3
{ A spectacular move. White's dark-squared bishop cannot move because of ...Qg2# mate. }
8. gxh3 { What's the best way to win the bishop? } 8... h6
{ Pinning and winning back the bishop. After ...hxg5 also, our rook is activated. Black has an advantage because of White's broken pawn structure in front of the king. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Theme based tactics drills "]
[Black "Exercise 14: Italian: Pin"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqkb1r/p1p2ppp/5n2/1p1Pp1N1/3n4/1BN5/PPPP1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 0 7"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ What piece from White is misplaced and how can we make use of that? } 7... h6
8. Nf3 { Which White piece gives Black the most trouble at this very moment? }
8... Bg4
{ Creating a deadly pin on the knight and Black has a winning position. We plan to trap White's light-squared bishop with a5-a4. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Theme based tactics drills "]
[Black "Exercise 15: Albin Countergambit: Pin + Defense"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b1kbnr/ppp2ppp/2n5/3q4/3P4/5N2/PP3PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 6"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ White is threatening to chase away our queen with Nc3 to subsequently play d5 hunting the knight. How can we react in a precise way? }
6... Bg4 { Pinning the knight and putting more pressure on the d4-pawn. } 7.
Nc3 Bxf3
{ 7...Bb4  to pin the knight would be a sound alternative. I like  7...Bxf3  better as it gives us more attacking changes. }
8. Nxd5
{ White has to capture the queen. After  8.gxf3  Qxd4  Black is a pawn up with a good position. }
8... Bxd1 9. Nxc7+
{ White forks the king and rook. In the end, their knight will be misplaced on a8. }
9... Kd7
{ Getting the king off the back rank allows us the possibility to grab the knight on a8 with the rook one day. }
10. Nxa8 Bh5 { We get our bishop back to safety. } 11. d5
{ White is hunting our knight. Defending with  11.Be3  would be a mistake since we strike with  11...Bb4+  and White is in big trouble. }
11... Nd4
{ The position is very similar to the position in my White Chessable course coming from the Alapin Barmen's defense. Here the game went @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.c3  d5  3.exd5  Qxd5  4.d4  cxd4  5.cxd4  Nc6  6.Nf3  Bg4  7.Nc3  Bxf3  8.Nxd5  Bxd1  9.Nc7+  Kd7  10.Nxa8  Bh5  11.d5  Nd4  There, I recommend  12.Bf4  a brilliant rook sacrifice when after  12...Nc2+?  13.Kd2  Nxa1  14.Bb5+  Kd8  15.Bc7+  White has a devastating attack and winning position.  The only difference with the position here is that we don't have the e7-pawn, which benefits us as our dark-squared bishop can develop. Luckily there is no need to worry about such tricks from White here when White plays   @@StartFEN@@N4bnr/pp1k1ppp/8/3P3b/3n4/8/PP3PPP/R1B1KB1R w KQ - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Bf4?  now than  12...Bb4+  13.Bd2  Nc2#  is a brilliant mate to finish the game. White's only good move is, therefore,   @@StartFEN@@N4bnr/pp1k1ppp/8/3P3b/3n4/8/PP3PPP/R1B1KB1R w KQ - 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12.Bd3  defending against the fork when we play  12...Bg6  to trade the defending bishop and reinforce the threat of the fork with ...Nc2+. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Theme based tactics drills "]
[Black "Exercise 16: 1.e4 e5 Sidelines: X-ray"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/8/3pP3/3Qn3/2P2N2/PP3PPP/RNB1KB1R b KQkq - 0 6"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ What are White's vulnerabilities? } 6... Bc5
{ Attacking the queen and increasing the pressure on the f2-pawn. } 7. Qa4+ Bd7
{ Blocking the check with tempo, attacking the queen. We can take the f2-pawn next move. Black has a winning position. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Theme based tactics drills "]
[Black "Exercise 17: Ruy Lopez: Mate "]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2qkbnr/1pp2pp1/p1p5/4p2p/4P1P1/5N2/PPPP1PP1/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 0 7"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ We just sacrificed a piece and want to start attacking the White king. How do we do that? }
7... hxg4 8. Nxe5
{ The most popular move at the 1600-level, and we already have a forced checkmate. White's best try is to give the piece back with for example  8.d3  gxf3  . The rook is great on the open h-file. How can we make use of it? }
8... Qh4 { Threatening ...Qh1# mate. } 9. f3
{ White tries to create an escape square for the king, we will stop their plan. How can we prevent the White king from fleeing? }
9... g3
{ Taking away White's escape square and ...Qh1# is mate on the next move. We shouldn't let the king escape by playing  9...Qh1+  10.Kf2  . }
10. Re1 Qh1# { Mate! } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Theme based tactics drills "]
[Black "Exercise 18: 1.e4 e5 Sidelines: Mate"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/p1p2ppp/2p5/2bpP3/5Pn1/2NB4/PPP3PP/R1BQ1R1K b - - 0 11"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ The bishop and knight are very active and can work together to win the exchange. Should we go for that or do we have a stronger idea? }
11... Qh4
{ 11...Nf2+  is also quite good, winning the exchange. But mate is better! }
12. h3 Qg3 { 12...Nf2+  only wins the exchange. } 13. hxg4
{ White could also play  13.Qxg4  to prevent mate when after  13...Bxg4  Black wins the queen. }
13... Qh4# { Mate! } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Theme based tactics drills "]
[Black "Exercise 19: Italian: Mate"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2k1b1r/pbp2ppp/8/1B1np1q1/3P4/3P4/PP3PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b - - 0 11"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ White is attacking our queen! How should we react? } 11... Nf4
{ Threatening ...Qg2# mate and even after  12.Bxf4  Qxg2  is mate. } 12. g3
{ White's other defensive move doesn't help either. } 12... Nh3#
{ A fantastic mate to finish the game! } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Theme based tactics drills "]
[Black "Exercise 20: Albin Countergambit: Mate"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r2qk2r/1pp2ppp/8/pPb1n3/2PP2b1/P7/1B1Q1PPP/RN2KB1R b KQkq - 0 12"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ White has a double attack on the bishop and knight. How will we counterattack? }
12... Qh4
{ Black's next move is castling queenside, and if White prevents that by taking either the knight or the bishop, we play ...Rd8 with a devastating effect. }
13. dxe5
{ A better move for White would be  13.dxc5  when Black still keep a strong intiative and advantage as explained here. }
13... Rd8
{ We bring the rook to the d-file with a deadly effect. After  14.g3  Rxd2  15.gxh4  Rd1#  it's mate. }
14. Qc2 Rd1+
{ 14...Qxf2  15.Qxf2  Rd1  might be an even nicer way to finish the game! } 15.
Qxd1 Qxf2# { A fantastic checkmate. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Theme based tactics drills "]
[Black "Exercise 21: Scotch: Mate"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b1k2r/ppppnppp/2N2q2/2b5/4P3/2P1B3/PP3PPP/RN1QKB1R b KQkq - 0 7"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Should we capture the bishop or the knight? } 7... Bxe3
{ Threatening mate and destroying White's pawn structure. } 8. Nxe7
{ White tries to win a piece but we don't recapture it. White should have recaptured with  8.fxe3  when after  8...dxc6  Black has a significant advantage because of the better pawn structure and active queen. }
8... Qxf2# { Mate! } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Theme based tactics drills "]
[Black "Exercise 22: Italian: Mate"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqkb1r/p1p2ppp/2P2n2/4p1N1/2p5/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 b kq - 0 7"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ What typical motif do we have here? } 7... h6 8. Nf3 e4 9. Ne5 Bd6
{ We keep on hunting White's knight and kindly invite them to capture the c4-pawn. }
10. Nxc4
{ And now it's time to show White they cannot just move their knight all the time. }
10... Bxh2+ { A brilliant bishop sacrifice also known as the Greek gift. } 11.
Kxh2 Ng4+
{ When the king goes back with  12.Kg1  we play  12...Qh4  threatening checkmate with ...Qh2#.   Also  12.Kh3  is not a good idea for White when  12...Nxf2+  wins the queen with a discovered check.   That's why White's best defensive try is  12.Kg3  , we destroy him with  12...h5  followed by ...h4+. This chases the king to the h3-square when we have the same discovered check motif to win the queen. }
12. Kg1 Qh4 { Deadly mating threat! } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Theme based tactics drills "]
[Black "Exercise 23: Ruy Lopez: Removing the Defender"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r3kbnr/1pp2ppp/p1p2q2/4p1B1/4P1b1/3P1N2/PPP2PPP/RN1Q1RK1 b kq - 0 7"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ The queen is under attack! What to do about it? } 7... Bxf3
{ We eliminate the defender of the bishop and also attack the queen. } 8. Bxf6
Bxd1 { Black's a piece up. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Theme based tactics drills "]
[Black "Exercise 24: 1.e4 e5 Sidelines: Removing the Defender"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/ppp2p1p/8/3pP1p1/3P1p2/5N2/PPP3PP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 5"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Although Black hasn't developed any pieces yet, there are already attacking possibilities. How should we attack? }
5... g4
{ Black is already winning. The best and most played move is  6.Bxf4  , after which we win the knight with  6...gxf3  . After  7.Qxf3  , we can move out of White's attack by castling queenside with, for example,  7...Be6  8.Bd3  Nc6  9.c3  Qd7  10.O-O  O-O-O  . }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Theme based tactics drills "]
[Black "Exercise 25: Italian: Removing the Defender"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1b1kb1r/p1p2ppp/2n2n2/1B1qp1N1/8/2N5/PPPP1PPP/R1BQK2R b KQkq - 0 7"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ What should we do with our queen? } 7... Qxg2
{ We capture and attack the rook! } 8. Bxc6+ Qxc6
{ We are still threatening to capture the rook. } 9. Rg1 Bg4
{ Attacking the queen! } 10. Rxg4
{ We have a lovely tactic to win the rook without trading it for our knight.  10.f3  Would weaken White's position, and we can attack the rook with  10...Bc5  . }
10... Qh1+
{ Planning to trade queens to subsequently win the entire rook!  10...Nxg4  would be a mistake since White can recapture the knight with  11.Qxg4  . }
11. Ke2 Qxd1+ 12. Nxd1 Nxg4 { Black has a winning endgame. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Theme based tactics drills "]
[Black "Exercise 26: Scotch: Removing the Defender + Pin"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r3k1nr/ppp2ppp/2p1bq2/2b5/4P3/2N1B3/PPP1QPPP/R3KB1R b KQkq - 0 8"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ Our bishop is under attack. How should we handle this? } 8... Ba3
{ A lovely idea! Black is winning after  9.bxa3  since  9...Qxc3  forks the king and the rook. }
9. O-O-O
{ The most-played move for White at the 1600-level and a big mistake.  9.Rb1  doesn't work either since after  9...Bxb2  10.Rxb2  Qxc3+  forks the king and the rook. }
9... Qxc3
{ White cannot capture our queen since we are pinning the b2-pawn. After  10.bxa3  Qxa3+  Black has a devastating attack and a winning position. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Theme based tactics drills "]
[Black "Exercise 27: Albin Countergambit: Intermediate Moves"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqk1nr/ppp2ppp/2n5/4P3/1BP5/4pN2/PP3PPP/RN1QKB1R b KQkq - 0 7"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ How can we reach a significant advantage here? } 7... exf2+
{ A powerful intermediate check! White cannot recapture since this would lose the queen. }
8. Ke2 { The White king needs to keep touching his majesty. } 8... Qxd1+
{ We trade the queens before we recapture the bishop. } 9. Kxd1 Nxb4
{ Black has a significant advantage and easy development. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Theme based tactics drills "]
[Black "Exercise 28: 1.e4 e5 Sidelines: Intermediate Moves"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqkb1r/ppp2ppp/2n5/3pP3/4N3/5Q2/PPPP2PP/R1B1KBNR b KQkq - 0 6"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ We don't need to take the knight immediately if we can create a bigger threat first. How can we do that? }
6... Nd4 { Attacking the queen and the c2-pawn. } 7. Qd3 dxe4
{ We capture the knight and attack the queen. } 8. Qxe4
{ What's the most aggressive developing move? } 8... Bf5
{ We attack the queen, and when she moves, ...Nxc2+ is coming with a fork on the king and rook. }
9. Qxb7 { Does White threaten Bb5+, which we have to prevent? } 9... Rb8
{ Cashing in the rook with  9...Nxc2+  10.Kd1  Nxa1  gives an unexpected chance for White with  11.Bb5+  and after  11...Bd7  12.Bxd7+  Kxd7  White can give perpetual checks starting with  13.Qd5+  . }
10. Qxa7 { How to win material? } 10... Nxc2+ 11. Kd1 Nxa1
{ Black is a rook up and White has no dangerous checks. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Theme based tactics drills "]
[Black "Exercise 29: Albin Countergambit: Intermediate Moves"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqkb1r/ppp2ppp/2n3n1/4P3/1PPp4/P4N2/1B2PPPP/RN1QKB1R b KQkq - 0 7"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ White played great so far and threatens to win the d4-pawn. How do we turn the tables? }
7... a5
{ A cunning move! Before we capture the e5-pawn, we provoke White to play b5. It gives us the possibility to develop our with ...Bc5 later. }
8. b5 { White attacks the knight. } 8... Ncxe5
{ We regain the pawn and also attack the c4-pawn! Please note that we are threatening to capture the pawn without any trouble in this case. In earlier variations, when White's pawn was still on b2 instead of b5 ...Nxc4 wouldn't be a threat since White can fork the king and knight with Qa4+. }
9. Nxe5 Nxe5 10. e3
{ A cunning move from White, increasing the pressure on the pinned d4-pawn and opening the diagonal for the light-squared bishop to protect the c4-pawn. After  10.Bxd4  Nxc4   Or after  10.Qxd4  Qxd4  11.Bxd4  Nxc4  , we gain the pawn back, and Black has no troubles. }
10... Bc5
{ A crazy and brilliant move. White's king is still stuck in the middle, and that's why we want to provoke White to capture on d4 with the pawn forking our knight and bishop. }
11. exd4
{ White captures the d4-pawn forking the knight and bishop. Surely, your opponent will think they have a winning position now; however, in reality, White is in big danger. White's strongest move is  11.Bxd4  which has been covered here. }
11... Bg4
{ Ignoring White's threats and developing the bishop with tempo, attacking the queen. }
12. f3
{ White attacks the other bishop as well, we ignore all the hanging pieces and are going after the king. }
12... Qh4+ { Check! } 13. g3
{ The most logical move from White, also attacking our queen. It seems like we left all the pieces hanging for no reason. Even though White's moves look cunning, they made three significant mistakes in a row, and we reach a winning position. Let's destroy White with a devastating attack. }
13... Nxf3+
{ We continue attacking the king and capture the pawn with a check. } 14. Qxf3
{ White is fine giving up the queen in case they can capture our queen. Luckily we don't have to cooperate with that plan. Also, after  14.Kf2  Qf6  15.dxc5  Nd4+  16.Kg1  Bxd1  Black is a queen up. }
14... Qe7+
{ A brilliant intermediate move, safeguarding our queen and ensuring we will win White's queen on the next move. We shouldn't capture the queen on the previous move with  14...Bxf3?  Because in the end, we lose the bishop:  15.gxh4  Bxh1  16.dxc5  , and we are down in material. }
*

