[White "8) Theme based tactics drills "]
[Black "Exercise 41: English Opening: Knight-Hunt"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/pppp1ppp/2n2n2/4p3/1bP5/2N2NP1/PP1PPPBP/R1BQ1RK1 b - - 0 6"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ What idea do we have to put White under pressure? } 6... e4
{ Our signature knight-hunting move. Those who also studied the White course are already familiar with this idea. Generally speaking, White's knight's best places are c3 and f3, and we would like to hunt these knights from their comfortable squared. In the White course, we mercilessly went for the same strategy hunting Black's knights on c6 and f6. }
7. Ng5
{ White has three attackers on the e4-pawn. We should eliminate the knight now. }
7... Bxc3 { Eliminating one of the attackers. } 8. bxc3 Re8
{ Since the rook can help, we can sufficiently defend the pawn. } 9. Qc2
{ White adds the queen as an attacker so we should defend with the queen as well. }
9... Qe7
{ Since the knight on g5 is misplaced, White has to trade the e4-pawn to ensure the knight can come back to f3. At the 1600-level, most of the White players didn't know how to handle this position properly. }
10. d4 { One of the most popular moves at the 1600-level. } 10... h6
{ We kick the knight to the edge of the board, forcing it to move for the third time. This is our idea whenever White didn't play d3 or f3 to trade our e4-pawn.   After  11.Nh3  Na5  Black already wins the c4-pawn and has a significant advantage. }
*

